{"title_page": "Laulasi Island", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name          = Laulasi Island\n|image_name    = Solomon Islands- Langa Langa Lagoon.png\n|image_caption = Current map of Langa Langa lagoon, Malaita Solomon Islands\n|image_size    = 240px\n|locator_map   = \n|native_name   = Akwalaafu\n|native_name_link = \n|location      = Pacific Ocean\n|coordinates   = {{Coord|8|52|43.22|S|160|44|46.55|E |region:SB_type:isle |display=inline,title}}\n|archipelago   = [[Solomon Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_m2       = 100\n|area_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|length_m      = 100\n|length_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|width_m       = 100\n|width_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m   =\n|country       = Solomon Islands\n|country_admin_divisions_title = Province\n|country_admin_divisions = [[Malaita Province]]\n|country_largest_city = [[Honiara]]\n|country_largest_city_population = 54,600 (2003 est.)\n|population    = 20\n|population_as_of = 2008\n|density_km2   = 2.2\n|density_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|ethnic_groups = [[Melanesia]]n 100%\n}}\n'''Laulasi island''' is an artificial island in the [[Langa Langa Lagoon]], South of [[Auki]] on the island of [[Malaita]] in the [[Solomon Islands]]. It is believed that hostilities among the inlanders of Malaita forced some people into the lagoon where over time they built their islands on sandbars after diving for coral. The religion of the island was based on prayers and offerings to the ghosts of dead ancestors, mediated by priests who kept their skulls and relics in tabu houses. Some ancestors were incarnated as sharks which protected their descendants. Langalanga is also the main source of the [[shell money]] now made in Solomon Islands.\n\n==History==\n\nIn Malaita legend, the first settlement on the island began around 3,000 BC at a place called Siale. The first places in the Malaita area to be settled were ''Dukwasi'' (Kwara'ae speaking people), and the ''Asi'' (man-made islands) namely: Aoke, Kaloka and Rarata in Langa Langa lagoon, Laulasi, Alite Koalia and Gwa'ata&nbsp;\u2013 Ta'alulolo.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIt is also believed the early settlers originated from Mt. Kolovrat (Alasa'a), the highest peak on the main Malaita Island. The early settlers were believed to be castaways from the Alasa'a community. Some said they chose not to return to Alasa\u00b4a because of the distance. It is an approximately two days walk. And the main reason why they came is to fish and in search for other sea foods in the island of Launasi meaning \u00b4\u00b4I'm stuck\u00b4\u00b4now known as Laulasi. From then they named the island Launasi in relation to the expression.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nAfter they had settled, other people began to arrive from different parts of Malaita and outside to settle in the Langalanga lagoon. They came from Small Malaita, Florida (Ngella), some came from the northern part of Guadalcanal believed to be from Longuvalasi area and others from the northern region of Malaita. Through inter-marriages, their descendants spread to the whole of the Langalanga lagoon. Certain cultural features or ''Tambu House'' (Place of the first settlements) are still preserved which attest to the settlement patterns that were made.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:LaulasiIslandSolomonISlandsPart1video.webm|thumb|150px |Part 1 Documentary Video]]\n[[File:LaulasiIslandPart2higher.webm|thumb|150px |Part 2 Documentary Video]]\n\n==1800 to 1900==\n\nIn 1892 the [[Queensland]] government Australia abandoned the Pacific labour trade known as [[Blackbirding]] and in 1901 the Commonwealth of Australia enacted the [[Pacific Island Labourers Act 1901]] which facilitated the deportation of Pacific Islanders that was the precursor to the [[White Australia policy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nBritain was provided with a \"plausible excuse for protecting the Solomons\" and so protecting their labour reserves. By declaring a protectorate, the British were able to justify keeping out other colonial powers.<ref name=\"wealth\">{{cite book |title=Wealth of the Solomons: A History of a Pacific Archipelago, 1800\u20131978 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CP8HlIuTaF8C |author=Judith A. Bennett|isbn=978-0-8248-1078-8 |id={{ISBN|0-8248-1078-3}}|year=1987 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press}}</ref>\n\nIn 1893 then Gibson of [[HMS Curacoa|HMS Curacoa (1854)]] sailed around the islands to declare a protectorate with the only opposition by the Laulasi villages who refused the British flag. When Gibson asked why the flag was refused, the villages were afraid that their acceptance of it would signify to the bush people that by aligning themselves with Britain the lagoon dwellers were preparing for war and this would lead the bush people discontinuing trade with the lagoon people, who had no gardens and were dependent on food.<ref name=\"wealth\"/>\n\n==1911 \u2013 Author Jack London==\n\nAmerican author [[Jack London]] travelled to Langa Langa in a yacht in 1908.<ref name=\"JL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huntington.org/WebAssets/Templates/content.aspx?id=10902|title=Jack London: Chronology |accessdate=22 March 2014 |publisher=The Huntington |date=}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"We ran down the lagoon from Langa Langa, between mangrove swamps through passages scaresly wider than the Monota, and passed the reef villages of Kaloka and Auki. Like the founders of Venice, these salt water men were originally refugees form the mainland. Too weak to hold their own in the bush, survivors of village massacres, they fled to the sand banks of the lagoon. These sand banks they built up into islands and they were compelled to seek their provender from the sea. They developed canoo bodies, unable to walk about, spending all their time in the canoos, they became thick armed and broad shouldered with narrow waists and frail legs\" (p 138)<ref>{{cite book |title=Cruise of the Snark  |url=https://archive.org/details/cruisesnark00londgoog|author=[[Jack london]]|year=1911 |publisher=Harvard University Digitized 19 Jan 2006}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"I sailed in the teak-built ketch, the Minota, on a blackbirding cruise to Malaita, and I took my wife along. The hatchet-marks were still raw on the door of our tiny stateroom advertising an event of a few months before. The event was the taking of Captain Mackenzie's head, Captain Mackenzie, at that time, being master of the Minota.... As we sailed in to Langa-Langa on the shore side of the lagoon, was [[Binu]], the place where the Minota was captured a year previously and her captain killed by the bushmen of Malaita, having been hacked to pieces and eaten\" (p 135)<ref>https://archive.org/details/logofsnark00londrich Log of the Stark</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"He(Mackenzie) believed in kindness. He also contended that better confidence was established by carrying no weapons. On his second trip to Malaita, recruiting,he ran into Bina, which is near Langa Langa. The rifles with which the boat's-crew should have been armed, were locked up in his cabin. When the whale-boat went ashore after recruits, he paraded around the deck without even a revolver on him. He was tomahawked. His head remains in Malaita. It was suicide.<ref>http://www.readprint.com/chapter-6916/Jack-London ''Adventure'' \u2013 by Jack London (1911)</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Log of the Snark states:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"..still bore the tomahawk marks where the Malaitans at Langa Langa several months before broke in for the trove of rifles and ammunition locked therein, after bloodily slaughtering Jansen's predecessor, Captain Mackenzie. The burning of the vessel was somehow prevented by the black crew, but this was so unprecedented that the owner feared some complicity between them and the attacking party. However, it could not be proved, and we sailed with the majority of this same crew. The present skipper smilingly warned us that the same tribe still required two more heads from the Minota, to square up for deaths on the Ysabel plantation. (p 387)<ref>https://archive.org/stream/logofsnark00londrich/logofsnark00londrich_djvu.txt The Log of the Stark</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Three fruitless days were spent at Su'u. The Minota got no recruits from the bush and the bushmen got no heads from the Minota. We towed out with a whaleboat and ran along the coast to Langa Langa, a large village of salt-water people built with labour on a sand bank&nbsp;\u2013 literally built up\"<ref name=\"Tales of Adventure\">{{cite book |title=Tales of Adventure |url=https://archive.org/details/talesofadventur000lond |url-access=registration |quote=Langa Langa. |author=Jack London|year=1956 |publisher=Hanover House, University of Michigan}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==World War II==\n\nOn the morning of 7 August 1942 (same date as the [[Guadalcanal Campaign|US Landings on Guadacanal]]),\n\n<blockquote>\n\"..seven US planes bombed the island. The reason was due to an error namely that the Americans mistook Laulasi for the Japanese camp at Afufu in North Malaita. Which resulted in the killing 24 children, destroying the shell money industry and the incident still remains the subject of an unresolved compensation claim\".<ref name=\"Iume\">{{cite book |title=Ples Blong iume: Solomon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0MAyfyJY05QC |author=Sam Alasia & 13 others, Hugh Laracy|isbn= 978-982-02-0027-2 |year=2006 |publisher=University South Pacific}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe British resident commissioner wrote in his diary:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"7 US planes bombed Laulasi village&nbsp;\u2013 18 killed&nbsp;\u2013 most inexplicable as no enemy repeorted there\"(Marchant 7 Aug 1942)<ref name=\"bombing\">{{cite book |title=The Pacific Theatre: Island Representations of World War II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ONQf-Qui0UC |author1=Geoffrey Miles White |author2=Lamont Lindstrom |isbn= 978-0-8248-1146-4 |year=1989 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The bombing of Laulasi island was the worst loss of civilian lives in the entire Solomon Islands conflict\".<ref name=\"landmark\">{{cite book |title=Guadalcanal: The Definitive Account of the Landmark Battle |url=https://archive.org/details/guadalcanal00rich |url-access=registration |quote=Laulasi. |author=Richard B. Frank|isbn= 978-0-14-016561-6 |year=1992 |publisher=Penguin Books}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Cultural Practices and Beliefs==\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The LangaLanga and Kwara'ae people more or less have the same cultural and traditional practices and follow the same chiefly system. Male children for example are more valued than females because they will continue with the line or tribe. Girls are not so preferred because they leave the community when they get married. Boys are separated from their parents when they are around 12 or 13 years old to live separate in the men's houses. Around that age, they are taught by the fathers basic important skills such as fishing, building houses, making canoes or cutting and sewing sago palm leaves\".\n\n\"Girls on the other hand, they stay with their mother and taught household cores such as cooking, weeding around the house, cleaning and looking after their younger brothers of sisters. One of the important things that girls learn at an early age too is how to make shell money\".\n\n</blockquote>\n[[File:Warriorwelcome.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Tribal warriors challenging the visitors. Taken 2008]]\nHistorically, chiefs in the Langalanga lagoon are looked upon as very important in uniting communities. Normally, chiefs are chosen from chiefly tribes or clan. Villages in the past used to have threes chiefs, Fa'atabu who makes offering and communicated with the spirits and ancestors, the Ramo is responsible for tribal warfare and Waenotolo is the chief responsible for controlling, organising, leadership and uniting the whole community.\n\nPriests in Laulasi live in \"spirit houses,\" and when they die, their bodies are taken to the nearby village of Alite to decompose, after which the skulls are brought back and placed in a \"house of skulls.\"<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite book |title=Moon Handbooks South Pacific |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_EDGapfBX-CAC |pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_EDGapfBX-CAC/page/n1025 1006]|author=David Stanley|isbn= 978-1-56691-411-6 |year=2004 |publisher=David Stanley}}</ref>\n\nOn the side of the island is an inlet where custom priests calls the sharks to come to the surface. The sharks are re-incarnation of the people's ancestors who died many years before. They also offer sacrifices to the sharks in the form of pigs. Ordinary men are not allowed to visit the shark site unless invited by the custom priest.<ref name=\"Moon\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2008}}\n\nAccording to local legend, a fisherman whose boat capsizes at sea may call on a shark to rescue him; after being rescued and returned to shore, he must sacrifice a pig, or else the shark will eat him next time he goes out to sea.<ref name=\"Iume\"/><ref name=\"Moon\"/>\n\nBy the 1960s many of the LangaLanga villages were Christian. Many of the communities previously sited on the artificial islands had been shifted to the mainland, with encouragement from the missionaries anxious to promote a clean break with the pagan past, and inducement in the form of greater access to land for subsistence farming.<ref name=\"ANU\">{{cite book |title=Melanesia: Beyond Diversity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8gpzAAAAMAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Ronald James May, Hank Nelson, Australian National University Research School of Pacific Studies|isbn= 978-0-86784-045-2 |year=1982 |publisher=Research School of Pacific Studies, The Australian National University}}</ref>\n\n==Last Pagan priest==\n\nIn 1980, Moses Beogo who was the last Pagan priest (Fata'abu) on Laulasi and the last to perform the shark calling tradition, died. His skull is kept with the skulls of the other priests.<ref name=\"Iume\"/>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Laulasiapartment1.jpg|right|thumb|150px|An \"apartment\" to store Priest Heads of another tribe. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:Laulasiapartment.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Another \"apartment\" to store Priest Heads of one tribe. Taken 2008]]\n\nA report on the British Solomon Islands dated 1972 states:\n<blockquote>\n\"where the traditional process of making shell money and other island activities may be observed, once again proved popular with the tourists\".<ref name=\"report72\">{{cite book |title=British Solomon Islands: Report |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YTmYZfvEOMMC&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Great Britain Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Colonial Office|year=1972 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Off}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1981 a symposium in the then U.S.S.R heard of Solomon Islands that:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"One of the more successful ventures in the tourist industry is Laulasi Adventure Tours Ltd\"<ref name=\"symposium\">{{cite book |title=Persistence and Exchange: Papers from a Symposium on Ecological Problems of the Traditional Societies of the Pacific Region : XIV Pacific Science Congress, Khabarovsk, U.S.S.R., August\u2014September, 1979 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BzuxAAAAIAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Roland W. Force, Brenda Bishop, Pacific Science Association|isbn= 978-0-9604480-2-9 |year=1981 |publisher=Pacific Science Association}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1982 a research paper by the [[Australian National University]] claimed:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Laulasi has become one of the notable tourist attractions of the South Pacific&nbsp;\u2013 with all the predictable consequences for the integrity of the ancestoral religion and the fabric of community social life. Moreover, the expatriate entrepreneurs were Baha'is, and offered a ready-made religious accommodation between ancestors and capitalism\".<ref name=\"ANU\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1997 an author stated:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Laulasi village, at the centre of the lagoon, makes a business of being nice to visitors. A real business, because it charges more than a Disneyland ticket to tread its man made shores\".<ref name=\"Romancing\">{{cite book |title=Romancing the Islands: Journeys in the South Pacific |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q1N0AAAAMAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Kim Gravelle|isbn= 978-982-214002-6 |year=1997 |publisher=Graphics (Pacific) Ltd}}<!--Check ISBN Hyphenation--></ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 2006 [[The Last Heathen]] by Charles Montgomery concludes that for this he was expecting to find a volatile mixture of the tribal, pagan religion and Christianity. He found a comfortable hybrid instead, the two religions living in harmony.<ref name=\"Last Heathen\">{{cite book |title=The Last Heathen: Encounters with Ghosts and Ancestors in Melanesia ([[Shark God]])|author=Charles Montgomery|year=2004 |publisher=HarperCollins}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008 on an invitation from the Laulasi community a delegation from [[RAMSI]] was invited to attend to officiate the \"re-opening\" of the Laulasi Tourist Industry. Members took footage and photographs with a view of assisting with publicity. The delegation was escorted to the dock with a traditional war canoe trailing and a 10-seat war canoe leading with the latter being Laulasi women singing a traditional welcome song.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nOn arrival at the dock, warriors confronted the delegation until a sum of shell money was presented to the warriors as a sign of peace. Once this gift was received the village girls offered the delegation refreshments.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe men of the delegation were permitted to tour the three \"apartments\" that each represented a tribe. In each apartment, the skulls of past priests were laid atop one another. Once this tour concluded, the delegation was presented with a display of song and dance and formalities and a demonstration of the minting process of the shell money. The village women then sang as the delegation sailed away.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Boatbuilding==\n\nThe Annual Report on the British Solomon Islands dated 1953 states\n<blockquote>\n\"..a flourishing boat building industry has been established and cutters are being built for the inter-island trade. A boatbuilding school has been established.<ref name=\"report53\">{{cite book |title=Annual Report on the British Solomon Islands |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-VaB7cg3wsC&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Great Britain Colonial Office|year=1953 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Off}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney.jpg|left|thumb|150px|The shell money minting production line. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney2.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Cutting the shell with a sharp stone. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney3.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Drilling the hole with a traditional drill. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney1.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Beading the shells for the finished product. Taken 2008]]\nGenerally, the Lanagalanga people are very skilful boat builders. It can be said that it is unique to the constituency. In the early stages people used to build dingies. Later, with improvements in skills, they built what they referred to as 'CARTER BOATS' which is sharp at both ends. They used sails to travel around Malaita and to other Islands such as Gudalcanal and Isabel. Commercial boat building in the constituency started in the 1960s around the time when the Government established a boat building school in Auki. Mr. Frank Faulker who used to teach at the school and who now settled in Auki, is said to be the main person behind the success of the industry in Langalanga.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Shell Money==\n\nThe history of shell-money making in the langa langa lagoon is patchy. Stories retold from myths said that the first person to introduce shell money to the Langalanga lagoon was a woman from [[Buin, Papua New Guinea|Buin]] in Bougainville. She was banish and floated in a coconut shell from Buin to Guadalcanal and finally to Malaita and landed at Tafilo a village at Lalana near Laulasi. Traditionally, there had been substantive trade between the Langalanga people and people from Buin in shell money until the emergence of the Bougainville crises. Most of the private ship owners from the constituency generated capital through shell money trade to build their ships. They took shell money to Buin and traded it for cash and used the cash to build wooden boats.<ref name=\"Economic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/1613811/_Making_Money_Objects_Productions_and_Performances_of_Shell_Money_Manufacture_in_Langalanga_Solomon_Islands  |title=\"Making Money\": Objects, Productions, and Performances of Shell Money Manufacture in Langalanga, Solomon Island|author=Pei-yi Guo|accessdate=22 March 2014 |publisher=The Frontiers of Southeast Asia and Pacific Studies |date=1 January 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs the production rate increased, shell resources were depleted, particularly in Langalanga lagoon. Even in the 1970s some types of shell were rare.\n\nFour different types of shell are used in making shell money, A red lipped rock oyster called Romu (chama pacifica), white shell known as Kee (Beguina semi-orbiculata), black horse mussel shells called Kurila (Atrina vexillum) and thick white disks from a rigid cockle known as Kakadu (Anadara granosa)<ref name=\"sustainability\">{{cite book |title=Pacific Voices: Equity and Sustainability in Pacific Island Fisheries|author=Iren\u00e9 Novaczek, Jean Mitchell, Joeli Vietayaki, University of the South Pacific, Institute of Pacific Studies|isbn= 978-982-020372-3 |year=2005 |publisher=University of the South Pacific}}<!--Check ISBN Hyphenation--></ref>\n\nWhat makes this money valuable are the purple disks, whose number per string is carefully calculated and which are made from the lips of the Romu shell which the Langa Langa people collect twice a year from the lagoon areas of the clan of the Lau tribe. The chief of the Lau clan allows them to fish for the shells in exchange for half the money strings.<ref name=\"gift\">{{cite book |title=The Enigma of the Gift|author1=Maurice Godelier |author2=Nora Scott |isbn= 978-0-226-30045-0 |year=1999 |publisher=University of the Chicago Press}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Bartholomew Ulufa'alu]] (25 December 1950&nbsp;\u2013 25 May 2007) was the Prime Minister of the Solomon Islands from 27 August 1997 to 30 June 2000.\n\n==See also==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tSX7FXmhBlc Youtube video of Laulasi Island]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Islands of the Solomon Islands}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Anthropology]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:History of the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Exploration of Asia]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name          = Laulasi Island\n|image_name    = Solomon Islands- Langa Langa Lagoon.png\n|image_caption = Current map of Langa Langa lagoon, Malaita Solomon Islands\n|image_size    = 240px\n|locator_map   = \n|native_name   = Akwalaafu\n|native_name_link = \n|location      = Pacific Ocean\n|coordinates   = {{Coord|8|52|43.22|S|160|44|46.55|E |region:SB_type:isle |display=inline,title}}\n|archipelago   = [[Solomon Islands]]\n|total_islands = \n|major_islands = \n|area_m2       = 100\n|area_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|length_m      = 100\n|length_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|width_m       = 100\n|width_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|highest_mount = \n|elevation_m   =\n|country       = Solomon Islands\n|country_admin_divisions_title = Province\n|country_admin_divisions = [[Malaita Province]]\n|country_largest_city = [[Honiara]]\n|country_largest_city_population = 54,600 (2003 est.)\n|population    = 20\n|population_as_of = 2008\n|density_km2   = 2.2\n|density_footnotes = {{Citation needed|date=June 2010}}\n|ethnic_groups = [[Melanesia]]n 100%\n}}\n'''Laulasi island''' is an artificial island in the [[Langa Langa Lagoon]], South of [[Auki]] on the island of [[Malaita]] in the [[Solomon Islands]]. It is believed that hostilities among the inlanders of Malaita forced some people into the lagoon where over time they built their islands on sandbars after diving for coral. The religion of the island was based on prayers and offerings to the ghosts of dead ancestors, mediated by priests who kept their skulls and relics in tabu houses. Some ancestors were incarnated as sharks which protected their descendants. Langalanga is also the main source of the [[shell money]] now made in Solomon Islands.\n\n==History==\n\nIn Malaita legend, the first settlement on the island began around 3,000 BC at a place called Siale. The first places in the Malaita area to be settled were ''Dukwasi'' (Kwara'ae speaking people), and the ''Asi'' (man-made islands) namely: Aoke, Kaloka and Rarata in Langa Langa lagoon, Laulasi, Alite Koalia and Gwa'ata&nbsp;\u2013 Ta'alulolo.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIt is also believed the early settlers originated from Mt. Kolovrat (Alasa'a), the highest peak on the main Malaita Island. The early settlers were believed to be castaways from the Alasa'a community. Some said they chose not to return to Alasa\u00b4a because of the distance. It is an approximately two days walk. And the main reason why they came is to fish and in search for other sea foods in the island of Launasi meaning \u00b4\u00b4I'm stuck\u00b4\u00b4now known as Laulasi. From then they named the island Launasi in relation to the expression.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nAfter they had settled, other people began to arrive from different parts of Malaita and outside to settle in the Langalanga lagoon. They came from Small Malaita, Florida (Ngella), some came from the northern part of Guadalcanal believed to be from Longuvalasi area and others from the northern region of Malaita. Through inter-marriages, their descendants spread to the whole of the Langalanga lagoon. Certain cultural features or ''Tambu House'' (Place of the first settlements) are still preserved which attest to the settlement patterns that were made.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n[[File:LaulasiIslandSolomonISlandsPart1video.webm|thumb|150px |Part 1 Documentary Video]]\n[[File:LaulasiIslandPart2higher.webm|thumb|150px |Part 2 Documentary Video]]\n\n==1800 to 1900==\n\nIn 1892 the [[Queensland]] government Australia abandoned the Pacific labour trade known as [[Blackbirding]] and in 1901 the Commonwealth of Australia enacted the [[Pacific Island Labourers Act 1901]] which facilitated the deportation of Pacific Islanders that was the precursor to the [[White Australia policy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nBritain was provided with a \"plausible excuse for protecting the Solomons\" and so protecting their labour reserves. By declaring a protectorate, the British were able to justify keeping out other colonial powers.<ref name=\"wealth\">{{cite book |title=Wealth of the Solomons: A History of a Pacific Archipelago, 1800\u20131978 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CP8HlIuTaF8C |author=Judith A. Bennett|isbn=978-0-8248-1078-8 |id={{ISBN|0-8248-1078-3}}|year=1987 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press}}</ref>\n\nIn 1893 then Gibson of [[HMS Curacoa|HMS Curacoa (1854)]] sailed around the islands to declare a protectorate with the only opposition by the Laulasi villages who refused the British flag. When Gibson asked why the flag was refused, the villages were afraid that their acceptance of it would signify to the bush people that by aligning themselves with Britain the lagoon dwellers were preparing for war and this would lead the bush people discontinuing trade with the lagoon people, who had no gardens and were dependent on food.<ref name=\"wealth\"/>\n\n==1911 \u2013 Author Jack London==\n\nAmerican author [[Jack London]] travelled to Langa Langa in a yacht in 1908.<ref name=\"JL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.huntington.org/WebAssets/Templates/content.aspx?id=10902|title=Jack London: Chronology |accessdate=22 March 2014 |publisher=The Huntington |date=}}</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"We ran down the lagoon from Langa Langa, between mangrove swamps through passages scaresly wider than the Monota, and passed the reef villages of Kaloka and Auki. Like the founders of Venice, these salt water men were originally refugees form the mainland. Too weak to hold their own in the bush, survivors of village massacres, they fled to the sand banks of the lagoon. These sand banks they built up into islands and they were compelled to seek their provender from the sea. They developed canoo bodies, unable to walk about, spending all their time in the canoos, they became thick armed and broad shouldered with narrow waists and frail legs\" (p 138)<ref>{{cite book |title=Cruise of the Snark  |url=https://archive.org/details/cruisesnark00londgoog|author=[[Jack london]]|year=1911 |publisher=Harvard University Digitized 19 Jan 2006}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"I sailed in the teak-built ketch, the Minota, on a blackbirding cruise to Malaita, and I took my wife along. The hatchet-marks were still raw on the door of our tiny stateroom advertising an event of a few months before. The event was the taking of Captain Mackenzie's head, Captain Mackenzie, at that time, being master of the Minota.... As we sailed in to Langa-Langa on the shore side of the lagoon, was [[Binu]], the place where the Minota was captured a year previously and her captain killed by the bushmen of Malaita, having been hacked to pieces and eaten\" (p 135)<ref>https://archive.org/details/logofsnark00londrich Log of the Stark</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"He(Mackenzie) believed in kindness. He also contended that better confidence was established by carrying no weapons. On his second trip to Malaita, recruiting,he ran into Bina, which is near Langa Langa. The rifles with which the boat's-crew should have been armed, were locked up in his cabin. When the whale-boat went ashore after recruits, he paraded around the deck without even a revolver on him. He was tomahawked. His head remains in Malaita. It was suicide.<ref>http://www.readprint.com/chapter-6916/Jack-London ''Adventure'' \u2013 by Jack London (1911)</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Log of the Snark states:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"..still bore the tomahawk marks where the Malaitans at Langa Langa several months before broke in for the trove of rifles and ammunition locked therein, after bloodily slaughtering Jansen's predecessor, Captain Mackenzie. The burning of the vessel was somehow prevented by the black crew, but this was so unprecedented that the owner feared some complicity between them and the attacking party. However, it could not be proved, and we sailed with the majority of this same crew. The present skipper smilingly warned us that the same tribe still required two more heads from the Minota, to square up for deaths on the Ysabel plantation. (p 387)<ref>https://archive.org/stream/logofsnark00londrich/logofsnark00londrich_djvu.txt The Log of the Stark</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Three fruitless days were spent at Su'u. The Minota got no recruits from the bush and the bushmen got no heads from the Minota. We towed out with a whaleboat and ran along the coast to Langa Langa, a large village of salt-water people built with labour on a sand bank&nbsp;\u2013 literally built up\"<ref name=\"Tales of Adventure\">{{cite book |title=Tales of Adventure |url=https://archive.org/details/talesofadventur000lond |url-access=registration |quote=Langa Langa. |author=Jack London|year=1956 |publisher=Hanover House, University of Michigan}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==World War II==\n\nOn the morning of 7 August 1942 (same date as the [[Guadalcanal Campaign|US Landings on Guadacanal]]),\n\n<blockquote>\n\"..seven US planes bombed the island. The reason was due to an error namely that the Americans mistook Laulasi for the Japanese camp at Afufu in North Malaita. Which resulted in the killing 24 children, destroying the shell money industry and the incident still remains the subject of an unresolved compensation claim\".<ref name=\"Iume\">{{cite book |title=Ples Blong iume: Solomon |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0MAyfyJY05QC |author=Sam Alasia & 13 others, Hugh Laracy|isbn= 978-982-02-0027-2 |year=2006 |publisher=University South Pacific}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe British resident commissioner wrote in his diary:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"7 US planes bombed Laulasi village&nbsp;\u2013 18 killed&nbsp;\u2013 most inexplicable as no enemy repeorted there\"(Marchant 7 Aug 1942)<ref name=\"bombing\">{{cite book |title=The Pacific Theatre: Island Representations of World War II |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ONQf-Qui0UC |author1=Geoffrey Miles White |author2=Lamont Lindstrom |isbn= 978-0-8248-1146-4 |year=1989 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The bombing of Laulasi island was the worst loss of civilian lives in the entire Solomon Islands conflict\".<ref name=\"landmark\">{{cite book |title=Guadalcanal: The Definitive Account of the Landmark Battle |url=https://archive.org/details/guadalcanal00rich |url-access=registration |quote=Laulasi. |author=Richard B. Frank|isbn= 978-0-14-016561-6 |year=1992 |publisher=Penguin Books}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Cultural Practices and Beliefs==\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The LangaLanga and Kwara'ae people more or less have the same cultural and traditional practices and follow the same chiefly system. Male children for example are more valued than females because they will continue with the line or tribe. Girls are not so preferred because they leave the community when they get married. Boys are separated from their parents when they are around 12 or 13 years old to live separate in the men's houses. Around that age, they are taught by the fathers basic important skills such as fishing, building houses, making canoes or cutting and sewing sago palm leaves\".\n\n\"Girls on the other hand, they stay with their mother and taught household cores such as cooking, weeding around the house, cleaning and looking after their younger brothers of sisters. One of the important things that girls learn at an early age too is how to make shell money\".\n\n</blockquote>\n[[File:Warriorwelcome.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Tribal warriors challenging the visitors. Taken 2008]]\nHistorically, chiefs in the Langalanga lagoon are looked upon as very important in uniting communities. Normally, chiefs are chosen from chiefly tribes or clan. Villages in the past used to have threes chiefs, Fa'atabu who makes offering and communicated with the spirits and ancestors, the Ramo is responsible for tribal warfare and Waenotolo is the chief responsible for controlling, organising, leadership and uniting the whole community.\n\nPriests in Laulasi live in \"spirit houses,\" and when they die, their bodies are taken to the nearby village of Alite to decompose, after which the skulls are brought back and placed in a \"house of skulls.\"<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite book |title=Moon Handbooks South Pacific |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_EDGapfBX-CAC |pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_EDGapfBX-CAC/page/n1025 1006]|author=David Stanley|isbn= 978-1-56691-411-6 |year=2004 |publisher=David Stanley}}</ref>\n\nOn the side of the island is an inlet where custom priests calls the sharks to come to the surface. The sharks are re-incarnation of the people's ancestors who died many years before. They also offer sacrifices to the sharks in the form of pigs. Ordinary men are not allowed to visit the shark site unless invited by the custom priest.<ref name=\"Moon\"/>{{Failed verification|date=November 2008}}\n\nAccording to local legend, a fisherman whose boat capsizes at sea may call on a shark to rescue him; after being rescued and returned to shore, he must sacrifice a pig, or else the shark will eat him next time he goes out to sea.<ref name=\"Iume\"/><ref name=\"Moon\"/>\n\nBy the 1960s many of the LangaLanga villages were Christian. Many of the communities previously sited on the artificial islands had been shifted to the mainland, with encouragement from the missionaries anxious to promote a clean break with the pagan past, and inducement in the form of greater access to land for subsistence farming.<ref name=\"ANU\">{{cite book |title=Melanesia: Beyond Diversity |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8gpzAAAAMAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Ronald James May, Hank Nelson, Australian National University Research School of Pacific Studies|isbn= 978-0-86784-045-2 |year=1982 |publisher=Research School of Pacific Studies, The Australian National University}}</ref>\n\n==Last Pagan priest==\n\nIn 1980, Moses Beogo who was the last Pagan priest (Fata'abu) on Laulasi and the last to perform the shark calling tradition, died. His skull is kept with the skulls of the other priests.<ref name=\"Iume\"/>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Laulasiapartment1.jpg|right|thumb|150px|An \"apartment\" to store Priest Heads of another tribe. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:Laulasiapartment.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Another \"apartment\" to store Priest Heads of one tribe. Taken 2008]]\n\nA report on the British Solomon Islands dated 1972 states:\n<blockquote>\n\"where the traditional process of making shell money and other island activities may be observed, once again proved popular with the tourists\".<ref name=\"report72\">{{cite book |title=British Solomon Islands: Report |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YTmYZfvEOMMC&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Great Britain Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Colonial Office|year=1972 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Off}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1981 a symposium in the then U.S.S.R heard of Solomon Islands that:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"One of the more successful ventures in the tourist industry is Laulasi Adventure Tours Ltd\"<ref name=\"symposium\">{{cite book |title=Persistence and Exchange: Papers from a Symposium on Ecological Problems of the Traditional Societies of the Pacific Region : XIV Pacific Science Congress, Khabarovsk, U.S.S.R., August\u2014September, 1979 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BzuxAAAAIAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Roland W. Force, Brenda Bishop, Pacific Science Association|isbn= 978-0-9604480-2-9 |year=1981 |publisher=Pacific Science Association}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1982 a research paper by the [[Australian National University]] claimed:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Laulasi has become one of the notable tourist attractions of the South Pacific&nbsp;\u2013 with all the predictable consequences for the integrity of the ancestoral religion and the fabric of community social life. Moreover, the expatriate entrepreneurs were Baha'is, and offered a ready-made religious accommodation between ancestors and capitalism\".<ref name=\"ANU\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 1997 an author stated:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Laulasi village, at the centre of the lagoon, makes a business of being nice to visitors. A real business, because it charges more than a Disneyland ticket to tread its man made shores\".<ref name=\"Romancing\">{{cite book |title=Romancing the Islands: Journeys in the South Pacific |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q1N0AAAAMAAJ&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Kim Gravelle|isbn= 978-982-214002-6 |year=1997 |publisher=Graphics (Pacific) Ltd}}<!--Check ISBN Hyphenation--></ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn 2006 [[The Last Heathen]] by Charles Montgomery concludes that for this he was expecting to find a volatile mixture of the tribal, pagan religion and Christianity. He found a comfortable hybrid instead, the two religions living in harmony.<ref name=\"Last Heathen\">{{cite book |title=The Last Heathen: Encounters with Ghosts and Ancestors in Melanesia ([[Shark God]])|author=Charles Montgomery|year=2004 |publisher=HarperCollins}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008 on an invitation from the Laulasi community a delegation from [[RAMSI]] was invited to attend to officiate the \"re-opening\" of the Laulasi Tourist Industry. Members took footage and photographs with a view of assisting with publicity. The delegation was escorted to the dock with a traditional war canoe trailing and a 10-seat war canoe leading with the latter being Laulasi women singing a traditional welcome song.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nOn arrival at the dock, warriors confronted the delegation until a sum of shell money was presented to the warriors as a sign of peace. Once this gift was received the village girls offered the delegation refreshments.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe men of the delegation were permitted to tour the three \"apartments\" that each represented a tribe. In each apartment, the skulls of past priests were laid atop one another. Once this tour concluded, the delegation was presented with a display of song and dance and formalities and a demonstration of the minting process of the shell money. The village women then sang as the delegation sailed away.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Boatbuilding==\n\nThe Annual Report on the British Solomon Islands dated 1953 states\n<blockquote>\n\"..a flourishing boat building industry has been established and cutters are being built for the inter-island trade. A boatbuilding school has been established.<ref name=\"report53\">{{cite book |title=Annual Report on the British Solomon Islands |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K-VaB7cg3wsC&q=Laulasi&dq=Laulasi&pgis=1 |author=Great Britain Colonial Office|year=1953 |publisher=H.M. Stationery Off}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney.jpg|left|thumb|150px|The shell money minting production line. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney2.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Cutting the shell with a sharp stone. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney3.jpg|right|thumb|150px|Drilling the hole with a traditional drill. Taken 2008]]\n[[File:LaulasiShellmoney1.jpg|left|thumb|150px|Beading the shells for the finished product. Taken 2008]]\nGenerally, the Lanagalanga people are very skilful boat builders. It can be said that it is unique to the constituency. In the early stages people used to build dingies. Later, with improvements in skills, they built what they referred to as 'CARTER BOATS' which is sharp at both ends. They used sails to travel around Malaita and to other Islands such as Gudalcanal and Isabel. Commercial boat building in the constituency started in the 1960s around the time when the Government established a boat building school in Auki. Mr. Frank Faulker who used to teach at the school and who now settled in Auki, is said to be the main person behind the success of the industry in Langalanga.{{Citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Shell Money==\n\nThe history of shell-money making in the langa langa lagoon is patchy. Stories retold from myths said that the first person to introduce shell money to the Langalanga lagoon was a woman from [[Buin, Papua New Guinea|Buin]] in Bougainville. She was banish and floated in a coconut shell from Buin to Guadalcanal and finally to Malaita and landed at Tafilo a village at Lalana near Laulasi. Traditionally, there had been substantive trade between the Langalanga people and people from Buin in shell money until the emergence of the Bougainville crises. Most of the private ship owners from the constituency generated capital through shell money trade to build their ships. They took shell money to Buin and traded it for cash and used the cash to build wooden boats.<ref name=\"Economic\">{{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/1613811/_Making_Money_Objects_Productions_and_Performances_of_Shell_Money_Manufacture_in_Langalanga_Solomon_Islands  |title=\"Making Money\": Objects, Productions, and Performances of Shell Money Manufacture in Langalanga, Solomon Island|author=Pei-yi Guo|accessdate=22 March 2014 |publisher=The Frontiers of Southeast Asia and Pacific Studies |date=1 January 2006}}</ref>\n\nAs the production rate increased, shell resources were depleted, particularly in Langalanga lagoon. Even in the 1970s some types of shell were rare.\n\nFour different types of shell are used in making shell money, A red lipped rock oyster called Romu (chama pacifica), white shell known as Kee (Beguina semi-orbiculata), black horse mussel shells called Kurila (Atrina vexillum) and thick white disks from a rigid cockle known as Kakadu (Anadara granosa)<ref name=\"sustainability\">{{cite book |title=Pacific Voices: Equity and Sustainability in Pacific Island Fisheries|author=Iren\u00e9 Novaczek, Jean Mitchell, Joeli Vietayaki, University of the South Pacific, Institute of Pacific Studies|isbn= 978-982-020372-3 |year=2005 |publisher=University of the South Pacific}}<!--Check ISBN Hyphenation--></ref>\n\nWhat makes this money valuable are the purple disks, whose number per string is carefully calculated and which are made from the lips of the Romu shell which the Langa Langa people collect twice a year from the lagoon areas of the clan of the Lau tribe. The chief of the Lau clan allows them to fish for the shells in exchange for half the money strings.<ref name=\"gift\">{{cite book |title=The Enigma of the Gift|author1=Maurice Godelier |author2=Nora Scott |isbn= 978-0-226-30045-0 |year=1999 |publisher=University of the Chicago Press}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\n* [[Bartholomew Ulufa'alu]] (25 December 1950&nbsp;\u2013 25 May 2007) was the Prime Minister of the Solomon Islands from 27 August 1997 to 30 June 2000.\n\n==See also==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tSX7FXmhBlc Youtube video of Laulasi Island]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Islands of the Solomon Islands}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Anthropology]]\n[[Category:World War II sites in the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:History of the Solomon Islands]]\n[[Category:Exploration of Asia]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laulasi_Island"}
{"title_page": "1891 Michigan Wolverines football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox college sports team season\n| sport = football\n| year = 1891\n| team = Michigan Wolverines\n| image = 1891 Michigan Wolverines football team.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| conference = Independent\n| record = 4\u20135\n| head_coach = [[Frank Crawford]] & [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = [[James Van Inwagen]]\n| stadium = [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n}}\n{{1891 Midwestern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1891 Michigan Wolverines football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented the [[University of Michigan]] in the [[1891 college football season]]. The team compiled a 4\u20135 record and outscored opponents by a total of 168 to 124.<ref name=t91>{{cite news|title=1891 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}(The Bentley web site erroneously reports the Chicago University Club game a 10-0 loss. Contemporaneous accounts confirm the Chicago University Club scored 20 points on four touchdowns (four points each) and two kicks for goal (two points each))</ref>\n\n[[James Van Inwagen]] was the team captain. [[Frank Crawford]] was the team's coach, assisted by [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 10\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\n| site_stadium = [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| site_cityst = [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor, MI]]\n| score = 62\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 17\n| w/l = l\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 4\u201310\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}}\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Olivet, Michigan|Olivet, MI]]\n| score = 18\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 24\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 26\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 31\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 42\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 14\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = Chicago University Club\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Chicago|Chicago, IL]]\n| score = 0\u201320\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 21\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1891 Cornell Big Red football team|Cornell]]\n| site_stadium = D.A.C. Park\n| site_cityst = [[Detroit|Detroit, MI]]\n| score = 12\u201358\n| attend = 2,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 26\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = Cleveland Athletic Club\n| site_stadium = Cleveland Athletic Club\n| site_cityst = [[Cleveland|Cleveland, OH]]\n| score = 4\u20138\n| attend = 5,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = Cornell\n| site_stadium = [[South Side Park]]\n| site_cityst = Chicago, IL\n| score = 0\u201310\n| attend = 300\n}}\n}}\n\n==Season summary==\n===Michigan's first football coach===\nThe 1891 season was the first in which the Michigan football team had a coach.  In his history of the University of Michigan, Wilfred Byron Shaw cites the hiring of [[Frank Crawford]] as a watershed moment in the history of the school's football program: \"A new era in the history of football at Michigan began in 1891, when with a fair schedule and an experienced coach, Frank Crawford . . ., the systematic development of a team began ...\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilfred Byron Shaw|title=The University of Michigan|page=[https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu/page/250 250]|year=1920|publisher=Harcourt, Brace, and Howe|url=https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Crawford was an 1891 graduate of [[Yale University]] who was enrolled at the [[University of Michigan School of Law]].  As a first-year law student, Crawford was both the unpaid coach and a substitute player for the 1891 team.<ref name=t91/><ref name=Roster>{{cite web|title=1891 Michigan Football Roster |publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library |url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find |accessdate=2 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703111500/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find |archivedate=3 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCrawford was already enrolled at the law school and a member of the football team when he was selected as Michigan's first head coach. The appointment was made at a meeting of the university's athletic directors on October 16, 1891. The directors also confirmed the appointment of [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]], the trainer at the Detroit Athletic Club, to assist Crawford.<ref>{{cite news|title=Athletic Directors' Meeting|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 17, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/65|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The University|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 19, 1891|page=6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21757942/the_university/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThere is some inconsistency in how coaching responsibilities for the 1891 team have been recorded.  While Crawford has been identified by several sources as Michigan's first football coach,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forum|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 60|year=1954|page=258}}(\"He [Crawford] was the first football coach in University of Michigan history and he was unpaid.\")</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alumni Meeting in Omaha|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 15|date=December 1908|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgjiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}(\"Frank Crawford first coach of a Michigan football team and captain of the baseball team\")</ref> others indicate that Crawford and Murphy were the joint head coaches in 1891.<ref name=t91/>  Still others indicate that Murphy was the one directing the team,<ref name=BTL>{{cite news|title=BETWEEN THE RUSH LINES|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 16, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/results.html?st=advanced&QryTxt=%22frank+crawford%22&type=historic&sortby=RELEVANCE&datetype=6&frommonth=05&fromday=24&fromyear=1891&tomonth=05&today=26&toyear=1892&By=&Title=| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}(\"The U. of M. eleven has been making great progress under the able direction of Mike Murphy, the trainer of the D. A. C., and Frank Crawford, of Yale College. ...  The team has shown great improvement under Murphy's direction.\")</ref> or that Murphy relinquished the coaching duties to Crawford midway through the season to focus on his duties as trainer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frank Crawford Bio|publisher=Huskers.com|url=http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991| accessdate= 2 July 2011 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110712232822/http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991| archivedate= 12 July 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>  Murphy was the leading athletic trainer in the United States.  He gained his reputation as a trainer at Yale and was hired in 1889 by the [[Detroit Athletic Club]] where he trained [[John Owen (athlete)|John Owen]] and [[Harry M. Jewett]], who became the fastest sprinters in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Good Trust Guarding Thirty Thousand Collegians|publisher=Ft. Wayne Sentinel|date=1911-10-28}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' reported in November 1891 that the Michigan team was \"coached systematically\" by Murphy, Crawford, [[Horace Greely Prettyman]] and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Players From Ann Arbor: A New but Strong Team Which Will Play a Clean Game|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 14, 1891}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-season expectations===\nThe 1891 season began with complaints that the student body had become apathetic toward football.  On October 3, 1891, ''The Chronicle-Argonaut'' reported that the university's Athletic Association was having difficulty securing memberships.  Students asked to subscribe had responded, \"I guess I'll wait till I see what the foot-ball prospects are.\"<ref name=CA/>  The newspaper urged, \"No policy is more fatal to athletic interest than this. ... You must subscribe ''now'' and encourage the management if you desire to see good games and see our Eleven go to the front.  How can our manager arrange for games if there are no funds backing him?  How can he hire a trainer?\"<ref name=CA>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Chronicle-Argonaut|date=October 3, 1891|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0viAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Elsewhere in the same issue, interested students were encouraged to submit their names to the team's captain, [[James Van Inwagen]], to fill open place on the line.<ref>{{cite news|title=Athletics|newspaper=The Chronicle-Argonaut|date=October 3, 1891|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0viAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 1891, ''The Yellow and Blue'', a weekly publication of the university's fraternities, wrote:<blockquote>\"Although it is not our desire to find fault with the football management, we would like to ask one or two pertinent questions in regard to the present situation.  Why has no training table been provided?  Is an earnest effort being made to secure a coach who is thoroughly acquainted with eastern tactics?  No eastern captain would consider his team in condition without several weeks of physical training, including the training table.  We have never taken the trouble here to give the system of physical training a fair trial, neither have we won a great game of football. ... The expense of a training table would not be very great, and money could not e expended to better advantage.\"<ref name=YB>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Yellow and Blue|date=October 24, 1891|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VEHiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=foot&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe article noted that, with 2,600 students, there should be an ability to raise funds for football, but that there \"seems to be a general apathy in regard to foot ball.\"<ref name=YB/>\n\n===Ann Arbor High School===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 1: Ann Arbor High School at Michigan'''\n|Visitor=[[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\n|V1=0 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=38 |H2=24\n|Date=October 10\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 10, 1891, Michigan opened its season with a 62\u20130 victory over [[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\nat the [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]. Michigan scored 12 touchdowns: six by Edward De Pont, four by [[James Van Inwagen]], and one each by William Pearson and [[Roger Sherman]]. Van Inwagen kicked seven goals from touchdown. Despite the score, ''The U. of M. Daily'' wrote: \"The work of the University team was very poor. There was absolutely no team work, as was to be expected since the men had never lined up together before.\"<ref name=AAHS/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup in the game was [[George Dygert]] (left end), William Pearson (left tackle), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Berry (center), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Wright (right tackle), [[Roger Sherman]] (right end), George S. Holden (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (halfback), Frank Loomis (halfback), Edward P. De Pont (fullback).<ref name=AAHS>{{cite news|title=The First Game: The 'Varsity Eleven Makes Its First Appearance|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 12, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/45|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Albion===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 2: Albion at Michigan'''\n|Visitor='''{{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}}'''\n|V1=10 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=0 |H2=4\n|Date=October 17\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 17, 1891, Michigan lost for the first time to {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}} by a 10\u20134 score. The game was played at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds in 30-minute halves.<ref name=Albion/> Michigan had played Albion seven times from 1886 to 1890 and had won all seven of the previous matches by a combined score of 287-22.\n\nAlbion scored first, using a formation that Michigan argued was illegal. The Albion linemen, excepting the ends, locked arms and formed a wedge of protection for the quarterback who ran behind the wedge. The ends, halfbacks, and fullback locked in behind the quarterback, protecting the ball carrier from all sides. Because Albion's line was heavier, Michigan's line had difficulty in stopping Albion's advance. Michigan argued that the use of interlocking of arms violated new rules prohibiting the use of arms to interfere with or obstruct an opponent who was not carrying the ball. Michigan also argued that the quarterback run was illegal as a violation of a rule prohibiting the first man to receive the ball when snapped from advancing the ball.<ref name=Albion/><ref>{{cite news|title=Albion, 10; University, 4|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 18, 1891|page=19|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21745495/albion_10_university_4/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Burnham (quarterback and captain) and Anderson (left halfback) scored touchdowns for Albion in the first half, and Burnham kicked a goal from touchdown. Hayes scored a touchdown for Michigan in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|title=Not Won According To New Rules|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 18, 1891|page=5|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21745652/not_won_according_to_new_rules/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Albion team arrived at its local train station at midnight following the game. They were met at the depot by a large crowd, including almost every male student at the college, armed with kazoos, razoos, bells, drums, and fish-horns.  The team was taken by carriage to a bonfire on College Hill, where Burnham provided a first-hand account of the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Protest From Albion -- How the Team Was Received Upon Its Return|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 19, 1891|page=6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21746112/a_protest_from_albion_how_the_team/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Albion was Ralph Hayes (right end), [[George Dygert]] (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Berry (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Williams (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback and captain), Lawrence Grosh (left halfback), and Edward P. De Pont (fullback).<ref name=Albion>{{cite news|title=Albion, 10; Michigan, 4: Albion Employs Questionable Tactics with its \"Beefy\" Line|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 19, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/71|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Olivet===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 3: Michigan at Olivet'''\n|Visitor='''Michigan'''\n|V1=6 |V2=12\n|Host={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}}\n|H1=6 |H2=0\n|Date=October 19\n|Location=[[Olivet, MI]]\n| Attendance =\n|Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Monday, October 19, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}} by an 18\u20136 score at [[Olivet, Michigan]]. The train carrying the Michigan team left Ann Arbor at 7:40&nbsp;a.m. and arrived in Olivet at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. The game began at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 30-minute halves. In the first half, Olivet scored a touchdown, but Powers blocked the kick for goal. Olivet also scored on a safety that resulted from a blocked punt after which the punter, [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]], fell on the ball. The score was tied at 6-6 at halftime. Michigan scored three touchdowns against Olivet, two by Lawrence Grosh and one by [[James Van Inwagen]]. Duffy kicked all three goals from touchdown. ''The U. of M. Daily'' complained that Olivet played \"a very unprofessional game\" with \"considerable slugging\" and \"dirty work\" by Gilbert who was finally disqualified from the game.<ref name=Olivet>{{cite news|title=Michigan 18, Olivet 6: Our Eleven Improves in Team Work but Is Still Weak at Centre|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 20, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/75|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Olivet was [[Frank Crawford]] (right end), Ralph Hayes (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Wickes (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Hiram Powers (left tackle), [[George Dygert]] (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback), Lawrence Grosh (left halfback), and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]] (fullback).<ref name=Olivet/>\n\n===Oberlin===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 4: Oberlin at Michigan'''\n|Visitor={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}\n|V1=6 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=8 |H2=18\n|Date=October 24\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 24, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}, 26\u20136, at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds. The game began at 3:32&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 30-minute halves. Oberlin scored first and kicked goal for a 6-0 lead. [[James Van Inwagen]] scored around end, but the goal was missed, and Michigan trailed, 6-4. Michigan's second touchdown was scored by quarterback [[Roger Sherman]]. After another Michigan back fumbled, an Oberlin player \"stooped to pick it up, when Sherman darted beneath him, secured the ball and pushed it over the line.\"<ref name=Ober/> Michigan again missed the kick for goal, but took an 8-6 lead into halftime.<ref name=Ober>{{cite news|title=Michigan, 26; Oberlin 6|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 26, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/95|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the second half, Michigan scored 18 points on three touchdowns by left tackle William Pearson and three kicks for goal by [[George Dygert]]. ''The U. of M. Daily'' praised Oberlin for a clean and gentlemanly game, but criticized two Michigan players (Hiram Powers and Ralph Hayes) for \"unnecessary talking in the rush line,\" opining that such \"incessant 'jawing'\" was a fault that lessened their effectiveness as players.<ref name=Ober/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Oberlin was Hiram Powers (right end), Ralph Hayes (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Wickes (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Ralph Stewart McPherran (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[George Dygert]] (right halfback), Williams (left halfback), and [[James Van Inwagen]] (fullback and captain).<ref name=Ober/>\n\n===Butler===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 5: Butler at Michigan'''\n|Visitor={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}\n|V1=0 |V2=6\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=20 |H2=22\n|Date=October 31\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 31, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}, 42\u20136, at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds. The game began at 3:22&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 45-minute halves. Michigan's head coach and left halfback [[Frank Crawford]] scored the first touchdown on a 25-yard run around the right end, dodging several Butler players. [[George Dygert]] kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 6-0. Left tackle William Pearson scored Michigan's second touchdown, carrying \"several Butler men over the line on his shoulders.\"<ref name=But/> Dygert missed the goal, and Michigan led, 10-0. Pearson scored the third touchdown, and Dygert again missed the goal. [[James Van Inwagen]] scored the fourth touchdown on a left end run with blocking from Crawford. Dygert kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 20-0, at halftime.<ref name=But/>\n\nIn the second half, Pearson and Van Inwagen each scored two more touchdowns.  Dygert kicked three goals. One of Butler's players was disqualified for slugging Michigan's quarterback, [[Roger Sherman]]. The disqualified player later came onto the field and interfered with Van Inwagen and refused to leave when directed to step back by one of the officials.<ref name=But/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup was Ralph Hayes (right end), Harry Mowrey (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Dana Wickes (center), Berry (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Hiram Powers (left end), [[Roger Sherman (American football)|Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback and captain), [[Frank Crawford]] (left halfback), and [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=But>{{cite news|title=Michigan 52, Butler 6: The Indiana Champions Do Not Measure up to Michigan|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 2, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/119|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nOne hour prior to the game, Michigan's trainer and assistant football coach, [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]], oversaw a series of foot races, including contests at 100 yards, 220 yards, and 440 yards.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Races|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 2, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/119|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago University Club===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 6: Michigan at Chicago University Club'''\n|Visitor=Michigan\n|V1=0 |V2=0\n|Host='''Chicago University Club'''\n|H1=0 |H2=20\n|Date=November 14\n|Location=[[Chicago]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 14, 1891, Michigan lost to the Chicago University Club. Although University of Michigan records reflect the score as 10-0,<ref name=t91/> contemporaneous press accounts report the score as 20-0 with the Chicago club scoring four touchdowns and kicking two goals from touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|title=They Failed To Score|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 15, 1891|pages=3, 6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21758461/they_failed_to_score/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  The ''Detroit Free Press'' reported: \"After a hard fight, during which neither side scored until the second innings, the Chicago University team won the great foot ball match against the University of Michigan by 20 points to nothing.  It was a gallant battle, the Michigan men contesting every inch gained by their opponents.\"<ref name=DFPCh>{{cite news|title=The Chicago University Team Defeats the U. of M.|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 16, 1891|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21758490/the_chicago_university_team_defeats_the/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's lineup against the Chicago University Club was as follows: Hayes and Griffin (right end), Tupper (right tackle), Mowrey (right guard), Jefferis (center), Wickes (left guard), Pearson and Thomas (left tackle), Powers (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (captain and quarterback), James Van Inwagen (right halfback), Rittenger (left halfback), [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=CUC>{{cite news|title=A Deliberate Steal: Michigan Suffers at the Hands of a Biased Umpire|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 16, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/167|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell (Detroit)===\nThe 1891 season included two games against [[Cornell Big Red football|Cornell]], played in Detroit on November 21, 1891, and in Chicago on November 28, 1891.<ref name=t91/>  In the first game, played at [[Detroit Athletic Club|D.A.C. Park]], Cornell won by a lopsided score of 58-12.<ref>{{cite news|title=CORNELL WINS THE THIRD: The U. of M. Football Players Beaten and Dragged in the Mud|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 23, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727626112.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+23%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=CORNELL+WINS+THE+THIRD.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The ''Detroit Free Press'' reported that the game was played in the rain and, while the crowd of 2,300 persons was \"made up of the best class of people including many ladies, the rain doubtless kept fully as many away who would have been on hand but for the thought that the game would be played in the mist and mud.\"<ref name=DFPC>{{cite news|title=Football: Cornell Was Victorious Again|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 23, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727626132.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+23%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=FOOT+BALL.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Michigan's scoring came on touchdowns by Van Inwagen and Rittinger, and two successful goal kicks by Dygert.<ref name=DFPC/>\n\nDespite the lopsided score of the first Cornell game, the ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' reported: \"The Cornell-University of Michigan football at D.A.C. Park this afternoon was undoubtedly the finest exhibition of sport ever seen in Detroit.  The game was one-sided, but was by no means a walkaway for the victors.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=MICHIGAN TOO LIGHT FOR CORNELL: White and Red Victorious at Detroit by a Score of 58 to 12|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 22, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/430948012.html?dids=430948012:430948012&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+22%2C+1891&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=MICHIGAN+TOO+LIGHT+FOR+CORNELL.&pqatl=google| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Michigan coach, Mike Murphy, also saw some positive signs in Michigan's performance, as the ''Free Press'' reported: \"Michigan has the greater weight on the rush line and with practice will be far stronger than at present.  In fact Murphy is jubilant and thinks that next year he can hustle them all.\"<ref name=DFPC/>\n\nMichigan's lineup in the first Cornell game was as follows: Southworth (left end), Pearson and Griffin (left tackle), Tupper (left guard), Jefferis (center), Wickes (right guard), Mowrey (right tackle), Hayes (right end), Sherman (quarterback), Rittinger (left halfback), Van Inwagen (right halfback), and Dygert (fullback).<ref>{{cite news|title=Cornell, 58; Michigan, 12|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 23, 1891|pages=1, 3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/191|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Athletic Club===\nOn November 26, 1891, Michigan lost a mid-week road game against the Cleveland Athletic Club. The game was played at the Cleveland Athletic Club grounds in Cleveland.  The Michigan team arrived in Cleveland at 8:30&nbsp;a.m., and the game was played at 11:00&nbsp;a.m. in front of a crowd estimated at 3,000 persons.  The game was played on a slippery field described by the ''Detroit Free Press'' as follows: \"A part of the field was covered by turf, but the greater part had been recently broken and rolled, and was in miserable condition.  Besides, there was about an inch or two of soft mud on top of frozen ground, making it very slippery.\"<ref name=CLE/>  Cleveland took an 8-0 lead before Michigan's fullback, [[George Dygert]], broke through for a touchdown in the second half.  Cleveland won by a final score of 8-4.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' attributed the loss to a strategic mistake by Michigan's captain: \"A fatal mistake was made when Capt. Van Inwagen consented to play thirty-minute halves, instead of forty-five, for the Cleveland team was 'beefy' and did not have good wind.  One of the Buckeye players, in particular, was stretched out on the ground nearly half of the time, merely to give his men time to recover their wind.\"<ref name=CLE>{{cite news|title=The U. of M. Beaten at Cleveland|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 27, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727630072.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+27%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=2&desc=The+U.+of+M.+Beaten+at+Cleveland.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=CAC/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Cleveland was as follows: Edward P. De Pont (left end), Harry Mowrey (left tackle) [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Albert W. Jefferis (center), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Willard W. Griffin (right tackle), Ralph Hayes (right end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), Charles F. Rittinger (right halfback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (captain and left halfback), and [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=CAC>{{cite news|title=Referee vs. Umpire: Michigan's Eleven Runs Against a Snag at Cleveland|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 30, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/195|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell (Chicago)===\nThe final game was played on November 28, 1891, at the [[South Side Park|South Side Baseball Grounds]] in Chicago, with Cornell winning 10-0.<ref>{{cite news|title=FOUGHT IN THE SNOW: CORNELL DEFEATS MICHIGAN IN A HARD STRUGGLE; An Interesting Game in Which an Absence of Slugging Was a Noticeble Feature--The Yellow and Blue Beaten by a Score of 10 to 0--Ann Arbor's Strong Play-Cornell's Work Better than That of Thanksgiving Day|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 29, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/430958742.html?dids=430958742:430958742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+29%2C+1891&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=FOUGHT+IN+THE+SNOW.&pqatl=google| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The ''New York Times'' called it \"one of the prettiest foot-ball games ever played in the West\" and described the wintry conditions of the game: \"The field was covered with a six-inch blanket of snow, the air was icy, and frosted feet and hands were among the thousands of spectators ... Three minutes after the game began the ball was covered with ice, but the dazzling white ground soon began to look as though a herd of elephants had been tramping on it.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=On a Snow-Covered Field: Cornell Defeats Michigan in a Very Brilliant Game|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 29, 1891|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/11/29/106055123.pdf| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Detroit Free Press'' reported that Michigan gave Cornell \"a sharp tussle\" and that six of Cornell's points \"were scored on a fluke, the ball being fumbled on a pass back.\"<ref name=DFPCo/>  Powers, left end; Mowrey, left tackle; Thomas, left guard; Jeffries, center; Tupper, right guard; Griffin, right tackle;Hayes, right end, Sherman, quarterback; Van Inwagen, left half; Riitenger, right half; Dygert, fullback.<ref name=DFPCo>{{cite news|title=FOOT BALL|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 30, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727635112.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+30%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=FOOT+BALL.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of the Western Intercollegiate Athletic Association===\nIn April 1892, an athletic league, to include football, baseball, and track, was formed at Chicago between Michigan, the [[University of Wisconsin]], the [[University of Minnesota]], and [[Northwestern University]].  \"The plans of the league are to have a series of base ball games in the spring, an inter-collegiate field day to be held in Chicago in June and a series of foot-ball games in the fall.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Ariel|date=April 23, 1892|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LrYNAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The new athletic league, named the Western Intercollegiate Athletic Association, was later renamed the [[Big Ten Conference]].<ref>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The University Record|date=June 1892|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMonAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Varsity letter winners===\nThe following 13 players were awarded varsity letters in football for the 1891 season, according to University of Michigan records.<ref name=Roster/>\n\n*[[George Dygert]], [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] - started 5 games at fullback, 2 games at left end, 1 game at right tackle, and 1 game at right halfback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"George Dygert, the full back, plays the game well from start to finish.  He kicks and dodges to perfection and is a reliable man all the way through. Dygert is not a fast runner, but uses his head and invariably makes god gains with the ball.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Lawrence C. Grosh,<ref>Lawrence Chamberlaine Grosh was born August 19, 1870, in [[Goshen, Indiana]]. He later became a medical doctor in Toledo starting in 1898.  He was the chief of staff at Toledo Hospital from 1931 to 1943. He reportedly pioneered medical research at the hospital.  He died July 6, 1944, at Rossford, Ohio.  See [ Obituary].</ref> [[Toledo, Ohio]] - started two games at left halfback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Grosh, half-back, is regarded as the best man to send against the line.  He runs well with the ball and is a hard man to stop.  He has trained faithfully all the season and shows the result of his work in his steady playing in the practice games on the field.  His weight is 162 pounds.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Ralph W. Hayes,<ref>Ralph Waldo Emerson Hayes was born February 19, 1872, in [[Stark County, Illinois]].  He married Estella Mink in 1896.  He returned to Galva, Illinois, where he became a manufacturer and inventor.  Among other things, he invented the Hayes pump, used in irrigation and agriculture.  His company was known as the Hayes Pump & Planter Co., in that city.  He died February 11, 1932.</ref> [[Galva, Illinois]] - started 6 games at right end, 2 games at right tackle\n*[[Albert W. Jefferis]], [[Omaha, Nebraska]] - started 4 games at center.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Jeffries [sic] will doubtless play center and will make a good man for the position.  He weighs 201 and is strong and very active.  He snaps the ball well and will bother his opponents on the line.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Harry J. Mowrey,<ref>Harry Josiah Mowrey was born May 28, 1872, at [[Stockton, Pennsylvania]].  He moved to South Dakota after completing his legal education at Michigan. He served in the 1st South Dakota Volunteers during the Spanish\u2013American War.  He married Estella Holden in 1909.  From 1907, he worked for Armour & Co. and ran its operation in [[Aberdeen, South Dakota]].  He died at Lake Minnetonka, July 2, 1921, and was buried in [[Watertown, South Dakota]].</ref> [[Lake Minnetonka]], [[Minnesota]] - started 2 games at right tackle, 2 games at left tackle, 1 game at right guard. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Mowery [sic], the other candidate for tackle, weighs 187 pounds and is a strong active player.  He tackles well and follows the ball with as much speed as the backs.  Murphy is particularly well pleased with this player and considers him a gret find.\"\n*William W. Pearson,<ref>William Wilson Pearson later lived in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].  He served as a Professor of Ophthalmology and Dean of the College of Medicine at the Drake University.</ref>  [[Springfield, Illinois]] - started 6 games at left tackle. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Pearson, left tackle, is the best rusher the college has seen for many years.  He weighs 192 pounds and is very powerful, often carrying two or three men on his back in some of his rushes.  When given the ball Pearson usually makes a gain.  He plays third base on the nine and is a good example of an all-around athlete.  He is quick on his feet and a hard man to stop.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Hiram Powers, [[Buffalo, New York]] - started 4 games at left end, 1 game at right end, 1 game at left tackle. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Powers has played a good game at right end thus far and seems sure of his position.  He follows the ball closely, tackles well and plays a hard game for his weight, which is 145 pounds.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Charles Frederick Rittinger - started 3 games at left halfback, 1 game at right halfback.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Possibly the greatest find of the season is Rittenger [sic], another of Murphy's discoveries.  He is trying for half back, and seems sure of the place on the eleven. He weighs 173 pounds and excels in running the ball and bucking the rush line.\"<ref name=BTL/>  Rittinger was a school principal in [[Okemos, Michigan]], before enrolling at Michigan's Law Department in 1881.  He was injured during an 1891 game against Cornell.  Several months later, \"hemorrhages set in, and the injury proved to be a vital one.\"  He died August 21, 1893, at [[Cass City, Michigan]], at age 24. The ''Speculum'' wrote: \"In many respects Mr. Rittinger was a superior character, and gave promise of becoming a star among men.  In intellectual vigor he ranked high.  His generosity was unbounded.  The qualities with this impetuosity and fiery zeal enabled him to subdue difficulties and laugh at all possibilities.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Scroll of Phi Delta Theta, Volume 18|publisher=Phi Delta Theta Fraternity|page=438|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y-MSAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 5 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n*[[Roger Sherman (American football)|Roger Sherman]], [[Chicago, Illinois]] - started 8 games at quarterback, 1 game at right end. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Roger Sherman, at quarter, is as good a man for the position as the university has seen for many years.  Although the lightest man on the eleven he plays a strong game and finishes well.  He tackles cleverly and is usually sure of his man.  His passing is accurate and he falls on the ball better than any man on the team.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n* [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles L. Thomas]], [[Omaha, Nebraska]] - started 6 games at right guard, 1 game at left guard, and 1 game at left tackle.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Thomas has also been playing tackle and has played his position well, although not up to his standard, as he is well built, weighs 183, and is a good man for the line.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*[[Virgil Tupper]], [[Bay City, Michigan]] - started 6 games at left guard, 1 game at right guard, 1 game at right tackle.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Tupper will play right guard ... Tupper weighs 194 pounds and is very owerful.  He runs well and follows the ball closely.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*[[James Van Inwagen]] - started 8 games at halfback, 1 game at fullback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Van Inwagen, the captain, received his foot ball education at Exeter, N.H., ...  He weighs 160 pounds, is a speedy runner (the fastest man on the eleven) and plays a brilliant, showy game.  His opponents give him credit for being the hardest man to tackle on the team.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n* Edward Dana Wickes,<ref>Wickes was born March 11, 1870.  He later became an electrical engineer and lived in Columbus, Ohio, and Chicago.</ref> [[Helena, Montana]] - started 3 games at center, 1 game at left guard, 1 game at right guard. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Wickes, left guard, weighs 186 pounds and is playing a good game.  He is very aggressive and keeps his man moving most of the time.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n\n===Substitutes===\nThe following players are recorded as substitutes for the 1891 football team, according to University of Michigan records.<ref name=Roster/>\n* Berry - substitute, [[Howard, Ohio]]\n*[[Frank Crawford]], [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]] - started 1 game at right end, 1 game at left halfback.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Crawford, left end, weighs 146 pounds, but plays a hard game from the start.  He is a good runner and tackler, and is very slippery.  He is quick to take advantage of an opening and makes some very good runs.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Edward Paul De Pont,<ref>DePont was the son of a professor and the registrar at the University of Michigan, Paul Rousseau Bellon de Pont.  He was later a salesman for a spice company in Toledo.</ref> [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] - started 2 games at fullback.\n*[[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]], [[Bay City, Michigan]] - started 1 game at fullback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Duffy is too well known to need further introduction to the average reader who follows athletics on the field or track.  He is a brilliant runner, a sure tackler and altogether a very desirable half-back.  His kicking is his specialty, however, and in this line he has never been excelled.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Willard Wilmer Griffin, [[Wenona, Illinois]] - substitute guard.\n*Charles Wilson Southworth,<ref>Southworth later attended the University of Buffalo Department of Medicine and practiced medicine in [[Salem, Oregon]].  He died January 17, 1924, at age 53.</ref> [[Forestville, New York]] - substitute end.\n\n===Coaching staff===\n* Head coach: [[Frank Crawford]]<ref name=t91/>\n* Trainer: [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]]<ref name=t91/>\n* Manager: [[Royal T. Farrand]]<ref name=t91/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm 1891 Football Team -- Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan Athletics History]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=VEHiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Yellow and Blue, 1891-1892]\n\n{{Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1891 college football season|Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football seasons]]\n[[Category:1891 in sports in Michigan|Michigan Football]]\n[[Category:1890s in Detroit]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| sport = football\n| year = 1891\n| team = Michigan Wolverines\n| image = 1891 Michigan Wolverines football team.jpg\n| image_size = 300\n| conference = Independent\n| record = 4\u20135\n| head_coach = [[Frank Crawford]] & [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = \n| def_scheme = \n| captain = [[James Van Inwagen]]\n| stadium = [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n}}\n{{1891 Midwestern college football independents records}}\nThe '''1891 Michigan Wolverines football team''' was an [[American football]] team that represented the [[University of Michigan]] in the [[1891 college football season]]. The team compiled a 4\u20135 record and outscored opponents by a total of 168 to 124.<ref name=t91>{{cite news|title=1891 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}(The Bentley web site erroneously reports the Chicago University Club game a 10-0 loss. Contemporaneous accounts confirm the Chicago University Club scored 20 points on four touchdowns (four points each) and two kicks for goal (two points each))</ref>\n\n[[James Van Inwagen]] was the team captain. [[Frank Crawford]] was the team's coach, assisted by [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]].\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 10\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\n| site_stadium = [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| site_cityst = [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor, MI]]\n| score = 62\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 17\n| w/l = l\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 4\u201310\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}}\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Olivet, Michigan|Olivet, MI]]\n| score = 18\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 24\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 26\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 31\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}\n| site_stadium = Ann Arbor Fairgrounds\n| site_cityst = Ann Arbor, MI\n| score = 42\u20136\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 14\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = Chicago University Club\n| site_stadium = \n| site_cityst = [[Chicago|Chicago, IL]]\n| score = 0\u201320\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 21\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1891 Cornell Big Red football team|Cornell]]\n| site_stadium = D.A.C. Park\n| site_cityst = [[Detroit|Detroit, MI]]\n| score = 12\u201358\n| attend = 2,300\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 26\n| w/l = l\n| away = y\n| opponent = Cleveland Athletic Club\n| site_stadium = Cleveland Athletic Club\n| site_cityst = [[Cleveland|Cleveland, OH]]\n| score = 4\u20138\n| attend = 5,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = Cornell\n| site_stadium = [[South Side Park]]\n| site_cityst = Chicago, IL\n| score = 0\u201310\n| attend = 300\n}}\n}}\n\n==Season summary==\n===Michigan's first football coach===\nThe 1891 season was the first in which the Michigan football team had a coach.  In his history of the University of Michigan, Wilfred Byron Shaw cites the hiring of [[Frank Crawford]] as a watershed moment in the history of the school's football program: \"A new era in the history of football at Michigan began in 1891, when with a fair schedule and an experienced coach, Frank Crawford . . ., the systematic development of a team began ...\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilfred Byron Shaw|title=The University of Michigan|page=[https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu/page/250 250]|year=1920|publisher=Harcourt, Brace, and Howe|url=https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Crawford was an 1891 graduate of [[Yale University]] who was enrolled at the [[University of Michigan School of Law]].  As a first-year law student, Crawford was both the unpaid coach and a substitute player for the 1891 team.<ref name=t91/><ref name=Roster>{{cite web|title=1891 Michigan Football Roster |publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library |url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find |accessdate=2 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703111500/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find |archivedate=3 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCrawford was already enrolled at the law school and a member of the football team when he was selected as Michigan's first head coach. The appointment was made at a meeting of the university's athletic directors on October 16, 1891. The directors also confirmed the appointment of [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]], the trainer at the Detroit Athletic Club, to assist Crawford.<ref>{{cite news|title=Athletic Directors' Meeting|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 17, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/65|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The University|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 19, 1891|page=6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21757942/the_university/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThere is some inconsistency in how coaching responsibilities for the 1891 team have been recorded.  While Crawford has been identified by several sources as Michigan's first football coach,<ref>{{cite news|title=Forum|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 60|year=1954|page=258}}(\"He [Crawford] was the first football coach in University of Michigan history and he was unpaid.\")</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alumni Meeting in Omaha|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 15|date=December 1908|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgjiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}(\"Frank Crawford first coach of a Michigan football team and captain of the baseball team\")</ref> others indicate that Crawford and Murphy were the joint head coaches in 1891.<ref name=t91/>  Still others indicate that Murphy was the one directing the team,<ref name=BTL>{{cite news|title=BETWEEN THE RUSH LINES|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 16, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/results.html?st=advanced&QryTxt=%22frank+crawford%22&type=historic&sortby=RELEVANCE&datetype=6&frommonth=05&fromday=24&fromyear=1891&tomonth=05&today=26&toyear=1892&By=&Title=| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}(\"The U. of M. eleven has been making great progress under the able direction of Mike Murphy, the trainer of the D. A. C., and Frank Crawford, of Yale College. ...  The team has shown great improvement under Murphy's direction.\")</ref> or that Murphy relinquished the coaching duties to Crawford midway through the season to focus on his duties as trainer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frank Crawford Bio|publisher=Huskers.com|url=http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991| accessdate= 2 July 2011 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110712232822/http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991| archivedate= 12 July 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>  Murphy was the leading athletic trainer in the United States.  He gained his reputation as a trainer at Yale and was hired in 1889 by the [[Detroit Athletic Club]] where he trained [[John Owen (athlete)|John Owen]] and [[Harry M. Jewett]], who became the fastest sprinters in the country.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Good Trust Guarding Thirty Thousand Collegians|publisher=Ft. Wayne Sentinel|date=1911-10-28}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' reported in November 1891 that the Michigan team was \"coached systematically\" by Murphy, Crawford, [[Horace Greely Prettyman]] and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Players From Ann Arbor: A New but Strong Team Which Will Play a Clean Game|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 14, 1891}}</ref>\n\n===Pre-season expectations===\nThe 1891 season began with complaints that the student body had become apathetic toward football.  On October 3, 1891, ''The Chronicle-Argonaut'' reported that the university's Athletic Association was having difficulty securing memberships.  Students asked to subscribe had responded, \"I guess I'll wait till I see what the foot-ball prospects are.\"<ref name=CA/>  The newspaper urged, \"No policy is more fatal to athletic interest than this. ... You must subscribe ''now'' and encourage the management if you desire to see good games and see our Eleven go to the front.  How can our manager arrange for games if there are no funds backing him?  How can he hire a trainer?\"<ref name=CA>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Chronicle-Argonaut|date=October 3, 1891|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0viAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Elsewhere in the same issue, interested students were encouraged to submit their names to the team's captain, [[James Van Inwagen]], to fill open place on the line.<ref>{{cite news|title=Athletics|newspaper=The Chronicle-Argonaut|date=October 3, 1891|page=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a0viAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 1891, ''The Yellow and Blue'', a weekly publication of the university's fraternities, wrote:<blockquote>\"Although it is not our desire to find fault with the football management, we would like to ask one or two pertinent questions in regard to the present situation.  Why has no training table been provided?  Is an earnest effort being made to secure a coach who is thoroughly acquainted with eastern tactics?  No eastern captain would consider his team in condition without several weeks of physical training, including the training table.  We have never taken the trouble here to give the system of physical training a fair trial, neither have we won a great game of football. ... The expense of a training table would not be very great, and money could not e expended to better advantage.\"<ref name=YB>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Yellow and Blue|date=October 24, 1891|page=2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VEHiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=foot&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref></blockquote>\nThe article noted that, with 2,600 students, there should be an ability to raise funds for football, but that there \"seems to be a general apathy in regard to foot ball.\"<ref name=YB/>\n\n===Ann Arbor High School===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 1: Ann Arbor High School at Michigan'''\n|Visitor=[[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\n|V1=0 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=38 |H2=24\n|Date=October 10\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 10, 1891, Michigan opened its season with a 62\u20130 victory over [[Pioneer High School (Ann Arbor, Michigan)|Ann Arbor High School]]\nat the [[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]. Michigan scored 12 touchdowns: six by Edward De Pont, four by [[James Van Inwagen]], and one each by William Pearson and [[Roger Sherman]]. Van Inwagen kicked seven goals from touchdown. Despite the score, ''The U. of M. Daily'' wrote: \"The work of the University team was very poor. There was absolutely no team work, as was to be expected since the men had never lined up together before.\"<ref name=AAHS/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup in the game was [[George Dygert]] (left end), William Pearson (left tackle), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Berry (center), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Wright (right tackle), [[Roger Sherman]] (right end), George S. Holden (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (halfback), Frank Loomis (halfback), Edward P. De Pont (fullback).<ref name=AAHS>{{cite news|title=The First Game: The 'Varsity Eleven Makes Its First Appearance|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 12, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/45|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Albion===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 2: Albion at Michigan'''\n|Visitor='''{{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}}'''\n|V1=10 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=0 |H2=4\n|Date=October 17\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 17, 1891, Michigan lost for the first time to {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Albion Britons|title=Albion}} by a 10\u20134 score. The game was played at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds in 30-minute halves.<ref name=Albion/> Michigan had played Albion seven times from 1886 to 1890 and had won all seven of the previous matches by a combined score of 287-22.\n\nAlbion scored first, using a formation that Michigan argued was illegal. The Albion linemen, excepting the ends, locked arms and formed a wedge of protection for the quarterback who ran behind the wedge. The ends, halfbacks, and fullback locked in behind the quarterback, protecting the ball carrier from all sides. Because Albion's line was heavier, Michigan's line had difficulty in stopping Albion's advance. Michigan argued that the use of interlocking of arms violated new rules prohibiting the use of arms to interfere with or obstruct an opponent who was not carrying the ball. Michigan also argued that the quarterback run was illegal as a violation of a rule prohibiting the first man to receive the ball when snapped from advancing the ball.<ref name=Albion/><ref>{{cite news|title=Albion, 10; University, 4|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 18, 1891|page=19|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21745495/albion_10_university_4/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> Burnham (quarterback and captain) and Anderson (left halfback) scored touchdowns for Albion in the first half, and Burnham kicked a goal from touchdown. Hayes scored a touchdown for Michigan in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|title=Not Won According To New Rules|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 18, 1891|page=5|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21745652/not_won_according_to_new_rules/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Albion team arrived at its local train station at midnight following the game. They were met at the depot by a large crowd, including almost every male student at the college, armed with kazoos, razoos, bells, drums, and fish-horns.  The team was taken by carriage to a bonfire on College Hill, where Burnham provided a first-hand account of the game.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Protest From Albion -- How the Team Was Received Upon Its Return|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=October 19, 1891|page=6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21746112/a_protest_from_albion_how_the_team/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Albion was Ralph Hayes (right end), [[George Dygert]] (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Berry (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Williams (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback and captain), Lawrence Grosh (left halfback), and Edward P. De Pont (fullback).<ref name=Albion>{{cite news|title=Albion, 10; Michigan, 4: Albion Employs Questionable Tactics with its \"Beefy\" Line|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 19, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/71|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Olivet===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 3: Michigan at Olivet'''\n|Visitor='''Michigan'''\n|V1=6 |V2=12\n|Host={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}}\n|H1=6 |H2=0\n|Date=October 19\n|Location=[[Olivet, MI]]\n| Attendance =\n|Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn Monday, October 19, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Olivet Comets|title=Olivet}} by an 18\u20136 score at [[Olivet, Michigan]]. The train carrying the Michigan team left Ann Arbor at 7:40&nbsp;a.m. and arrived in Olivet at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. The game began at 2:30&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 30-minute halves. In the first half, Olivet scored a touchdown, but Powers blocked the kick for goal. Olivet also scored on a safety that resulted from a blocked punt after which the punter, [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]], fell on the ball. The score was tied at 6-6 at halftime. Michigan scored three touchdowns against Olivet, two by Lawrence Grosh and one by [[James Van Inwagen]]. Duffy kicked all three goals from touchdown. ''The U. of M. Daily'' complained that Olivet played \"a very unprofessional game\" with \"considerable slugging\" and \"dirty work\" by Gilbert who was finally disqualified from the game.<ref name=Olivet>{{cite news|title=Michigan 18, Olivet 6: Our Eleven Improves in Team Work but Is Still Weak at Centre|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 20, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/75|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Olivet was [[Frank Crawford]] (right end), Ralph Hayes (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Wickes (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Hiram Powers (left tackle), [[George Dygert]] (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback), Lawrence Grosh (left halfback), and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]] (fullback).<ref name=Olivet/>\n\n===Oberlin===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 4: Oberlin at Michigan'''\n|Visitor={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}\n|V1=6 |V2=0\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=8 |H2=18\n|Date=October 24\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 24, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Oberlin Yeoman|title=Oberlin}}, 26\u20136, at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds. The game began at 3:32&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 30-minute halves. Oberlin scored first and kicked goal for a 6-0 lead. [[James Van Inwagen]] scored around end, but the goal was missed, and Michigan trailed, 6-4. Michigan's second touchdown was scored by quarterback [[Roger Sherman]]. After another Michigan back fumbled, an Oberlin player \"stooped to pick it up, when Sherman darted beneath him, secured the ball and pushed it over the line.\"<ref name=Ober/> Michigan again missed the kick for goal, but took an 8-6 lead into halftime.<ref name=Ober>{{cite news|title=Michigan, 26; Oberlin 6|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=October 26, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/95|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the second half, Michigan scored 18 points on three touchdowns by left tackle William Pearson and three kicks for goal by [[George Dygert]]. ''The U. of M. Daily'' praised Oberlin for a clean and gentlemanly game, but criticized two Michigan players (Hiram Powers and Ralph Hayes) for \"unnecessary talking in the rush line,\" opining that such \"incessant 'jawing'\" was a fault that lessened their effectiveness as players.<ref name=Ober/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Oberlin was Hiram Powers (right end), Ralph Hayes (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Wickes (center), [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Ralph Stewart McPherran (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[George Dygert]] (right halfback), Williams (left halfback), and [[James Van Inwagen]] (fullback and captain).<ref name=Ober/>\n\n===Butler===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 5: Butler at Michigan'''\n|Visitor={{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}\n|V1=0 |V2=6\n|Host='''Michigan'''\n|H1=20 |H2=22\n|Date=October 31\n|Location=[[Ann Arbor Fairgrounds]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn October 31, 1891, Michigan defeated {{cfb link|year=1891|team=Butler Christians|title=Butler}}, 42\u20136, at the Ann Arbor Fairgrounds. The game began at 3:22&nbsp;p.m. and was played in 45-minute halves. Michigan's head coach and left halfback [[Frank Crawford]] scored the first touchdown on a 25-yard run around the right end, dodging several Butler players. [[George Dygert]] kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 6-0. Left tackle William Pearson scored Michigan's second touchdown, carrying \"several Butler men over the line on his shoulders.\"<ref name=But/> Dygert missed the goal, and Michigan led, 10-0. Pearson scored the third touchdown, and Dygert again missed the goal. [[James Van Inwagen]] scored the fourth touchdown on a left end run with blocking from Crawford. Dygert kicked the goal, and Michigan led, 20-0, at halftime.<ref name=But/>\n\nIn the second half, Pearson and Van Inwagen each scored two more touchdowns.  Dygert kicked three goals. One of Butler's players was disqualified for slugging Michigan's quarterback, [[Roger Sherman]]. The disqualified player later came onto the field and interfered with Van Inwagen and refused to leave when directed to step back by one of the officials.<ref name=But/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup was Ralph Hayes (right end), Harry Mowrey (right tackle), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Edward Dana Wickes (center), Berry (left guard), William Pearson (left tackle), Hiram Powers (left end), [[Roger Sherman (American football)|Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (right halfback and captain), [[Frank Crawford]] (left halfback), and [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=But>{{cite news|title=Michigan 52, Butler 6: The Indiana Champions Do Not Measure up to Michigan|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 2, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/119|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\nOne hour prior to the game, Michigan's trainer and assistant football coach, [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]], oversaw a series of foot races, including contests at 100 yards, 220 yards, and 440 yards.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Races|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 2, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/119|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago University Club===\n{{AFB game box start\n|Title='''Game 6: Michigan at Chicago University Club'''\n|Visitor=Michigan\n|V1=0 |V2=0\n|Host='''Chicago University Club'''\n|H1=0 |H2=20\n|Date=November 14\n|Location=[[Chicago]]\n| Attendance =\n| Referee =\n}}\n{{AFB game box end}}\nOn November 14, 1891, Michigan lost to the Chicago University Club. Although University of Michigan records reflect the score as 10-0,<ref name=t91/> contemporaneous press accounts report the score as 20-0 with the Chicago club scoring four touchdowns and kicking two goals from touchdown.<ref>{{cite news|title=They Failed To Score|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=November 15, 1891|pages=3, 6|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21758461/they_failed_to_score/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>  The ''Detroit Free Press'' reported: \"After a hard fight, during which neither side scored until the second innings, the Chicago University team won the great foot ball match against the University of Michigan by 20 points to nothing.  It was a gallant battle, the Michigan men contesting every inch gained by their opponents.\"<ref name=DFPCh>{{cite news|title=The Chicago University Team Defeats the U. of M.|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 16, 1891|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21758490/the_chicago_university_team_defeats_the/|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nMichigan's lineup against the Chicago University Club was as follows: Hayes and Griffin (right end), Tupper (right tackle), Mowrey (right guard), Jefferis (center), Wickes (left guard), Pearson and Thomas (left tackle), Powers (left end), [[Roger Sherman]] (captain and quarterback), James Van Inwagen (right halfback), Rittenger (left halfback), [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=CUC>{{cite news|title=A Deliberate Steal: Michigan Suffers at the Hands of a Biased Umpire|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 16, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/167|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell (Detroit)===\nThe 1891 season included two games against [[Cornell Big Red football|Cornell]], played in Detroit on November 21, 1891, and in Chicago on November 28, 1891.<ref name=t91/>  In the first game, played at [[Detroit Athletic Club|D.A.C. Park]], Cornell won by a lopsided score of 58-12.<ref>{{cite news|title=CORNELL WINS THE THIRD: The U. of M. Football Players Beaten and Dragged in the Mud|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 23, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727626112.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+23%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=CORNELL+WINS+THE+THIRD.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The ''Detroit Free Press'' reported that the game was played in the rain and, while the crowd of 2,300 persons was \"made up of the best class of people including many ladies, the rain doubtless kept fully as many away who would have been on hand but for the thought that the game would be played in the mist and mud.\"<ref name=DFPC>{{cite news|title=Football: Cornell Was Victorious Again|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 23, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727626132.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+23%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=FOOT+BALL.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  Michigan's scoring came on touchdowns by Van Inwagen and Rittinger, and two successful goal kicks by Dygert.<ref name=DFPC/>\n\nDespite the lopsided score of the first Cornell game, the ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' reported: \"The Cornell-University of Michigan football at D.A.C. Park this afternoon was undoubtedly the finest exhibition of sport ever seen in Detroit.  The game was one-sided, but was by no means a walkaway for the victors.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=MICHIGAN TOO LIGHT FOR CORNELL: White and Red Victorious at Detroit by a Score of 58 to 12|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 22, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/430948012.html?dids=430948012:430948012&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+22%2C+1891&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=MICHIGAN+TOO+LIGHT+FOR+CORNELL.&pqatl=google| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Michigan coach, Mike Murphy, also saw some positive signs in Michigan's performance, as the ''Free Press'' reported: \"Michigan has the greater weight on the rush line and with practice will be far stronger than at present.  In fact Murphy is jubilant and thinks that next year he can hustle them all.\"<ref name=DFPC/>\n\nMichigan's lineup in the first Cornell game was as follows: Southworth (left end), Pearson and Griffin (left tackle), Tupper (left guard), Jefferis (center), Wickes (right guard), Mowrey (right tackle), Hayes (right end), Sherman (quarterback), Rittinger (left halfback), Van Inwagen (right halfback), and Dygert (fullback).<ref>{{cite news|title=Cornell, 58; Michigan, 12|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 23, 1891|pages=1, 3|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/191|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Athletic Club===\nOn November 26, 1891, Michigan lost a mid-week road game against the Cleveland Athletic Club. The game was played at the Cleveland Athletic Club grounds in Cleveland.  The Michigan team arrived in Cleveland at 8:30&nbsp;a.m., and the game was played at 11:00&nbsp;a.m. in front of a crowd estimated at 3,000 persons.  The game was played on a slippery field described by the ''Detroit Free Press'' as follows: \"A part of the field was covered by turf, but the greater part had been recently broken and rolled, and was in miserable condition.  Besides, there was about an inch or two of soft mud on top of frozen ground, making it very slippery.\"<ref name=CLE/>  Cleveland took an 8-0 lead before Michigan's fullback, [[George Dygert]], broke through for a touchdown in the second half.  Cleveland won by a final score of 8-4.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' attributed the loss to a strategic mistake by Michigan's captain: \"A fatal mistake was made when Capt. Van Inwagen consented to play thirty-minute halves, instead of forty-five, for the Cleveland team was 'beefy' and did not have good wind.  One of the Buckeye players, in particular, was stretched out on the ground nearly half of the time, merely to give his men time to recover their wind.\"<ref name=CLE>{{cite news|title=The U. of M. Beaten at Cleveland|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 27, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727630072.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+27%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=2&desc=The+U.+of+M.+Beaten+at+Cleveland.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref name=CAC/>\n\nMichigan's starting lineup against Cleveland was as follows: Edward P. De Pont (left end), Harry Mowrey (left tackle) [[Virgil Tupper]] (left guard), Albert W. Jefferis (center), [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles Thomas]] (right guard), Willard W. Griffin (right tackle), Ralph Hayes (right end), [[Roger Sherman]] (quarterback), Charles F. Rittinger (right halfback), [[James Van Inwagen]] (captain and left halfback), and [[George Dygert]] (fullback).<ref name=CAC>{{cite news|title=Referee vs. Umpire: Michigan's Eleven Runs Against a Snag at Cleveland|newspaper=The U. of M. Daily|date=November 30, 1891|page=1|url=https://digital.bentley.umich.edu/midaily/mdp.39015071730704/195|via=[[Bentley Historical Library]]}}</ref>\n\n===Cornell (Chicago)===\nThe final game was played on November 28, 1891, at the [[South Side Park|South Side Baseball Grounds]] in Chicago, with Cornell winning 10-0.<ref>{{cite news|title=FOUGHT IN THE SNOW: CORNELL DEFEATS MICHIGAN IN A HARD STRUGGLE; An Interesting Game in Which an Absence of Slugging Was a Noticeble Feature--The Yellow and Blue Beaten by a Score of 10 to 0--Ann Arbor's Strong Play-Cornell's Work Better than That of Thanksgiving Day|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 29, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/430958742.html?dids=430958742:430958742&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+29%2C+1891&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=FOUGHT+IN+THE+SNOW.&pqatl=google| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The ''New York Times'' called it \"one of the prettiest foot-ball games ever played in the West\" and described the wintry conditions of the game: \"The field was covered with a six-inch blanket of snow, the air was icy, and frosted feet and hands were among the thousands of spectators ... Three minutes after the game began the ball was covered with ice, but the dazzling white ground soon began to look as though a herd of elephants had been tramping on it.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=On a Snow-Covered Field: Cornell Defeats Michigan in a Very Brilliant Game|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 29, 1891|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1891/11/29/106055123.pdf| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Detroit Free Press'' reported that Michigan gave Cornell \"a sharp tussle\" and that six of Cornell's points \"were scored on a fluke, the ball being fumbled on a pass back.\"<ref name=DFPCo/>  Powers, left end; Mowrey, left tackle; Thomas, left guard; Jeffries, center; Tupper, right guard; Griffin, right tackle;Hayes, right end, Sherman, quarterback; Van Inwagen, left half; Riitenger, right half; Dygert, fullback.<ref name=DFPCo>{{cite news|title=FOOT BALL|newspaper=Detroit Free Press|date=November 30, 1891|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/freep/access/1727635112.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Nov+30%2C+1891&author=&pub=Detroit+Free+Press+(1858-1922)&edition=&startpage=7&desc=FOOT+BALL.| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n===Formation of the Western Intercollegiate Athletic Association===\nIn April 1892, an athletic league, to include football, baseball, and track, was formed at Chicago between Michigan, the [[University of Wisconsin]], the [[University of Minnesota]], and [[Northwestern University]].  \"The plans of the league are to have a series of base ball games in the spring, an inter-collegiate field day to be held in Chicago in June and a series of foot-ball games in the fall.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The Ariel|date=April 23, 1892|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LrYNAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>  The new athletic league, named the Western Intercollegiate Athletic Association, was later renamed the [[Big Ten Conference]].<ref>{{cite news|title=untitled|newspaper=The University Record|date=June 1892|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMonAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 2 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Varsity letter winners===\nThe following 13 players were awarded varsity letters in football for the 1891 season, according to University of Michigan records.<ref name=Roster/>\n\n*[[George Dygert]], [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] - started 5 games at fullback, 2 games at left end, 1 game at right tackle, and 1 game at right halfback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"George Dygert, the full back, plays the game well from start to finish.  He kicks and dodges to perfection and is a reliable man all the way through. Dygert is not a fast runner, but uses his head and invariably makes god gains with the ball.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Lawrence C. Grosh,<ref>Lawrence Chamberlaine Grosh was born August 19, 1870, in [[Goshen, Indiana]]. He later became a medical doctor in Toledo starting in 1898.  He was the chief of staff at Toledo Hospital from 1931 to 1943. He reportedly pioneered medical research at the hospital.  He died July 6, 1944, at Rossford, Ohio.  See [ Obituary].</ref> [[Toledo, Ohio]] - started two games at left halfback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Grosh, half-back, is regarded as the best man to send against the line.  He runs well with the ball and is a hard man to stop.  He has trained faithfully all the season and shows the result of his work in his steady playing in the practice games on the field.  His weight is 162 pounds.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Ralph W. Hayes,<ref>Ralph Waldo Emerson Hayes was born February 19, 1872, in [[Stark County, Illinois]].  He married Estella Mink in 1896.  He returned to Galva, Illinois, where he became a manufacturer and inventor.  Among other things, he invented the Hayes pump, used in irrigation and agriculture.  His company was known as the Hayes Pump & Planter Co., in that city.  He died February 11, 1932.</ref> [[Galva, Illinois]] - started 6 games at right end, 2 games at right tackle\n*[[Albert W. Jefferis]], [[Omaha, Nebraska]] - started 4 games at center.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Jeffries [sic] will doubtless play center and will make a good man for the position.  He weighs 201 and is strong and very active.  He snaps the ball well and will bother his opponents on the line.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Harry J. Mowrey,<ref>Harry Josiah Mowrey was born May 28, 1872, at [[Stockton, Pennsylvania]].  He moved to South Dakota after completing his legal education at Michigan. He served in the 1st South Dakota Volunteers during the Spanish\u2013American War.  He married Estella Holden in 1909.  From 1907, he worked for Armour & Co. and ran its operation in [[Aberdeen, South Dakota]].  He died at Lake Minnetonka, July 2, 1921, and was buried in [[Watertown, South Dakota]].</ref> [[Lake Minnetonka]], [[Minnesota]] - started 2 games at right tackle, 2 games at left tackle, 1 game at right guard. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Mowery [sic], the other candidate for tackle, weighs 187 pounds and is a strong active player.  He tackles well and follows the ball with as much speed as the backs.  Murphy is particularly well pleased with this player and considers him a gret find.\"\n*William W. Pearson,<ref>William Wilson Pearson later lived in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].  He served as a Professor of Ophthalmology and Dean of the College of Medicine at the Drake University.</ref>  [[Springfield, Illinois]] - started 6 games at left tackle. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Pearson, left tackle, is the best rusher the college has seen for many years.  He weighs 192 pounds and is very powerful, often carrying two or three men on his back in some of his rushes.  When given the ball Pearson usually makes a gain.  He plays third base on the nine and is a good example of an all-around athlete.  He is quick on his feet and a hard man to stop.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Hiram Powers, [[Buffalo, New York]] - started 4 games at left end, 1 game at right end, 1 game at left tackle. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Powers has played a good game at right end thus far and seems sure of his position.  He follows the ball closely, tackles well and plays a hard game for his weight, which is 145 pounds.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Charles Frederick Rittinger - started 3 games at left halfback, 1 game at right halfback.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Possibly the greatest find of the season is Rittenger [sic], another of Murphy's discoveries.  He is trying for half back, and seems sure of the place on the eleven. He weighs 173 pounds and excels in running the ball and bucking the rush line.\"<ref name=BTL/>  Rittinger was a school principal in [[Okemos, Michigan]], before enrolling at Michigan's Law Department in 1881.  He was injured during an 1891 game against Cornell.  Several months later, \"hemorrhages set in, and the injury proved to be a vital one.\"  He died August 21, 1893, at [[Cass City, Michigan]], at age 24. The ''Speculum'' wrote: \"In many respects Mr. Rittinger was a superior character, and gave promise of becoming a star among men.  In intellectual vigor he ranked high.  His generosity was unbounded.  The qualities with this impetuosity and fiery zeal enabled him to subdue difficulties and laugh at all possibilities.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Scroll of Phi Delta Theta, Volume 18|publisher=Phi Delta Theta Fraternity|page=438|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y-MSAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false| accessdate= 5 July 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n*[[Roger Sherman (American football)|Roger Sherman]], [[Chicago, Illinois]] - started 8 games at quarterback, 1 game at right end. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Roger Sherman, at quarter, is as good a man for the position as the university has seen for many years.  Although the lightest man on the eleven he plays a strong game and finishes well.  He tackles cleverly and is usually sure of his man.  His passing is accurate and he falls on the ball better than any man on the team.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n* [[Charles Thomas (American football)|Charles L. Thomas]], [[Omaha, Nebraska]] - started 6 games at right guard, 1 game at left guard, and 1 game at left tackle.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Thomas has also been playing tackle and has played his position well, although not up to his standard, as he is well built, weighs 183, and is a good man for the line.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*[[Virgil Tupper]], [[Bay City, Michigan]] - started 6 games at left guard, 1 game at right guard, 1 game at right tackle.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Tupper will play right guard ... Tupper weighs 194 pounds and is very owerful.  He runs well and follows the ball closely.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*[[James Van Inwagen]] - started 8 games at halfback, 1 game at fullback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Van Inwagen, the captain, received his foot ball education at Exeter, N.H., ...  He weighs 160 pounds, is a speedy runner (the fastest man on the eleven) and plays a brilliant, showy game.  His opponents give him credit for being the hardest man to tackle on the team.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n* Edward Dana Wickes,<ref>Wickes was born March 11, 1870.  He later became an electrical engineer and lived in Columbus, Ohio, and Chicago.</ref> [[Helena, Montana]] - started 3 games at center, 1 game at left guard, 1 game at right guard. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Wickes, left guard, weighs 186 pounds and is playing a good game.  He is very aggressive and keeps his man moving most of the time.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n\n===Substitutes===\nThe following players are recorded as substitutes for the 1891 football team, according to University of Michigan records.<ref name=Roster/>\n* Berry - substitute, [[Howard, Ohio]]\n*[[Frank Crawford]], [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]] - started 1 game at right end, 1 game at left halfback.  The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Crawford, left end, weighs 146 pounds, but plays a hard game from the start.  He is a good runner and tackler, and is very slippery.  He is quick to take advantage of an opening and makes some very good runs.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Edward Paul De Pont,<ref>DePont was the son of a professor and the registrar at the University of Michigan, Paul Rousseau Bellon de Pont.  He was later a salesman for a spice company in Toledo.</ref> [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] - started 2 games at fullback.\n*[[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]], [[Bay City, Michigan]] - started 1 game at fullback. The ''Detroit Free Press'' wrote, \"Duffy is too well known to need further introduction to the average reader who follows athletics on the field or track.  He is a brilliant runner, a sure tackler and altogether a very desirable half-back.  His kicking is his specialty, however, and in this line he has never been excelled.\"<ref name=BTL/>\n*Willard Wilmer Griffin, [[Wenona, Illinois]] - substitute guard.\n*Charles Wilson Southworth,<ref>Southworth later attended the University of Buffalo Department of Medicine and practiced medicine in [[Salem, Oregon]].  He died January 17, 1924, at age 53.</ref> [[Forestville, New York]] - substitute end.\n\n===Coaching staff===\n* Head coach: [[Frank Crawford]]<ref name=t91/>\n* Trainer: [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]]<ref name=t91/>\n* Manager: [[Royal T. Farrand]]<ref name=t91/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm 1891 Football Team -- Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan Athletics History]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=VEHiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false The Yellow and Blue, 1891-1892]\n\n{{Michigan Wolverines football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1891 college football season|Michigan]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football seasons]]\n[[Category:1891 in sports in Michigan|Michigan Football]]\n[[Category:1890s in Detroit]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1891_Michigan_Wolverines_football_team"}
{"title_page": "Wilkes University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name         = Wilkes University\n| image        = Wilkes_University_Seal_Blue.png\n| image_size   = 150px\n| motto        = \"Unity Amidst Diversity\"\n| established  = 1933\n| type         = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment    = $44.6 million<ref>{{cite web| title = Institutions By Total Assets| work = 2007 NACUBO Endowment Study| publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers| year = 2008| url = http://www.nacubo.org/Images/All%20Institutions%20Listed%20by%20FY%202007%20Market%20Value%20of%20Endowment%20Assets_2007%20NES.pdf| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216022244/http://www.nacubo.org/Images/All%20Institutions%20Listed%20by%20FY%202007%20Market%20Value%20of%20Endowment%20Assets_2007%20NES.pdf| url-status = dead| archive-date = 2008-02-16| accessdate = 2008-01-24}}</ref>\n| president    = Paul S. Adams, PhD (Interim) / Greg Cant, PhD (as of 06/15/20)\n| provost      = Terese Wignot, PhD (Interim)\n| undergrad    = 2,245\n| postgrad     = 2,254\n| address      = 84 West South Street\n| city         = [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Wilkes-Barre]]\n| state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = 35 [[acres]]; [[Urban area|Urban]]\n| former_names = [[Bucknell University|Bucknell]] Junior College\n| athletics    = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] \u2013 [[Middle Atlantic Conferences|MAC]] [[MAC Freedom Conference|Freedom Conference]]\n| nickname     = [http://www.gowilkesu.com Colonels]\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.wilkes.edu/}}\n| logo         = Wilkes University Seal Horizontal Blue.png\n| faculty      = 157 Full Time<ref name=\"factbook\">{{cite book| title = 2010-2011 Fact Book| publisher = Wilkes University| date = November 2010| url = http://www.wilkes.edu/Include/Fact%20Book%202010-11%20with%20cover.pdf| accessdate = 2011-07-24| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110816190315/http://www.wilkes.edu/Include/Fact%20Book%202010-11%20with%20cover.pdf| archive-date = 2011-08-16| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n| coordinates  = {{coord|41|14|36|N|75|53|27|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| colors       = Blue and Gold {{color box|blue}}&nbsp;{{color box|gold}}\n}}\n\n'''Wilkes University''' is a [[Private university|private]] university in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]. It has over 2,200 undergraduates and over 2,200 graduate students (both full and part-time).<ref name=\"factbook\" /> Wilkes was founded in 1933 as a satellite campus of [[Bucknell University]],<ref name=\"lit.blogs.bucknell.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://lit.blogs.bucknell.edu/2017/10/12/from-special-collectionsuniversity-archives-bucknell-junior-college/|title=From Special Collections/University Archives: Bucknell Junior College \u00ab Library and Information Technology|website=Bucknell Blogs}}</ref> and became an independent institution in 1947, naming itself Wilkes College, after English radical politician [[John Wilkes]] after whom Wilkes-Barre is named.<ref name=Castrignano>{{cite book| last=Castrignano| first=Elena| date=2012| title=Wilkes-Barre| location=Charleston, South Carolina| publisher=Arcadia Publishing| page=64| isbn=9780738555300}}</ref> The school was granted university status in January 1990.<ref name=patriot>{{cite news| agency=Associated Press| date=25 October 1989| newspaper= The Patriot| publisher=Patriot News Company| location= Pennsylvania}}</ref> It is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"Doctoral/Professional Universities\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.wilkes.edu/2019/01/17/wilkes-university-granted-doctoral-university-designation/|title=Wilkes University Granted Doctoral University Designation \u2013 Wilkes News|first=Sarah|last=Bedford|publisher=}}</ref>  Wilkes University is accredited by the Commission on Higher Education of the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/bulletin/current/undergraduate/introduction/academic-matters/Accreditation.aspx|title=Accreditation - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe school mascot, which was suggested by Wilkes student Joe Pringle (class of 1949),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poconorecord.com/article/20121201/NEWS90/212010322|title=How Wilkes Univ. got its colonel|first=BILL|last=O'BOYLE|website=poconorecord.com}}</ref> is a Colonel and the official colors are blue and yellow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesleader.com/stories/A-legend-among-Colonels,235456?search_filter=Wilkes+colonel&town_id=1&sub_type=stories/|title=A Legend Among Colonels|publisher=Wilkes-Barre Times Leader|accessdate=2012-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915052035/http://www.timesleader.com/stories/A-legend-among-Colonels,235456?search_filter=Wilkes+colonel&town_id=1&sub_type=stories%2F|archive-date=2014-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The campus symbol is a letter \"W\" known as the \"flying W\" by students and alumni.\n\n==History==\nWilkes University was first established in 1933 by [[Bucknell University]] under the name Bucknell University Junior College (BUJC) in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Wilkes-Barre]].<ref name=bucknell.edu>{{cite web| url=https://www.bucknell.edu/interested-in-bucknell/who-we-are/history-and-traditions/milestones/a-history-of-achievement.html| title=A History of Achievement| publisher=Bucknell University| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Frank G. Davis, chair of the Education department at Bucknell, first developed the idea of BUJC and served as an early liaison between BUJC and Bucknell.<ref name=\":0\" /> BUJC attracted many students who were the first members of their families to benefit from higher education as the need for junior colleges arose in urban areas.<ref name=Castrignano /> The college opened in downtown Wilkes-Barre, where the first classes were held on the third floor of the Wilkes-Barre Business College building.<ref name=Castrignano />  By 1934, the business college moved out of the building and BUJC had taken it over and continued to grow over the years, acquiring old mansions for student housing, classrooms, and administration offices along the streets of South River and South Franklin.<ref name=Castrignano /> By 1945, the Board of Trustees formally moved to develop the junior college into a four-year institution.<ref name=wilkes.edu>{{cite web| url=http://wilkes.edu/pages/140.asp| title=Wilkes History| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030538/http://wilkes.edu/pages/140.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, Wilkes College was instituted as an independent, nondenominational four-year college, with programs in the arts, sciences, and a number of professional fields, as well as numerous extracurricular activities.<ref name=bucknell.edu /> The student body in the postwar period was primarily composed of Luzerne County residents, especially G.I. bill recipients.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Wilkes University Historical Atlas|last=Cox|first=Harold|publisher=Wilkes University|year=1994|isbn=|location=Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|pages=}}</ref> In the 1950s, increasing numbers of students elected to live on campus, which led to a rapid expansion in on-campus student housing.  Increased federal funding for science and engineering in the 1950s led the college to develop academic programs in those areas, build the Stark Learning Center, and increase enrollment.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWilkes College became Wilkes University in December 1989, and the school officially received university status a month later, in January 1990.<ref name=\"patriot\" /><ref name=\"wilkes.edu\" />\n\nWilkes University opened the School of Pharmacy in 1996,<ref name=pharmacist>{{cite web| url=http://www.pharmacist.com/school-pharmacy-profile-wilkes-university-nesbitt-college-pharmacy-and-nursing| title=School of Pharmacy Profile: Wilkes University Nesbitt College of Pharmacy and Nursing| author=Julie L. Olenak| date=9 July 2012| publisher=American Pharmacists Association| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> and in 1999, through a donation from Mrs. Geraldine Nesbitt Orr, the Nesbitt School of Pharmacy was established.<ref name=wilkes.edu /> The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business & Leadership was created in 2004, and the following year, the Henry Student Center was expanded and the university purchased an 80,000-square-foot (7,400 m2) building in downtown Wilkes-Barre.<ref name=wilkes.edu /> The University Center on Main (Ucom) building houses the Sidhu School of Business and Leadership, an [[indoor track]] and field, and [[ropes course]].\n\nBy 2014, Wilkes University grew to include eight academic buildings, 20 residence halls, nine administrative buildings, and other facilities such as the Eugene S. Farley Library, the Henry Student Center, and athletic complexes.<ref name=wufastfacts>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/141.asp| title=Fast Facts| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916104005/http://wilkes.edu/pages/141.asp| archivedate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Presidents of Wilkes University===\n*'''Eugene S. Farley''', 1936\u201370           \u2192Chief Administrative Officer of Wilkes precursor [[Bucknell University]] Junior College<ref name=\"lit.blogs.bucknell.edu\"/> and Wilkes University first president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/18/archives/dr-eugene-farley-led-wilkes-college.html|title=Dr. Eugene Farley, Led Wilkes College|date=18 September 1973|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Wilkes' first holder of Chancellor/Honorary President title upon retirement. \n*'''Francis J. Michelini''', 1970\u201375       \u2192First president to ascend from the academic ranks, after serving as Wilkes biology faculty and then academic dean.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/news/2015/November/wilkes-university-dedicates-building-honoring-second-president.aspx|title=Wilkes University Dedicates Building Honoring Its Second President Francis J. Michelini - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  Resigned to become President of Pennsylvania Commission on Independent Colleges and Universities.<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 40225019|title = Academic Freedom and Tenure: Wilkes College (Pennsylvania)|journal = AAUP Bulletin|volume = 63|issue = 2|pages = 88\u201393|year = 1977}}</ref>\n*'''Robert S. Capin''' '50* H'83; 1975\u201384  \u2192*First university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/dr_robert_s_capin/|title=- Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  Wilkes first holder of President Emeritus title upon retirement as president and returning to the business faculty.\n*'''Christopher N. Breiseth''', 1984-2001<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/campus-life/student-affairs/commencement/past-ceremonies/past-speakers/christopher-n-breiseth.aspx|title=2014 Graduate Commencement Speaker - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  \u2192Retired to accept position as founding President and CEO of Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.francesperkinscenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/The-Frances-Perkins-I-Knew-by-Christopher-Breiseth.pdf |title=The Frances Perkins I Knew |last=Breiseth |first=Christopher |date=1966 |website=blog.francesperkinscenter.org |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Joseph \"Tim\" E. Gilmour''', 2001-2012  \u2192Currently serves on team of Strategic Initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategicinitiatives.com/team|title=Our Team - Strategic Initiatives|website=www.strategicinitiatives.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Patrick F. Leahy]]''', 2012\u20132019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/leadership/presidents-office/biography.aspx|title=Dr. Patrick F. Leahy Biography - Wilkes University|website=wilkes.edu}}</ref> \u2192Resigned effective July 31, 2019 to accept Presidency of [[Monmouth University]] in Monmouth, New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monmouth.edu/news/monmouth-university-names-patrick-f-leahy-10th-president/|title=Monmouth University Names Patrick F. Leahy 10th President - News - Monmouth University|first=Monmouth University 400 Cedar AvenueWest Long|last=BranchNJ07764732.571.3400|date=14 December 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''Alan Gregory \"Greg\" Cant''', 2020\u2013 <ref>https://www.wilkes.edu/news/2019/December/wilkes_university_names_seventh_president.aspx</ref> \u2192First president, born in Australia, to bring international experience to the position.\n\n===Interim Presidents of Wilkes University===\n*'''Robert S. Capin''' '50* H'83; 1974    \u2192*First university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>  Promoted to President 1975.  Wilkes first holder of President Emeritus title upon retirement as president and return to the business faculty.\n*'''Paul S. Adams''' '77, '82*; 2019-2020      \u2192*Second university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity and first to ascend from the student affairs division.<ref name=\"timesleader.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesleader.com/news/734889/wilkes-university-names-paul-adams-as-interim-president-beginning-aug-1|title=Wilkes University names Paul Adams as interim president beginning Aug. 1|last=timesleader|date=28 February 2019|website=Times Leader}}</ref>\n\n===Dean of Students of Wilkes University===\n*'''George F. Ralston''' (formerly Dean of Men) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/wilkes-magazine/_assets/Fall_2007/WilkesFall2007.pdf |title=Cover |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Arthur J. Hoover''' '55 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/24539991/arthur_hoover_son_of_mrs_marcella/|title=Arthur Hoover, son of Mrs Marcella Hoover named to New Wilkes Post- 1965|website=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n*'''Jane K. Lampe-Groh''' (formerly Dean of Women) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/citizensvoice/obituary.aspx?n=jane-lampe-groh&pid=174826408 |title=Jane Groh Obituary - Wilkes Barre, PA &#124; Citizens Voice |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Paul S. Adams''' '77, '82 <ref name=\"timesleader.com\"/>\n*'''Mark R. Allen''' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/campus-directory/mark.allen.aspx|title=- Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Academic buildings===\nMost of the academic buildings are located within the same city block, between South River Street, South Franklin Street, South Street, and Northampton Street. The Stark Learning Center (SLC), located on South River Street, is the largest building on campus with 220,000 square feet housing classrooms, laboratories, and office space.<ref name=wilkes-stark>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/239.asp| title=Stark Learning Center| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030621/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/239.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The facility consists of nursing, math and engineering offices and classrooms.<ref name=wilkes-stark />  Stark Learning Center received extensive renovation in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesleader.mycapture.com/mycapture/folder.asp?event=2208240&CategoryID=26411|title=Wilkes University Renovations - News - Times Leader|website=timesleader.mycapture.com|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvJpoJiA0BE|title=New Stark Learning Center Labs Sneak Peek!|last=WilkesUVideo|date=28 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=5 October 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2017/09/13/stark-learning-center-construction-updates/|title=Stark Learning Center construction updates|first=Cabrini|last=Rudnicki|publisher=|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nClassrooms and offices for humanities and social sciences are located in Breiseth Hall, a three-story building located on South Franklin Street, in the same block as SLC. Kirby Hall, a mansion formerly home to Fred Morgan Kirby, was renovated to house offices and classrooms for English.<ref name=wilkes-kirby>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/225.asp| title=Kirby Hall| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050555/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/225.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Cohen Science Center, a $35 million project, was established to house the biology and health sciences, chemistry and biochemistry, and environmental engineering and earth sciences departments.<ref name=timesleader1>{{cite web| url=http://timesleader.com/news/local-news-news/1236395/Wilkes-University-buys-Bartikowsky-building| title=Wilkes University buys Bartikowsky building| author=Andrew M. Seder| date=5 March 2014| publisher=Times Leader| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025225/http://timesleader.com/news/local-news-news/1236395/Wilkes-University-buys-Bartikowsky-building| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=wnep>{{cite web| url=http://wnep.com/2013/10/04/a-look-inside-wilkes-new-science-center/| title=A Look Inside Wilkes' New Science Center| author=Lara Greenberg| date=4 October 2013| publisher=16 WNEP News Station| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The facility has been built to [[LEED silver]] standards for environmental sustainability and allows for students to monitor energy use, water use, and general building performance to aid sustainability studies.<ref name=wilkes-cohen>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/cohen| title=Cohen Science Center Multimedia| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The building also features a rooftop vegetation area for greenhouse purposes and to assist in reducing rain runoff.<ref name=wilkes-cohen />\n\n===University Center on Main===\nIn 2005, the university acquired the former Wilkes-Barre Call Center building and parking garage on South Main Street.<ref name=timestrib>{{cite web| url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/business/colleges-push-into-area-s-downtowns-a-trend-seen-elsewhere-1.1635177| title=Colleges push into area's downtowns, a trend seen elsewhere| author=Denise Allabaugh| date=16 February 2014| publisher=The Times Tribune| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The parking garage is currently being used for student and faculty parking. The Public Safety department has remodeled and relocated to the basement of the garage.<ref name=chamberofbusiness>{{cite web| url=http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=178| title=Wilkes University Signs Purchase Agreement with City of Wilkes-Barre for Former Call Center| date=29 June 2005| publisher=Greater Wilkes-Barre Chamber of Business and Industry| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050551/http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=178| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Call Center building was renovated and renamed University Center on Main.<ref name=timestrib /> The building now houses recreation facilities including tennis and basketball courts, and a rock climbing wall.<ref name=bdcnetwork>{{cite web| url=http://www.bdcnetwork.com/student-center-opens-campus-wilkes-university| title=Student center opens on the campus of Wilkes University| date=11 August 2010| publisher=Building Design & Construction| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In summer 2014, the building was renovated to also house the Sidhu School of Business and Leadership.\n\n===Residence halls===\nThe campus offers seventeen different residence halls and apartment buildings for all levels of students, although some apartments are reserved for upperclassmen.<ref name=\"residence_halls\">{{cite web| title = Wilkes Residence Halls| publisher = Wilkes University| url = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp| accessdate = 2007-01-04| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093004/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp| archive-date = 2006-12-30| url-status = dead}}</ref> Many residence halls are located in 19th century mansions that were donated to the university, or other houses purchased by the university. Over 11 mansion and house style residence halls are used throughout the campus.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> Apartment style residences are found in University Towers and Rifkin Hall.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> Non-apartment residence halls include Catlin Hall, Doane Hall, Evans Hall, Fortinsky Halls, Passan Hall, Ross Hall, Roth Hall, Schiowitz Hall, Sterling Hall, Sturdevant Hall, Sullivan Hall, University Towers, Waller Halls (North and South), and Weiss Hall.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> First year and second year students are required to live in residence halls (unless he or she is a commuter), and can live off-campus starting their third year.<ref name=undergradhb>{{cite web| url=http://wilkes.edu/PDFFiles/StudentHandbook/Undergrad_Handbook_2012_2013_Upd081012.pdf| title=Wilkes University Student Handbook| date=2013\u20132014| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401164836/http://wilkes.edu/PDFFiles/StudentHandbook/Undergrad_Handbook_2012_2013_Upd081012.pdf| archive-date=2014-04-01| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTraditional [[dormitory]] housing is provided at Evans Residence Hall. With four floors and about 200 students, Evans Residence Hall is the largest first-year student residential hall on the Wilkes University campus. Renovated in 2008, Chesapeake and Delaware Residence Halls were re-dedicated as Lawrence W. Roth Residence Hall, a residential hall connecting the previously separate Chesapeake and Delaware Residence Halls. It is a first year student, non-traditional residential hall house with about seventy residents and three RAs. Students living on campus have access to laundry facilities, basic cable, and local phone service.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" />\n\nThe university purchased the University Towers apartment complex located at 10 East South Street from a private real estate company for $8.1 million. Approximately 400 students are housed in this building's 130 units.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Campus Housing\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |date         = 2013-01-18\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp\n |access-date  = 2007-01-04\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093004/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> Part of the nearby YMCA building has been renovated into apartment style residences and houses upperclassman.<ref name=wilkes-ymca>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/265.asp| title=YMCA Building| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722203949/http://wilkes.edu/pages/265.asp| archive-date=2014-07-22| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=citizensvoice1>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/ymca-renovations-will-expand-w-b-facility-s-residential-areas-1.1135404| title=YMCA renovations will expand W-B facility's residential areas| author=Andrew Staub| date=21 April 2011| publisher=The Citizen's Voice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The apartments are known as 40 West.<ref name=wilkes-ymca />\n\n===Bookstore===\nThe university partnered with neighboring [[King's College, Pennsylvania|King's College]] to operate a joint for-profit bookstore in downtown [[Wilkes-Barre]].<ref name=beacon2012>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2012/09/25/students-partaking-in-city-activities-helps-economy/| title=Students' partaking in city activities helps economy | author=Amanda Leonard| date=25 September 2012| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The new bookstore opened in October 2006, consolidating two independent bookstores into one new facility.<ref name=beacon2012 /><ref name=chamberofbusiness2>{{cite web| url=http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=339| title=BARNES AND NOBLE SIGNS AGREEMENT TO BRING BOOK STORE TO INNOVATION CENTER @ WILKES-BARRE| date=31 July 2006| publisher=Greater Wilkes-Barre Chamber of Business and Industry| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030458/http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=339| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The new bookstore, run by [[Barnes & Noble College Booksellers]], is located in the basement and first floor of the Innovation Center on South Main Street.<ref name=chamberofbusiness2 /> The bookstore includes a full selection of general trade books, a full-service [[Starbucks]] cafe, lounges and study areas, and a spirit shop featuring products from both Wilkes and King's College.<ref name=chamberofbusiness2 />\n\n=== Karambelas Media and Communications Center ===\nIn August 2017, the university dedicated the newly renovated Bartikowsky Jewelers building as the Karambelas Media and Communications Center. It houses [[WCLH|WCLH 90.7 FM]] (the university radio station), the Beacon newspaper, Zebra Communications (a student-run public relations agency)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesleader.com/news/673600/preview-tour-of-new-wilkes-media-center|title=New $4 million media center a 'jewel' at Wilkes University - Times Leader|website=www.timesleader.com|access-date=2018-02-01|date=2017-08-29}}</ref> and the Sordoni Art Gallery.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/lifestyles/revamped-wilkes-gallery-opens-with-warhol-exhibit-1.2250325|title=Revamped Wilkes gallery opens with Warhol exhibit|last=Jacobson|first=Charlotte L.|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Dorothy Dickson Darte Center for the Performing Arts ===\nThe Darte Center is the home of performing arts at Wilkes University. Built in 1965 to replace the Chase Theater (a converted carriage house),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Wilkes Theater Marks 20th Birthday: Benefactor Dorothy Dickson Darte Saluted|last=Roccograndi|first=Betty|date=October 23, 1985|work=The Times Leader|access-date=}}</ref> it includes the Darling Theater, which seats 478, a black box theater which seats 48, and a two-story music building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/campus/buildings-academic-administrative/darte-center.aspx|title=Darte Center - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> The land on which the Darte Center sits was donated by the Wyoming Valley Society of Arts and Sciences. The building was financed by an anonymous donation of $1 million by Dorothy Dickson Darte and dedicated in her honor after her death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Eugene Shedden Farley Library ===\nIn 1968, Wilkes College dedicated the newly constructed Eugene Shedden Farley Library and named it after the college's first president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/campus/buildings-academic-administrative/farley-library/index.aspx|title=Farley Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The library initially contained four special collection rooms - dedicated to [[Harold Rainsford Stark|Admiral Harold Stark]], Eleanor C. Farley, Gilbert McClintock, and Wyoming Valley residents of Polish heritage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/academics/archives/_archives/wilkes-beacon/WB28E.7.pdf|title=Convocation Set Tonight to Honor Wilkes President|last=|first=|date=November 1, 1968|work=The Beacon|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Polish room was designed by Stefan Mrozewski in the [[Zakopane Style]], and Stefan Hellersperk carved the furniture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/academics/library/about-us/the-polish-room/index.aspx|title=The Polish Room|last=|first=|date=|website=Wilkes University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/top-stories/2013/11/19/polish-room-keeps-heritage-tradition-alive/|title=Polish Room: Keeps heritage, tradition alive|last=Stencavage|first=Alyssa|website=The Beacon|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>  The first Norman Mailer Room was dedicated in 2000,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/wilkes-magazine/_assets/Spring_2008/WilkesSpring2008.pdf|title=Remembering Normal Mailer, 1923-2007|last=Lennon|first=Michael J.|date=2008|work=Wilkes Magazine|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|month=|issue=Spring|page=26}}</ref> and the second Norman Mailer Room and Collection were dedicated in October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://susanmailer.com/2019/11/10/susan-interviewed-on-art-scene/|title=Susan Interviewed on Art Scene|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2019|website=Susan Mailer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> The Harold Cox Archives room, which houses the Wilkes University Archives, was dedicated in 2004 and 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/academics/library/about-us/index.aspx|title=About E.S. Farley Library - Wilkes University in PA - Wilkes University|website=wilkes.edu|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citizensvoice.com/news/archivist-s-name-now-part-of-wilkes-history-1.1539911|title=Archivist's name now part of Wilkes history|last=Writer)|first=By Michael P. Buffer (Staff|website=www.citizensvoice.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> As of 2019, the library contained 200,000 books and bound journals, 75,000 electronic journals, and 430 newspaper and journal subscriptions, as well as circulating technology like ipads and laptops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.wilkes.edu/2019/02/06/library-lovers-month-ten-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-farley-library/|title=Library Lovers Month: Ten Things You Didn\u2019t Know About the Farley Library|last=Mayk|first=Vicki|date=2019-02-06|website=Wilkes News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nWilkes University has a 14 to one student to faculty ratio and with over 50 percent of classes having fewer than 20 students per class.<ref name=usnews>{{cite web| url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/wilkes-university-3394| title=Wilkes University| publisher=U.S. News and World Report| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university is accredited by the [[Middle State Association of Colleges and Schools]] and has also received accreditation from various professional accreditation associations for individual degree plans.<ref name=collegebluebook>{{cite journal| title=Wilkes University: Tabular Data.\" The College Blue Book. 36th ed. Vol. 2: Tabular Data| date=2009| publisher=Macmillan Reference USA| journal=College Bluebook}}</ref> The university offers majors in science, education, engineering, business, and liberal arts for undergraduate and graduate students.<ref name=undergrad>{{cite web\n |title        = Undergraduate Majors and Minors at Wilkes University\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/143.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-12\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093049/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/143.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> The academic programs at Wilkes University are divided among seven schools:<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Wilkes Colleges\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/299.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-04\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093114/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/299.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=beacon2013>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2013/11/04/honors-college-option-for-growth/| title=Honors college option for growth| author=Nicole Zukowski| date=4 November 2013| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n*College of Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences\n*College of Science and Engineering\n*Nesbitt School of Pharmacy\n*Passan School of Nursing\n*Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership\n*The School of Education \n*University College\n\nThe College of Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences includes six departments including behavioral and social sciences and performing arts.<ref name=undergrad /> One of the largest colleges is the College of Science and Engineering which has seven departments and divisions that encompass a wide range of majors and minors.<ref name=undergrad /> The College of Science and Engineering program in Electrical Engineering, Environmental Engineering, and Mechanical Engineering are accredited by the Engineering Accreditation Commission (EAC) of the Accreditation Board of Engineering and Technology (ABET).<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  The school's Nesbitt School of Pharmacy is one of seven pharmacy schools in Pennsylvania.<ref name=pharmchoice>{{cite web| url=http://www.pharmacychoice.com/education/pharmschools/pa.cfm| title=U.S. News and World Report 2008 Pharmacy Schools rankings| date=2008| publisher=Pharmacy Choice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The school is fully accredited by the Accreditation Council for Pharmacy Education.<ref name=uspharm>{{cite web| url=http://www.uspharmd.com/school/pharmacy/wilkes_university/| title=Wilkes University \u2013 Online Pharmacy & Pharmacy Technician Degrees| publisher=USPharmD| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The Passan School of Nursing undergraduate baccalaureate program in Nursing is approved by the Pennsylvania State Board of Nurse Examiners and is accredited by the Commission on Collegiate Nursing Education.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership has several business degree plans and includes one of the most popular undergraduate majors, management.<ref name=princetonreview>{{cite web| url=http://www.princetonreview.com/WilkesUniversity.aspx| title=Wilkes University| publisher=Princeton Review| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>  Select undergraduate programs of the Sidhu School are accredited by the Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/bulletin/current/undergraduate/schools-colleges/the-jay-s-sidhu-school-of-business-and-leadership/index.aspx|title=The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate studies===\nWilkes University offers over a dozen programs within its graduate school programs.<ref name=undergrad /> The Wilkes Graduate Teacher Education Program hosts classes online and at classroom sites across [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | vauthors = \n  | title = Graduate Teacher Education Schedule of Courses Spring 2007\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url = http://static4.mathcs.wilkes.edu/scheds/coursessp07grd.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2007-01-04 }}</ref> Some of the Wilkes Graduate Teacher Education programs are hosted entirely online. Other graduate programs such as nursing, creative writing, and bioengineering are also offered at the university.<ref name=undergrad /> The MBA program within the Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership was ranked among the top ten MBA programs in the state of Pennsylvania.<ref name=cpbj>{{cite web| url=http://www.cpbj.com/article/20140314/AWARDS/140319813/MBA-Programs:-Jay-S-Sidhu-School-of-Business-and-Leadership| title=#8 Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership| date=2014| publisher=Central Penn Business Journal| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Clubs and organizations===\nNumerous student-run clubs are recognized and funded by the student government. Many of the clubs are athletically focused, representing sports including [[crew]], [[lacrosse]], [[running]], [[skiing]], [[volleyball]], and [[ultimate frisbee]]. Clubs associated with academics and majors represent [[psychology]], [[sociology]], [[criminology]], and pre-[[pharmacy]]. Other clubs are formed around common interests such as animal advocacy, [[vegetarianism]], [[anime]], and [[robotics]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Wilkes Clubs & Organizations\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/134.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-17\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093309/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/134.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nWilkes has an active student media, including a television station within the Karambelas Media and Communications Center, FM radio station [[WCLH]], which celebrated its 45th anniversary in 2017, weekly newspaper ''The Beacon'', a literary magazine ''Manuscript'', which celebrated its 70th anniversary in 2017, and yearbook ''Amnicola'', which will celebrate its 70th anniversary in 2018. The university's newspaper was originally published as the ''Bison Stampede'' in 1934.<ref name=beacon2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/top-stories/2014/01/30/eight-decades-of-covering-the-campus/| title=Eight decades of covering the campus| author=Christine Lee| date=30 January 2014| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The publication was later renamed ''The Beacon'', and the paper celebrated its 85th anniversary in 2019.<ref name=beacon2014 />\n\nWilkes University Programming Board, an entertainment and event planning organization, has hosted events that featured Pennsylvania based bands such as [[Live (band)|Live]] and [[Fuel (band)|Fuel]], and national favorites including [[Alanis Morissette]], [[Rusted Root]], [[Joan Osborne]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Hoobastank]], [[Jack's Mannequin]], and [[Billy Joel]].<ref name=wilkes-pb>{{cite web |url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/2838.asp?item=61938 |title=Wilkes Event Details |publisher=Wilkes.edu |date=2011-03-18 |accessdate=2011-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929120819/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/2838.asp?item=61938 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWilkes University launched the first collegiate [[marching band]] in the northeast Pennsylvania region in 2014.<ref name=citizensvoice2>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/wilkes-to-start-region-s-first-collegiate-marching-band-1.1583010| title=Wilkes to start region's first collegiate marching band| author=Matt Bufano| date=10 November 2013| publisher=The Citizen's Voice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university said that the new marching band will be a welcomed new tradition and it will contribute to a growth in school spirit.<ref name=citizensvoice2 />\n\n===Student Government===\nThe Student Government organization at Wilkes hosts many annual events for undergraduates such as Homecoming and Winter Weekend, an annual themed weekend event in which teams of students participate in various competitive challenges such as team skits and eating contests.<ref name=wilkes-sg>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/345.asp| title=Student Government| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025615/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/345.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=salvato>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2013/02/05/winter-weekend-is-near/| title=Winter Weekend is near| author=Julianna Salvato| date=5 February 2013| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The Wilkes Student Government also coordinates all the other university organizations and clubs by formulating student activity budgets and reviewing fund requests.<ref name=wilkes-sg /> The organization is composed of various executive positions and councils including the president, presidents of Commuter Council, Inter-residence Hall Council, representatives, and a president from each class.<ref name=wilkes-sg />\n\n===ROTC Program===\nDetachment 752 of the [[Air Force Reserve Officer Training Corps]] is located at Wilkes University. Established in 1973, AF ROTC Detachment 752 has trained and prepared hundreds of young men and women for future careers as USAF officers.<ref name=wilkes-airforce>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/319.asp| title=Air Force ROTC| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030835/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/319.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> Wilkes also offers Army ROTC, but the classes are held at nearby [[King's College (Pennsylvania)|King's College]].<ref name=wilkes-army>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/1653.asp| title=Army ROTC| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025413/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/1653.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> When students graduate from Wilkes and complete the ROTC program, they earn a commission as an officer in their respective military branches.<ref name=wilkes-airforce /><ref name=wilkes-army /> The detachment serves 12 other crosstown colleges and universities in Northeast Pennsylvania.\n\n===Athletics===\nThe Wilkes University Colonels compete in [[NCAA Division III]] athletics.<ref name=ncaawilkes>{{cite web| url=https://www.ncaa.com/schools/wilkes| title=Wilkes University| publisher=NCAA| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university is a member of the [[Middle Atlantic Conference]] (MAC). Wilkes offers numerous intercollegiate sports team organizations at the university. Wilkes men's intercollegiate sports teams include baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming, tennis and wrestling. Wilkes women's intercollegiate sports teams include basketball, cross country, field hockey, golf, lacrosse, soccer, softball, swimming, tennis, and volleyball.\n\n====Men's conference titles====\nIn 2007, the Wilkes University baseball team was the MAC Freedom Conference champion.<ref name=mac-baseball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/BSB_0527142408.aspx?path=baseball| title=Baseball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Prior to that, the baseball team had been conference champion in 1994 and 1977.<ref name=mac-baseball />\n\nIn the 2007-2008 men's basketball season, the Wilkes men's team went 13-12 overall and finished fourth in the conference. Previously, the men's basketball team was Freedom Conference champion for the 2000-2001 season, 1998-99 season, 1997-98 season, and 1995-96 season.<ref name=mac-basketball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/MBB_0527144152.aspx?path=mbball| title=Men's Basketball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilkes University football team was the MAC champion for the 2006 season, and previously, the football team had been conference champion in 1993 and 1974.<ref name=mac-football>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/FB_0527143400.aspx?path=football| title=Football Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In the mid 1960s the Wilkes College football program had 32 straight wins\u2014the fourth longest streak in college football history at the time.<ref name=citizensvoice3>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/sports/wilkes-football-1965-69-1.1422845| title=WILKES FOOTBALL 1965-69| author=Neil Corbett| date=30 December 2012}}</ref> It began in the fourth game of the 1965 season and ended in 1969. From a 34-0 victory over Ursinus to a 13-7 loss to Ithaca. Rollie Schmidt coached the Colonels from 1962-81. His teams went 90-73-1 winning five MAC titles, two Lambert Bowls (best small college team in the East) and one Timmie Award (best small college team in the country).<ref name=citizensvoice3 />\n\nThe men's tennis team was MAC Freedom Conference champion in 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016.<ref name=mac-tennis>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/MTEN_0527145006.aspx?path=mten| title=Men's Tennis Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilkes wrestling team has won a total of 14 Middle Atlantic Conference team championships. In 1974, the team won the NCAA Div. III national championship, afterward, the Colonels moved to the NCAA Div. I ranks for 25 seasons before returning to Div. III ranks in 2000.<ref name=wilkes-wrestling>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/858.asp| title=Wilkes Wrestling History| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030602/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/858.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Women's conference titles====\nThe Wilkes University women's field hockey team was MAC champions in 2013 and 1999.<ref name=mac-fieldh>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/FH_0527142938.aspx?path=fhockey| title=Field Hockey Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In 2008 the women's field hockey team was ranked 18th in the nation by the NCAA.<ref>https://www.ncaa.com/ Retrieved 2009-03-13.</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the Wilkes women's soccer team was the MAC Freedom Conference champion.<ref name=mac-soccer>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WSOC_0527141513.aspx?path=wsoc| title=Women's Soccer Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The following year, the Wilkes women's softball team won the MAC region in 2006.<ref name=mac-softball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/SB_0527140211.aspx?path=softball| title=Softball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Prior to that, the women's softball team was the MAC champion in 1982.<ref name=mac-softball />\n\nThe women's tennis team at Wilkes was the MAC Freedom Conference champion in 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, and 2014.<ref name=mac-wt>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WTEN_0527141844.aspx?path=wten| title=Women's Tennis Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The women's volleyball team was the conference champion in 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, and 2011.<ref name=mac-volley>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WVB_0527140439.aspx?path=wvball| title=Volleyball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nWomen's golf and women's swimming, both NCAA Division III intercollegiate sports, were introduced to Wilkes University's sports roster in the 2014-15 season in the Middle Atlantic Conference.<ref name=citizensvoice2 />\n\n==Events==\n\n===Lecture series===\nThe university sponsors and hosts academically focused lectures series for its students and community. The [[Max Rosenn]] Lecture Series in Law and Humanities was established in the 1980s, and has brought many speakers to the university including author [[Norman Mailer]], Supreme Court Justice [[John Paul Stevens]], and journalist [[Bob Woodward]].<ref>{{cite press release\n |title        = Bob Woodward to Deliver Rosenn Lecture\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |date         = Apr 7, 2006\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=9088\n |accessdate   = Jan 5, 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230100400/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=9088\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  The Allan P. Kirby Lecture in Free Enterprise and Entrepreneurship has also hosted speakers including journalist and television host [[John Stossel]], and former New York Governor [[George Pataki]].<ref name=lectureseries>{{cite web\n |title        = Allan P. Kirby Lecture Series\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4296.asp\n |accessdate   = 2011-05-31\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110929121158/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4296.asp\n |archive-date = 2011-09-29\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> The center hosts two lectures annually.<ref name=lectureseries /> The [[United Nations]] lecture series was launched in the 2011-2012 academic year and the program brings U.N. officials to the campus to speak to students throughout the year through a partnership with the Higher Education Alliance of the United Nations.<ref name=wilkes-lectures>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4308.asp| title=Other Lectures at Wilkes| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050557/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4308.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Annual High School Mathematics Contest===\nFor over 60 years Wilkes University has been the host of the Annual High School Mathematics Contest as sponsored by the Luzerne County Council of Teachers of Mathematics (LCCTM).<ref name=timesleader2>{{cite web| url=http://www.timesleader.com/stories/Math-contest-at-Wilkes-adds-up-to-scholarships,120910| title=Math contest at Wilkes adds up to scholarships| author=JANINE UNGVARSKY| date=15 February 2013| publisher=The Times Leader| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030443/http://www.timesleader.com/stories/Math-contest-at-Wilkes-adds-up-to-scholarships,120910| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> Every year juniors and seniors from Luzerne County high schools come to Wilkes University to participate in the competition. The first-place winner in both the junior and senior divisions are awarded a full-tuition scholarship to Wilkes University.<ref name=timesleader2 />\n\n===ACM Intercollegiate Programming Contest===\nThe Wilkes University Math and Computer Science Department hosts the Eastern Pennsylvania division of the Mid-Atlantic Region of the annual [[International Collegiate Programming Contest|ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest]]. Wilkes University has been host to the event for the last 5 years. A total of 8 schools host teams in the Mid-Atlantic Region.<ref name=wilkes-pc>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=55075| title=Wilkes University Is Regional Site for International Computer Programming Competition on Nov. 7| author=Vicki Mayk| date=2 November 2009| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://archive.is/20140915003336/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=55075| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The competition is sponsored by [[IBM]] and the contest challenges the participants knowledge and creativity in solving computer programming problems.<ref name=wilkes-pc />\n\n===Annual Tom Bigler High School Journalism Conference===\nAnnually, hundreds of Pennsylvania high school students attend this annual media oriented event. Each year features a notable keynote speaker, hands-on workshops in the areas of telecommunications, journalism and public relations and panel discussions and presentation from media professionals and personalities. A high school journalism contest and awards ceremony is also a main event.\n\n===Plays===\nThe Wilkes University Theatre presents a full season of dramas and musicals on the main stage as well as a season of student produced black box productions at the Darte Center.<ref name=wilkes-theater>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/3833.asp| title=Theatre Arts| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030640/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/3833.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Division of Performing Arts presents a total of four shows annually at the Darte Center.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Ann Bartuska]], Ecologist and Biologist\n*[[Jackson Berkey]], classical music composer, pianist, and singer\n*[[Marty Blake]], general manager of the [[Atlanta Hawks]] franchise<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/sports/basketball/marty-blake-nba-scout-dies-at-86.html?_r=1&| title=Marty Blake, Sharp Judge of N.B.A. Talent, Dies at 86| author=Bruce Weber| date=9 April 2013| work=New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n*[[Gabriel J. Campana]], former mayor of [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n*[[Catherine Chandler]], poet\n*[[Jesse Choper]], constitutional law scholar and former dean of the UC-Berkeley School of Law\n*[[Catherine D. DeAngelis]], first woman and the first pediatrician to become the editor of the [[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]<ref name=nytimes2>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/09/us/woman-is-named-editor-of-ama-journal.html| title=Woman Is Named Editor of A.M.A. Journal| author=LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN| date=9 October 1999| work=New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n*[[William R. Evanina]], the NCIX, the [[Office of the National Counterintelligence Executive|National Counterintelligence Executive]] of the United States, and director of the U.S. National Counterintelligence and Security Center<ref>{{Cite news|author=Bolus, Kathleen |date=29 June 2014 |title=Midvalley resident rises in the ranks of FBI |url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/midvalley-resident-rises-in-the-ranks-of-fbi-1.1711108 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702091450/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/midvalley-resident-rises-in-the-ranks-of-fbi-1.1711108 |archivedate=2 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Donora Hillard]], author\n*[[Marlon James (novelist)|Marlon James]], Jamaican novelist<ref name=marlon>{{cite web| url=http://instituteofjamaica.org.jm/featured/3679/marlon-james-2013-silver-musgrave-medallist/profficer| title=MARLON JAMES, 2013 SILVER MUSGRAVE MEDALLIST| date=15 October 2013| publisher=Institute of Jamaica| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://archive.is/20140915003351/http://instituteofjamaica.org.jm/featured/3679/marlon-james-2013-silver-musgrave-medallist/profficer| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> and winner of the 2015 [[Man Booker Prize]]\n*[[Evana Manandhar]], [[Miss Nepal 2015]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekantipur.com/2015/04/18/top-story/evana-manandhar-crowned-miss-nepal-2015/404236.html|title=Evana Manandhar crowned Miss Nepal 2015|publisher=Ekantipur.com|date=18 April 2015|accessdate=19 April 2015|author=Ekantipur Staff}}</ref> \n*[[Eddie Day Pashinski]], Pennsylvania House of Representatives member<ref name=pahouse>{{cite web| url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/member_information/house_bio.cfm?id=1112| title=Eddie Day Pashinski| publisher=Pennsylvania House of Representatives| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n* [[Steve Poleskie]], artist and writer, Professor Emeritus at [[Cornell University]]\n*[[Bo Ryan]], head coach of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] men's basketball team\n*[[Edward Weber]], Regional President at Toll Brothers Inc.\n*[[Frank Zane]], Professional bodybuilder and three-time Mr. Olympia.\n\n==Notable Wilkes students (did not graduate)==\n*[[Lawrence Hilton-Jacobs]], actor [[Welcome Back Kotter]]<ref>[[Lawrence Hilton-Jacobs]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wilkes.edu/ Wilkes University]\n* [http://www.gowilkesu.com/ Wilkes University Athletics]\n* [http://www.wilkes.edu/Mesa Wilkes University in Mesa, AZ]\n* [http://www.becolonel.com/ Information for Prospective Undergraduate Students]\n* [http://www.wclh.org/ WCLH-FM]\n* ''[http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/ The Beacon]''\n* [http://mathcs.wilkes.edu/~lcctm/ Luzerne County Council of Teachers of Mathematics (LCCTM)]\n\n{{Colleges and Universities in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Middle Atlantic Conferences navbox}}\n{{United Collegiate Hockey Conference}}\n{{Northeastern Pennsylvania Colleges and Universities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Wilkes University|*]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Luzerne County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name         = Wilkes University\n| image        = Wilkes_University_Seal_Blue.png\n| image_size   = 150px\n| motto        = \"Unity Amidst Diversity\"\n| established  = 1933\n| type         = [[Private school|Private]]\n| endowment    = $44.6 million<ref>{{cite web| title = Institutions By Total Assets| work = 2007 NACUBO Endowment Study| publisher = National Association of College and University Business Officers| year = 2008| url = http://www.nacubo.org/Images/All%20Institutions%20Listed%20by%20FY%202007%20Market%20Value%20of%20Endowment%20Assets_2007%20NES.pdf| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216022244/http://www.nacubo.org/Images/All%20Institutions%20Listed%20by%20FY%202007%20Market%20Value%20of%20Endowment%20Assets_2007%20NES.pdf| url-status = dead| archive-date = 2008-02-16| accessdate = 2008-01-24}}</ref>\n| president    = Paul S. Adams, PhD (Interim) / Greg Cant, PhD (as of 06/15/20)\n| provost      = Terese Wignot, PhD (Interim)\n| undergrad    = 2,245\n| postgrad     = 2,254\n| address      = 84 West South Street\n| city         = [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Wilkes-Barre]]\n| state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| country      = United States\n| campus       = 35 [[acres]]; [[Urban area|Urban]]\n| former_names = [[Bucknell University|Bucknell]] Junior College\n| athletics    = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division III|Division III]] \u2013 [[Middle Atlantic Conferences|MAC]] [[MAC Freedom Conference|Freedom Conference]]\n| nickname     = [http://www.gowilkesu.com Colonels]\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.wilkes.edu/}}\n| logo         = Wilkes University Seal Horizontal Blue.png\n| faculty      = 157 Full Time<ref name=\"factbook\">{{cite book| title = 2010-2011 Fact Book| publisher = Wilkes University| date = November 2010| url = http://www.wilkes.edu/Include/Fact%20Book%202010-11%20with%20cover.pdf| accessdate = 2011-07-24| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110816190315/http://www.wilkes.edu/Include/Fact%20Book%202010-11%20with%20cover.pdf| archive-date = 2011-08-16| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n| coordinates  = {{coord|41|14|36|N|75|53|27|W|type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| colors       = Blue and Gold {{color box|blue}}&nbsp;{{color box|gold}}\n}}\n\n'''Wilkes University''' is a [[Private university|private]], [[non-denominational]] American university located in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]. It has over 2,200 undergraduates and over 2,200 graduate students (both full and part-time).<ref name=\"factbook\" /> Wilkes was founded in 1933 as a satellite campus of [[Bucknell University]],<ref name=\"lit.blogs.bucknell.edu\">{{cite web|url=https://lit.blogs.bucknell.edu/2017/10/12/from-special-collectionsuniversity-archives-bucknell-junior-college/|title=From Special Collections/University Archives: Bucknell Junior College \u00ab Library and Information Technology|website=Bucknell Blogs}}</ref> and became an independent institution in 1947, naming itself Wilkes College, after English radical politician [[John Wilkes]] after whom Wilkes-Barre is named.<ref name=Castrignano>{{cite book| last=Castrignano| first=Elena| date=2012| title=Wilkes-Barre| location=Charleston, South Carolina| publisher=Arcadia Publishing| page=64| isbn=9780738555300}}</ref> The school was granted university status in January 1990.<ref name=patriot>{{cite news| agency=Associated Press| date=25 October 1989| newspaper= The Patriot| publisher=Patriot News Company| location= Pennsylvania}}</ref> A doctoral university classification was granted by Carnegie Classification Institutions of Higher Education in 2019 - one of only 14 private institutions in Pa. to have this distinction.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.wilkes.edu/2019/01/17/wilkes-university-granted-doctoral-university-designation/|title=Wilkes University Granted Doctoral University Designation \u2013 Wilkes News|first=Sarah|last=Bedford|publisher=}}</ref>  Wilkes University is accredited by the Commission on Higher Education of the [[Middle States Association of Colleges and Secondary Schools]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/bulletin/current/undergraduate/introduction/academic-matters/Accreditation.aspx|title=Accreditation - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\nThe school mascot, which was suggested by Wilkes student Joe Pringle (class of 1949),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.poconorecord.com/article/20121201/NEWS90/212010322|title=How Wilkes Univ. got its colonel|first=BILL|last=O'BOYLE|website=poconorecord.com}}</ref> is a Colonel and the official colors are blue and yellow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesleader.com/stories/A-legend-among-Colonels,235456?search_filter=Wilkes+colonel&town_id=1&sub_type=stories/|title=A Legend Among Colonels|publisher=Wilkes-Barre Times Leader|accessdate=2012-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915052035/http://www.timesleader.com/stories/A-legend-among-Colonels,235456?search_filter=Wilkes+colonel&town_id=1&sub_type=stories%2F|archive-date=2014-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The campus symbol is a letter \"W\" known as the \"flying W\" by students and alumni.\n\n==History==\nWilkes University was first established in 1933 by [[Bucknell University]] under the name Bucknell University Junior College (BUJC) in [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Wilkes-Barre]].<ref name=bucknell.edu>{{cite web| url=https://www.bucknell.edu/interested-in-bucknell/who-we-are/history-and-traditions/milestones/a-history-of-achievement.html| title=A History of Achievement| publisher=Bucknell University| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Frank G. Davis, chair of the Education department at Bucknell, first developed the idea of BUJC and served as an early liaison between BUJC and Bucknell.<ref name=\":0\" /> BUJC attracted many students who were the first members of their families to benefit from higher education as the need for junior colleges arose in urban areas.<ref name=Castrignano /> The college opened in downtown Wilkes-Barre, where the first classes were held on the third floor of the Wilkes-Barre Business College building.<ref name=Castrignano />  By 1934, the business college moved out of the building and BUJC had taken it over and continued to grow over the years, acquiring old mansions for student housing, classrooms, and administration offices along the streets of South River and South Franklin.<ref name=Castrignano /> By 1945, the Board of Trustees formally moved to develop the junior college into a four-year institution.<ref name=wilkes.edu>{{cite web| url=http://wilkes.edu/pages/140.asp| title=Wilkes History| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030538/http://wilkes.edu/pages/140.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, Wilkes College was instituted as an independent, nondenominational four-year college, with programs in the arts, sciences, and a number of professional fields, as well as numerous extracurricular activities.<ref name=bucknell.edu /> The student body in the postwar period was primarily composed of Luzerne County residents, especially G.I. bill recipients.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Wilkes University Historical Atlas|last=Cox|first=Harold|publisher=Wilkes University|year=1994|isbn=|location=Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|pages=}}</ref> In the 1950s, increasing numbers of students elected to live on campus, which led to a rapid expansion in on-campus student housing.  Increased federal funding for science and engineering in the 1950s led the college to develop academic programs in those areas, build the Stark Learning Center, and increase enrollment.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWilkes College became Wilkes University in December 1989, and the school officially received university status a month later, in January 1990.<ref name=\"patriot\" /><ref name=\"wilkes.edu\" />\n\nWilkes University opened the School of Pharmacy in 1996,<ref name=pharmacist>{{cite web| url=http://www.pharmacist.com/school-pharmacy-profile-wilkes-university-nesbitt-college-pharmacy-and-nursing| title=School of Pharmacy Profile: Wilkes University Nesbitt College of Pharmacy and Nursing| author=Julie L. Olenak| date=9 July 2012| publisher=American Pharmacists Association| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> and in 1999, through a donation from Mrs. Geraldine Nesbitt Orr, the Nesbitt School of Pharmacy was established.<ref name=wilkes.edu /> The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business & Leadership was created in 2004, and the following year, the Henry Student Center was expanded and the university purchased an 80,000-square-foot (7,400 m2) building in downtown Wilkes-Barre.<ref name=wilkes.edu /> The University Center on Main (Ucom) building houses the Sidhu School of Business and Leadership, an [[indoor track]] and field, and [[ropes course]].\n\nBy 2014, Wilkes University grew to include eight academic buildings, 20 residence halls, nine administrative buildings, and other facilities such as the Eugene S. Farley Library, the Henry Student Center, and athletic complexes.<ref name=wufastfacts>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/141.asp| title=Fast Facts| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916104005/http://wilkes.edu/pages/141.asp| archivedate=16 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Presidents of Wilkes University===\n*'''Eugene S. Farley''', 1936\u201370           \u2192Chief Administrative Officer of Wilkes precursor [[Bucknell University]] Junior College<ref name=\"lit.blogs.bucknell.edu\"/> and Wilkes University first president.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/09/18/archives/dr-eugene-farley-led-wilkes-college.html|title=Dr. Eugene Farley, Led Wilkes College|date=18 September 1973|publisher=|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> Wilkes' first holder of Chancellor/Honorary President title upon retirement. \n*'''Francis J. Michelini''', 1970\u201375       \u2192First president to ascend from the academic ranks, after serving as Wilkes biology faculty and then academic dean.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/news/2015/November/wilkes-university-dedicates-building-honoring-second-president.aspx|title=Wilkes University Dedicates Building Honoring Its Second President Francis J. Michelini - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  Resigned to become President of Pennsylvania Commission on Independent Colleges and Universities.<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor = 40225019|title = Academic Freedom and Tenure: Wilkes College (Pennsylvania)|journal = AAUP Bulletin|volume = 63|issue = 2|pages = 88\u201393|year = 1977}}</ref>\n*'''Robert S. Capin''' '50* H'83; 1975\u201384  \u2192*First university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/dr_robert_s_capin/|title=- Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  Wilkes first holder of President Emeritus title upon retirement as president and returning to the business faculty.\n*'''Christopher N. Breiseth''', 1984-2001<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/campus-life/student-affairs/commencement/past-ceremonies/past-speakers/christopher-n-breiseth.aspx|title=2014 Graduate Commencement Speaker - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>  \u2192Retired to accept position as founding President and CEO of Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt Institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.francesperkinscenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/The-Frances-Perkins-I-Knew-by-Christopher-Breiseth.pdf |title=The Frances Perkins I Knew |last=Breiseth |first=Christopher |date=1966 |website=blog.francesperkinscenter.org |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Joseph \"Tim\" E. Gilmour''', 2001-2012  \u2192Currently serves on team of Strategic Initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.strategicinitiatives.com/team|title=Our Team - Strategic Initiatives|website=www.strategicinitiatives.com}}</ref>\n*'''[[Patrick F. Leahy]]''', 2012\u20132019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/leadership/presidents-office/biography.aspx|title=Dr. Patrick F. Leahy Biography - Wilkes University|website=wilkes.edu}}</ref> \u2192Resigned effective July 31, 2019 to accept Presidency of [[Monmouth University]] in Monmouth, New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monmouth.edu/news/monmouth-university-names-patrick-f-leahy-10th-president/|title=Monmouth University Names Patrick F. Leahy 10th President - News - Monmouth University|first=Monmouth University 400 Cedar AvenueWest Long|last=BranchNJ07764732.571.3400|date=14 December 2018|publisher=}}</ref>\n*'''Alan Gregory \"Greg\" Cant''', 2020\u2013 <ref>https://www.wilkes.edu/news/2019/December/wilkes_university_names_seventh_president.aspx</ref> \u2192First president, born in Australia, to bring international experience to the position.\n\n===Interim Presidents of Wilkes University===\n*'''Robert S. Capin''' '50* H'83; 1974    \u2192*First university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>  Promoted to President 1975.  Wilkes first holder of President Emeritus title upon retirement as president and return to the business faculty.\n*'''Paul S. Adams''' '77, '82*; 2019-2020      \u2192*Second university alumnus to serve in presidential capacity and first to ascend from the student affairs division.<ref name=\"timesleader.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.timesleader.com/news/734889/wilkes-university-names-paul-adams-as-interim-president-beginning-aug-1|title=Wilkes University names Paul Adams as interim president beginning Aug. 1|last=timesleader|date=28 February 2019|website=Times Leader}}</ref>\n\n===Dean of Students of Wilkes University===\n*'''George F. Ralston''' (formerly Dean of Men) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/wilkes-magazine/_assets/Fall_2007/WilkesFall2007.pdf |title=Cover |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Arthur J. Hoover''' '55 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newspapers.com/clip/24539991/arthur_hoover_son_of_mrs_marcella/|title=Arthur Hoover, son of Mrs Marcella Hoover named to New Wilkes Post- 1965|website=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n*'''Jane K. Lampe-Groh''' (formerly Dean of Women) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/citizensvoice/obituary.aspx?n=jane-lampe-groh&pid=174826408 |title=Jane Groh Obituary - Wilkes Barre, PA &#124; Citizens Voice |publisher=Legacy.com |date= |accessdate=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n*'''Paul S. Adams''' '77, '82 <ref name=\"timesleader.com\"/>\n*'''Mark R. Allen''' <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/campus-directory/mark.allen.aspx|title=- Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Academic buildings===\nMost of the academic buildings are located within the same city block, between South River Street, South Franklin Street, South Street, and Northampton Street. The Stark Learning Center (SLC), located on South River Street, is the largest building on campus with 220,000 square feet housing classrooms, laboratories, and office space.<ref name=wilkes-stark>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/239.asp| title=Stark Learning Center| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030621/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/239.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The facility consists of nursing, math and engineering offices and classrooms.<ref name=wilkes-stark />  Stark Learning Center received extensive renovation in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesleader.mycapture.com/mycapture/folder.asp?event=2208240&CategoryID=26411|title=Wilkes University Renovations - News - Times Leader|website=timesleader.mycapture.com|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvJpoJiA0BE|title=New Stark Learning Center Labs Sneak Peek!|last=WilkesUVideo|date=28 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=5 October 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2017/09/13/stark-learning-center-construction-updates/|title=Stark Learning Center construction updates|first=Cabrini|last=Rudnicki|publisher=|accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nClassrooms and offices for humanities and social sciences are located in Breiseth Hall, a three-story building located on South Franklin Street, in the same block as SLC. Kirby Hall, a mansion formerly home to Fred Morgan Kirby, was renovated to house offices and classrooms for English.<ref name=wilkes-kirby>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/225.asp| title=Kirby Hall| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050555/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/225.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Cohen Science Center, a $35 million project, was established to house the biology and health sciences, chemistry and biochemistry, and environmental engineering and earth sciences departments.<ref name=timesleader1>{{cite web| url=http://timesleader.com/news/local-news-news/1236395/Wilkes-University-buys-Bartikowsky-building| title=Wilkes University buys Bartikowsky building| author=Andrew M. Seder| date=5 March 2014| publisher=Times Leader| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025225/http://timesleader.com/news/local-news-news/1236395/Wilkes-University-buys-Bartikowsky-building| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=wnep>{{cite web| url=http://wnep.com/2013/10/04/a-look-inside-wilkes-new-science-center/| title=A Look Inside Wilkes' New Science Center| author=Lara Greenberg| date=4 October 2013| publisher=16 WNEP News Station| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The facility has been built to [[LEED silver]] standards for environmental sustainability and allows for students to monitor energy use, water use, and general building performance to aid sustainability studies.<ref name=wilkes-cohen>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/cohen| title=Cohen Science Center Multimedia| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The building also features a rooftop vegetation area for greenhouse purposes and to assist in reducing rain runoff.<ref name=wilkes-cohen />\n\n===University Center on Main===\nIn 2005, the university acquired the former Wilkes-Barre Call Center building and parking garage on South Main Street.<ref name=timestrib>{{cite web| url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/business/colleges-push-into-area-s-downtowns-a-trend-seen-elsewhere-1.1635177| title=Colleges push into area's downtowns, a trend seen elsewhere| author=Denise Allabaugh| date=16 February 2014| publisher=The Times Tribune| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The parking garage is currently being used for student and faculty parking. The Public Safety department has remodeled and relocated to the basement of the garage.<ref name=chamberofbusiness>{{cite web| url=http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=178| title=Wilkes University Signs Purchase Agreement with City of Wilkes-Barre for Former Call Center| date=29 June 2005| publisher=Greater Wilkes-Barre Chamber of Business and Industry| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050551/http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=178| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Call Center building was renovated and renamed University Center on Main.<ref name=timestrib /> The building now houses recreation facilities including tennis and basketball courts, and a rock climbing wall.<ref name=bdcnetwork>{{cite web| url=http://www.bdcnetwork.com/student-center-opens-campus-wilkes-university| title=Student center opens on the campus of Wilkes University| date=11 August 2010| publisher=Building Design & Construction| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In summer 2014, the building was renovated to also house the Sidhu School of Business and Leadership.\n\n===Residence halls===\nThe campus offers seventeen different residence halls and apartment buildings for all levels of students, although some apartments are reserved for upperclassmen.<ref name=\"residence_halls\">{{cite web| title = Wilkes Residence Halls| publisher = Wilkes University| url = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp| accessdate = 2007-01-04| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093004/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp| archive-date = 2006-12-30| url-status = dead}}</ref> Many residence halls are located in 19th century mansions that were donated to the university, or other houses purchased by the university. Over 11 mansion and house style residence halls are used throughout the campus.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> Apartment style residences are found in University Towers and Rifkin Hall.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> Non-apartment residence halls include Catlin Hall, Doane Hall, Evans Hall, Fortinsky Halls, Passan Hall, Ross Hall, Roth Hall, Schiowitz Hall, Sterling Hall, Sturdevant Hall, Sullivan Hall, University Towers, Waller Halls (North and South), and Weiss Hall.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" /> First year and second year students are required to live in residence halls (unless he or she is a commuter), and can live off-campus starting their third year.<ref name=undergradhb>{{cite web| url=http://wilkes.edu/PDFFiles/StudentHandbook/Undergrad_Handbook_2012_2013_Upd081012.pdf| title=Wilkes University Student Handbook| date=2013\u20132014| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401164836/http://wilkes.edu/PDFFiles/StudentHandbook/Undergrad_Handbook_2012_2013_Upd081012.pdf| archive-date=2014-04-01| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nTraditional [[dormitory]] housing is provided at Evans Residence Hall. With four floors and about 200 students, Evans Residence Hall is the largest first-year student residential hall on the Wilkes University campus. Renovated in 2008, Chesapeake and Delaware Residence Halls were re-dedicated as Lawrence W. Roth Residence Hall, a residential hall connecting the previously separate Chesapeake and Delaware Residence Halls. It is a first year student, non-traditional residential hall house with about seventy residents and three RAs. Students living on campus have access to laundry facilities, basic cable, and local phone service.<ref name=\"residence_halls\" />\n\nThe university purchased the University Towers apartment complex located at 10 East South Street from a private real estate company for $8.1 million. Approximately 400 students are housed in this building's 130 units.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Campus Housing\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |date         = 2013-01-18\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp\n |access-date  = 2007-01-04\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093004/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/203.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> Part of the nearby YMCA building has been renovated into apartment style residences and houses upperclassman.<ref name=wilkes-ymca>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/265.asp| title=YMCA Building| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722203949/http://wilkes.edu/pages/265.asp| archive-date=2014-07-22| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=citizensvoice1>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/ymca-renovations-will-expand-w-b-facility-s-residential-areas-1.1135404| title=YMCA renovations will expand W-B facility's residential areas| author=Andrew Staub| date=21 April 2011| publisher=The Citizen's Voice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The apartments are known as 40 West.<ref name=wilkes-ymca />\n\n===Bookstore===\nThe university partnered with neighboring [[King's College, Pennsylvania|King's College]] to operate a joint for-profit bookstore in downtown [[Wilkes-Barre]].<ref name=beacon2012>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2012/09/25/students-partaking-in-city-activities-helps-economy/| title=Students' partaking in city activities helps economy | author=Amanda Leonard| date=25 September 2012| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The new bookstore opened in October 2006, consolidating two independent bookstores into one new facility.<ref name=beacon2012 /><ref name=chamberofbusiness2>{{cite web| url=http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=339| title=BARNES AND NOBLE SIGNS AGREEMENT TO BRING BOOK STORE TO INNOVATION CENTER @ WILKES-BARRE| date=31 July 2006| publisher=Greater Wilkes-Barre Chamber of Business and Industry| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030458/http://wilkesbarre.org/cbi/news/news.php/news.php?continue=2&table=news&article=339| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The new bookstore, run by [[Barnes & Noble College Booksellers]], is located in the basement and first floor of the Innovation Center on South Main Street.<ref name=chamberofbusiness2 /> The bookstore includes a full selection of general trade books, a full-service [[Starbucks]] cafe, lounges and study areas, and a spirit shop featuring products from both Wilkes and King's College.<ref name=chamberofbusiness2 />\n\n=== Karambelas Media and Communications Center ===\nIn August 2017, the university dedicated the newly renovated Bartikowsky Jewelers building as the Karambelas Media and Communications Center. It houses [[WCLH|WCLH 90.7 FM]] (the university radio station), the Beacon newspaper, Zebra Communications (a student-run public relations agency)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesleader.com/news/673600/preview-tour-of-new-wilkes-media-center|title=New $4 million media center a 'jewel' at Wilkes University - Times Leader|website=www.timesleader.com|access-date=2018-02-01|date=2017-08-29}}</ref> and the Sordoni Art Gallery.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/lifestyles/revamped-wilkes-gallery-opens-with-warhol-exhibit-1.2250325|title=Revamped Wilkes gallery opens with Warhol exhibit|last=Jacobson|first=Charlotte L.|access-date=2018-02-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Dorothy Dickson Darte Center for the Performing Arts ===\nThe Darte Center is the home of performing arts at Wilkes University. Built in 1965 to replace the Chase Theater (a converted carriage house),<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Wilkes Theater Marks 20th Birthday: Benefactor Dorothy Dickson Darte Saluted|last=Roccograndi|first=Betty|date=October 23, 1985|work=The Times Leader|access-date=}}</ref> it includes the Darling Theater, which seats 478, a black box theater which seats 48, and a two-story music building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/campus/buildings-academic-administrative/darte-center.aspx|title=Darte Center - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-02-01}}</ref> The land on which the Darte Center sits was donated by the Wyoming Valley Society of Arts and Sciences. The building was financed by an anonymous donation of $1 million by Dorothy Dickson Darte and dedicated in her honor after her death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Eugene Shedden Farley Library ===\nIn 1968, Wilkes College dedicated the newly constructed Eugene Shedden Farley Library and named it after the college's first president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/campus/buildings-academic-administrative/farley-library/index.aspx|title=Farley Library|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The library initially contained four special collection rooms - dedicated to [[Harold Rainsford Stark|Admiral Harold Stark]], Eleanor C. Farley, Gilbert McClintock, and Wyoming Valley residents of Polish heritage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/academics/archives/_archives/wilkes-beacon/WB28E.7.pdf|title=Convocation Set Tonight to Honor Wilkes President|last=|first=|date=November 1, 1968|work=The Beacon|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Polish room was designed by Stefan Mrozewski in the [[Zakopane Style]], and Stefan Hellersperk carved the furniture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/academics/library/about-us/the-polish-room/index.aspx|title=The Polish Room|last=|first=|date=|website=Wilkes University|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/top-stories/2013/11/19/polish-room-keeps-heritage-tradition-alive/|title=Polish Room: Keeps heritage, tradition alive|last=Stencavage|first=Alyssa|website=The Beacon|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>  The first Norman Mailer Room was dedicated in 2000,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/about-wilkes/wilkes-magazine/_assets/Spring_2008/WilkesSpring2008.pdf|title=Remembering Normal Mailer, 1923-2007|last=Lennon|first=Michael J.|date=2008|work=Wilkes Magazine|access-date=January 29, 2020|url-status=live|month=|issue=Spring|page=26}}</ref> and the second Norman Mailer Room and Collection were dedicated in October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://susanmailer.com/2019/11/10/susan-interviewed-on-art-scene/|title=Susan Interviewed on Art Scene|last=|first=|date=November 10, 2019|website=Susan Mailer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> The Harold Cox Archives room, which houses the Wilkes University Archives, was dedicated in 2004 and 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wilkes.edu/academics/library/about-us/index.aspx|title=About E.S. Farley Library - Wilkes University in PA - Wilkes University|website=wilkes.edu|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citizensvoice.com/news/archivist-s-name-now-part-of-wilkes-history-1.1539911|title=Archivist's name now part of Wilkes history|last=Writer)|first=By Michael P. Buffer (Staff|website=www.citizensvoice.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> As of 2019, the library contained 200,000 books and bound journals, 75,000 electronic journals, and 430 newspaper and journal subscriptions, as well as circulating technology like ipads and laptops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.wilkes.edu/2019/02/06/library-lovers-month-ten-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-farley-library/|title=Library Lovers Month: Ten Things You Didn\u2019t Know About the Farley Library|last=Mayk|first=Vicki|date=2019-02-06|website=Wilkes News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nWilkes University has a 14 to one student to faculty ratio and with over 50 percent of classes having fewer than 20 students per class.<ref name=usnews>{{cite web| url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/wilkes-university-3394| title=Wilkes University| publisher=U.S. News and World Report| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university is accredited by the [[Middle State Association of Colleges and Schools]] and has also received accreditation from various professional accreditation associations for individual degree plans.<ref name=collegebluebook>{{cite journal| title=Wilkes University: Tabular Data.\" The College Blue Book. 36th ed. Vol. 2: Tabular Data| date=2009| publisher=Macmillan Reference USA| journal=College Bluebook}}</ref> The university offers majors in science, education, engineering, business, and liberal arts for undergraduate and graduate students.<ref name=undergrad>{{cite web\n |title        = Undergraduate Majors and Minors at Wilkes University\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/143.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-12\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093049/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/143.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> The academic programs at Wilkes University are divided among seven schools:<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Wilkes Colleges\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/299.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-04\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093114/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/299.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=beacon2013>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2013/11/04/honors-college-option-for-growth/| title=Honors college option for growth| author=Nicole Zukowski| date=4 November 2013| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n*College of Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences\n*College of Science and Engineering\n*Nesbitt School of Pharmacy\n*Passan School of Nursing\n*Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership\n*The School of Education \n*University College\n\nThe College of Arts, Humanities, and Social Sciences includes six departments including behavioral and social sciences and performing arts.<ref name=undergrad /> One of the largest colleges is the College of Science and Engineering which has seven departments and divisions that encompass a wide range of majors and minors.<ref name=undergrad /> The College of Science and Engineering program in Electrical Engineering, Environmental Engineering, and Mechanical Engineering are accredited by the Engineering Accreditation Commission (EAC) of the Accreditation Board of Engineering and Technology (ABET).<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>  The school's Nesbitt School of Pharmacy is one of seven pharmacy schools in Pennsylvania.<ref name=pharmchoice>{{cite web| url=http://www.pharmacychoice.com/education/pharmschools/pa.cfm| title=U.S. News and World Report 2008 Pharmacy Schools rankings| date=2008| publisher=Pharmacy Choice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The school is fully accredited by the Accreditation Council for Pharmacy Education.<ref name=uspharm>{{cite web| url=http://www.uspharmd.com/school/pharmacy/wilkes_university/| title=Wilkes University \u2013 Online Pharmacy & Pharmacy Technician Degrees| publisher=USPharmD| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The Passan School of Nursing undergraduate baccalaureate program in Nursing is approved by the Pennsylvania State Board of Nurse Examiners and is accredited by the Commission on Collegiate Nursing Education.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership has several business degree plans and includes one of the most popular undergraduate majors, management.<ref name=princetonreview>{{cite web| url=http://www.princetonreview.com/WilkesUniversity.aspx| title=Wilkes University| publisher=Princeton Review| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>  Select undergraduate programs of the Sidhu School are accredited by the Accreditation Council for Business Schools and Programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wilkes.edu/bulletin/current/undergraduate/schools-colleges/the-jay-s-sidhu-school-of-business-and-leadership/index.aspx|title=The Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership - Wilkes University|website=www.wilkes.edu}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate studies===\nWilkes University offers over a dozen programs within its graduate school programs.<ref name=undergrad /> The Wilkes Graduate Teacher Education Program hosts classes online and at classroom sites across [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web\n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | authorlink = \n  | vauthors = \n  | title = Graduate Teacher Education Schedule of Courses Spring 2007\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url = http://static4.mathcs.wilkes.edu/scheds/coursessp07grd.html\n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2007-01-04 }}</ref> Some of the Wilkes Graduate Teacher Education programs are hosted entirely online. Other graduate programs such as nursing, creative writing, and bioengineering are also offered at the university.<ref name=undergrad /> The MBA program within the Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership was ranked among the top ten MBA programs in the state of Pennsylvania.<ref name=cpbj>{{cite web| url=http://www.cpbj.com/article/20140314/AWARDS/140319813/MBA-Programs:-Jay-S-Sidhu-School-of-Business-and-Leadership| title=#8 Jay S. Sidhu School of Business and Leadership| date=2014| publisher=Central Penn Business Journal| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Clubs and organizations===\nNumerous student-run clubs are recognized and funded by the student government. Many of the clubs are athletically focused, representing sports including [[crew]], [[lacrosse]], [[running]], [[skiing]], [[volleyball]], and [[ultimate frisbee]]. Clubs associated with academics and majors represent [[psychology]], [[sociology]], [[criminology]], and pre-[[pharmacy]]. Other clubs are formed around common interests such as animal advocacy, [[vegetarianism]], [[anime]], and [[robotics]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Wilkes Clubs & Organizations\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/134.asp\n |accessdate   = 2007-01-17\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230093309/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/134.asp\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nWilkes has an active student media, including a television station within the Karambelas Media and Communications Center, FM radio station [[WCLH]], which celebrated its 45th anniversary in 2017, weekly newspaper ''The Beacon'', a literary magazine ''Manuscript'', which celebrated its 70th anniversary in 2017, and yearbook ''Amnicola'', which will celebrate its 70th anniversary in 2018. The university's newspaper was originally published as the ''Bison Stampede'' in 1934.<ref name=beacon2014>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/top-stories/2014/01/30/eight-decades-of-covering-the-campus/| title=Eight decades of covering the campus| author=Christine Lee| date=30 January 2014| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The publication was later renamed ''The Beacon'', and the paper celebrated its 85th anniversary in 2019.<ref name=beacon2014 />\n\nWilkes University Programming Board, an entertainment and event planning organization, has hosted events that featured Pennsylvania based bands such as [[Live (band)|Live]] and [[Fuel (band)|Fuel]], and national favorites including [[Alanis Morissette]], [[Rusted Root]], [[Joan Osborne]], [[Dashboard Confessional]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse]], [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Hoobastank]], [[Jack's Mannequin]], and [[Billy Joel]].<ref name=wilkes-pb>{{cite web |url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/2838.asp?item=61938 |title=Wilkes Event Details |publisher=Wilkes.edu |date=2011-03-18 |accessdate=2011-12-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929120819/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/2838.asp?item=61938 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWilkes University launched the first collegiate [[marching band]] in the northeast Pennsylvania region in 2014.<ref name=citizensvoice2>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/news/wilkes-to-start-region-s-first-collegiate-marching-band-1.1583010| title=Wilkes to start region's first collegiate marching band| author=Matt Bufano| date=10 November 2013| publisher=The Citizen's Voice| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university said that the new marching band will be a welcomed new tradition and it will contribute to a growth in school spirit.<ref name=citizensvoice2 />\n\n===Student Government===\nThe Student Government organization at Wilkes hosts many annual events for undergraduates such as Homecoming and Winter Weekend, an annual themed weekend event in which teams of students participate in various competitive challenges such as team skits and eating contests.<ref name=wilkes-sg>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/345.asp| title=Student Government| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025615/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/345.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=salvato>{{cite web| url=http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/news/2013/02/05/winter-weekend-is-near/| title=Winter Weekend is near| author=Julianna Salvato| date=5 February 2013| publisher=The Beacon| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The Wilkes Student Government also coordinates all the other university organizations and clubs by formulating student activity budgets and reviewing fund requests.<ref name=wilkes-sg /> The organization is composed of various executive positions and councils including the president, presidents of Commuter Council, Inter-residence Hall Council, representatives, and a president from each class.<ref name=wilkes-sg />\n\n===ROTC Program===\nDetachment 752 of the [[Air Force Reserve Officer Training Corps]] is located at Wilkes University. Established in 1973, AF ROTC Detachment 752 has trained and prepared hundreds of young men and women for future careers as USAF officers.<ref name=wilkes-airforce>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/319.asp| title=Air Force ROTC| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030835/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/319.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> Wilkes also offers Army ROTC, but the classes are held at nearby [[King's College (Pennsylvania)|King's College]].<ref name=wilkes-army>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/1653.asp| title=Army ROTC| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915025413/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/1653.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> When students graduate from Wilkes and complete the ROTC program, they earn a commission as an officer in their respective military branches.<ref name=wilkes-airforce /><ref name=wilkes-army /> The detachment serves 12 other crosstown colleges and universities in Northeast Pennsylvania.\n\n===Athletics===\nThe Wilkes University Colonels compete in [[NCAA Division III]] athletics.<ref name=ncaawilkes>{{cite web| url=https://www.ncaa.com/schools/wilkes| title=Wilkes University| publisher=NCAA| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The university is a member of the [[Middle Atlantic Conference]] (MAC). Wilkes offers numerous intercollegiate sports team organizations at the university. Wilkes men's intercollegiate sports teams include baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming, tennis and wrestling. Wilkes women's intercollegiate sports teams include basketball, cross country, field hockey, golf, lacrosse, soccer, softball, swimming, tennis, and volleyball.\n\n====Men's conference titles====\nIn 2007, the Wilkes University baseball team was the MAC Freedom Conference champion.<ref name=mac-baseball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/BSB_0527142408.aspx?path=baseball| title=Baseball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Prior to that, the baseball team had been conference champion in 1994 and 1977.<ref name=mac-baseball />\n\nIn the 2007-2008 men's basketball season, the Wilkes men's team went 13-12 overall and finished fourth in the conference. Previously, the men's basketball team was Freedom Conference champion for the 2000-2001 season, 1998-99 season, 1997-98 season, and 1995-96 season.<ref name=mac-basketball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/MBB_0527144152.aspx?path=mbball| title=Men's Basketball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilkes University football team was the MAC champion for the 2006 season, and previously, the football team had been conference champion in 1993 and 1974.<ref name=mac-football>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/FB_0527143400.aspx?path=football| title=Football Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In the mid 1960s the Wilkes College football program had 32 straight wins\u2014the fourth longest streak in college football history at the time.<ref name=citizensvoice3>{{cite web| url=http://citizensvoice.com/sports/wilkes-football-1965-69-1.1422845| title=WILKES FOOTBALL 1965-69| author=Neil Corbett| date=30 December 2012}}</ref> It began in the fourth game of the 1965 season and ended in 1969. From a 34-0 victory over Ursinus to a 13-7 loss to Ithaca. Rollie Schmidt coached the Colonels from 1962-81. His teams went 90-73-1 winning five MAC titles, two Lambert Bowls (best small college team in the East) and one Timmie Award (best small college team in the country).<ref name=citizensvoice3 />\n\nThe men's tennis team was MAC Freedom Conference champion in 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016.<ref name=mac-tennis>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/MTEN_0527145006.aspx?path=mten| title=Men's Tennis Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilkes wrestling team has won a total of 14 Middle Atlantic Conference team championships. In 1974, the team won the NCAA Div. III national championship, afterward, the Colonels moved to the NCAA Div. I ranks for 25 seasons before returning to Div. III ranks in 2000.<ref name=wilkes-wrestling>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/858.asp| title=Wilkes Wrestling History| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030602/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/858.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Women's conference titles====\nThe Wilkes University women's field hockey team was MAC champions in 2013 and 1999.<ref name=mac-fieldh>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/FH_0527142938.aspx?path=fhockey| title=Field Hockey Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> In 2008 the women's field hockey team was ranked 18th in the nation by the NCAA.<ref>https://www.ncaa.com/ Retrieved 2009-03-13.</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the Wilkes women's soccer team was the MAC Freedom Conference champion.<ref name=mac-soccer>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WSOC_0527141513.aspx?path=wsoc| title=Women's Soccer Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The following year, the Wilkes women's softball team won the MAC region in 2006.<ref name=mac-softball>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/SB_0527140211.aspx?path=softball| title=Softball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> Prior to that, the women's softball team was the MAC champion in 1982.<ref name=mac-softball />\n\nThe women's tennis team at Wilkes was the MAC Freedom Conference champion in 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, and 2014.<ref name=mac-wt>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WTEN_0527141844.aspx?path=wten| title=Women's Tennis Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> The women's volleyball team was the conference champion in 2006, 2008, 2009, 2010, and 2011.<ref name=mac-volley>{{cite web| url=http://gomacsports.com/sports/2014/5/27/WVB_0527140439.aspx?path=wvball| title=Volleyball Champions| publisher=Middle Atlantic Conference| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nWomen's golf and women's swimming, both NCAA Division III intercollegiate sports, were introduced to Wilkes University's sports roster in the 2014-15 season in the Middle Atlantic Conference.<ref name=citizensvoice2 />\n\n==Events==\n\n===Lecture series===\nThe university sponsors and hosts academically focused lectures series for its students and community. The [[Max Rosenn]] Lecture Series in Law and Humanities was established in the 1980s, and has brought many speakers to the university including author [[Norman Mailer]], Supreme Court Justice [[John Paul Stevens]], and journalist [[Bob Woodward]].<ref>{{cite press release\n |title        = Bob Woodward to Deliver Rosenn Lecture\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |date         = Apr 7, 2006\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=9088\n |accessdate   = Jan 5, 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061230100400/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=9088\n |archive-date = 2006-12-30\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>  The Allan P. Kirby Lecture in Free Enterprise and Entrepreneurship has also hosted speakers including journalist and television host [[John Stossel]], and former New York Governor [[George Pataki]].<ref name=lectureseries>{{cite web\n |title        = Allan P. Kirby Lecture Series\n |publisher    = Wilkes University\n |url          = http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4296.asp\n |accessdate   = 2011-05-31\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110929121158/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4296.asp\n |archive-date = 2011-09-29\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref> The center hosts two lectures annually.<ref name=lectureseries /> The [[United Nations]] lecture series was launched in the 2011-2012 academic year and the program brings U.N. officials to the campus to speak to students throughout the year through a partnership with the Higher Education Alliance of the United Nations.<ref name=wilkes-lectures>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4308.asp| title=Other Lectures at Wilkes| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915050557/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/4308.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Annual High School Mathematics Contest===\nFor over 60 years Wilkes University has been the host of the Annual High School Mathematics Contest as sponsored by the Luzerne County Council of Teachers of Mathematics (LCCTM).<ref name=timesleader2>{{cite web| url=http://www.timesleader.com/stories/Math-contest-at-Wilkes-adds-up-to-scholarships,120910| title=Math contest at Wilkes adds up to scholarships| author=JANINE UNGVARSKY| date=15 February 2013| publisher=The Times Leader| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030443/http://www.timesleader.com/stories/Math-contest-at-Wilkes-adds-up-to-scholarships,120910| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> Every year juniors and seniors from Luzerne County high schools come to Wilkes University to participate in the competition. The first-place winner in both the junior and senior divisions are awarded a full-tuition scholarship to Wilkes University.<ref name=timesleader2 />\n\n===ACM Intercollegiate Programming Contest===\nThe Wilkes University Math and Computer Science Department hosts the Eastern Pennsylvania division of the Mid-Atlantic Region of the annual [[International Collegiate Programming Contest|ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest]]. Wilkes University has been host to the event for the last 5 years. A total of 8 schools host teams in the Mid-Atlantic Region.<ref name=wilkes-pc>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=55075| title=Wilkes University Is Regional Site for International Computer Programming Competition on Nov. 7| author=Vicki Mayk| date=2 November 2009| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://archive.is/20140915003336/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/194.asp?item=55075| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The competition is sponsored by [[IBM]] and the contest challenges the participants knowledge and creativity in solving computer programming problems.<ref name=wilkes-pc />\n\n===Annual Tom Bigler High School Journalism Conference===\nAnnually, hundreds of Pennsylvania high school students attend this annual media oriented event. Each year features a notable keynote speaker, hands-on workshops in the areas of telecommunications, journalism and public relations and panel discussions and presentation from media professionals and personalities. A high school journalism contest and awards ceremony is also a main event.\n\n===Plays===\nThe Wilkes University Theatre presents a full season of dramas and musicals on the main stage as well as a season of student produced black box productions at the Darte Center.<ref name=wilkes-theater>{{cite web| url=http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/3833.asp| title=Theatre Arts| publisher=Wilkes University| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915030640/http://www.wilkes.edu/pages/3833.asp| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> The Division of Performing Arts presents a total of four shows annually at the Darte Center.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Ann Bartuska]], Ecologist and Biologist\n*[[Jackson Berkey]], classical music composer, pianist, and singer\n*[[Marty Blake]], general manager of the [[Atlanta Hawks]] franchise<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/10/sports/basketball/marty-blake-nba-scout-dies-at-86.html?_r=1&| title=Marty Blake, Sharp Judge of N.B.A. Talent, Dies at 86| author=Bruce Weber| date=9 April 2013| work=New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n*[[Gabriel J. Campana]], former mayor of [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n*[[Catherine Chandler]], poet\n*[[Jesse Choper]], constitutional law scholar and former dean of the UC-Berkeley School of Law\n*[[Catherine D. DeAngelis]], first woman and the first pediatrician to become the editor of the [[JAMA (journal)|Journal of the American Medical Association]]<ref name=nytimes2>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/10/09/us/woman-is-named-editor-of-ama-journal.html| title=Woman Is Named Editor of A.M.A. Journal| author=LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN| date=9 October 1999| work=New York Times| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n*[[William R. Evanina]], the NCIX, the [[Office of the National Counterintelligence Executive|National Counterintelligence Executive]] of the United States, and director of the U.S. National Counterintelligence and Security Center<ref>{{Cite news|author=Bolus, Kathleen |date=29 June 2014 |title=Midvalley resident rises in the ranks of FBI |url=http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/midvalley-resident-rises-in-the-ranks-of-fbi-1.1711108 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702091450/http://thetimes-tribune.com/news/midvalley-resident-rises-in-the-ranks-of-fbi-1.1711108 |archivedate=2 July 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Donora Hillard]], author\n*[[Marlon James (novelist)|Marlon James]], Jamaican novelist<ref name=marlon>{{cite web| url=http://instituteofjamaica.org.jm/featured/3679/marlon-james-2013-silver-musgrave-medallist/profficer| title=MARLON JAMES, 2013 SILVER MUSGRAVE MEDALLIST| date=15 October 2013| publisher=Institute of Jamaica| accessdate=14 September 2014| archive-url=https://archive.is/20140915003351/http://instituteofjamaica.org.jm/featured/3679/marlon-james-2013-silver-musgrave-medallist/profficer| archive-date=2014-09-15| url-status=dead}}</ref> and winner of the 2015 [[Man Booker Prize]]\n*[[Evana Manandhar]], [[Miss Nepal 2015]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ekantipur.com/2015/04/18/top-story/evana-manandhar-crowned-miss-nepal-2015/404236.html|title=Evana Manandhar crowned Miss Nepal 2015|publisher=Ekantipur.com|date=18 April 2015|accessdate=19 April 2015|author=Ekantipur Staff}}</ref> \n*[[Eddie Day Pashinski]], Pennsylvania House of Representatives member<ref name=pahouse>{{cite web| url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/member_information/house_bio.cfm?id=1112| title=Eddie Day Pashinski| publisher=Pennsylvania House of Representatives| accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref> \n* [[Steve Poleskie]], artist and writer, Professor Emeritus at [[Cornell University]]\n*[[Bo Ryan]], head coach of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] men's basketball team\n*[[Edward Weber]], Regional President at Toll Brothers Inc.\n*[[Frank Zane]], Professional bodybuilder and three-time Mr. Olympia.\n\n==Notable Wilkes students (did not graduate)==\n*[[Lawrence Hilton-Jacobs]], actor [[Welcome Back Kotter]]<ref>[[Lawrence Hilton-Jacobs]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=March 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wilkes.edu/ Wilkes University]\n* [http://www.gowilkesu.com/ Wilkes University Athletics]\n* [http://www.wilkes.edu/Mesa Wilkes University in Mesa, AZ]\n* [http://www.becolonel.com/ Information for Prospective Undergraduate Students]\n* [http://www.wclh.org/ WCLH-FM]\n* ''[http://www.thewilkesbeacon.com/ The Beacon]''\n* [http://mathcs.wilkes.edu/~lcctm/ Luzerne County Council of Teachers of Mathematics (LCCTM)]\n\n{{Colleges and Universities in Pennsylvania}}\n{{Middle Atlantic Conferences navbox}}\n{{United Collegiate Hockey Conference}}\n{{Northeastern Pennsylvania Colleges and Universities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Wilkes University|*]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1933]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Luzerne County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "ElKevbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilkes_University"}
{"title_page": "Laucala", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Laucala\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Island\n| pushpin_map             = Fiji\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Fiji\n| coordinates             = {{coord|16|45|00|S|179|41|00|W|region:FJ_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Fiji]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Island group\n| subdivision_name1       = Northern [[Lau Islands]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 10\n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Laucala''' (pronounced {{IPA-fj|lau\u02c8\u00f0ala|}}) is one of a triplet of small islands that lie to the east of Thurston Point on the island of [[Taveuni]] in [[Fiji]]. The privately owned islands are the site of the Laucala Resort.\n\nThe total land area of the main island is 12 square kilometres. It is 5 kilometres long with a maximum width of 3 kilometres, narrowing to 1.5 kilometres in some places. The other two islands in the group are [[Qamea]] several hundred metres to the west and [[Matagi Island|Matagi]].\n\n==Sale to Dietrich Mateschitz==\nIn 2003 [[Dietrich Mateschitz]], head of the [[Red Bull]] energy drink company, bought the island from [[Forbes]]'s heirs.<ref name=\"Booth, T\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.epubbud.com/read.php?g=B486GPP3&p=1|title=Travel Adventures - Fiji|author=Booth, Thomas H.|date=Oct 26, 2011|publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc.|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe resort now includes 25 [[Bure (Fiji)|bures]], each unique from one another with differing themes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.designboom.com/architecture/red-bull-co-founder-dietrich-mateschitzs-laucala-island-resort-10-12-2013/|title=red bull co-founder dietrich mateschitz's laucala island resort|date=Oct 26, 2011}}</ref> The projected cost per night ranges from US$7,000 to $36,000.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vanua Levu}}\n{{Islands of Fiji}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Fiji]]\n[[Category:Vanua Levu]]\n[[Category:Cakaudrove Province]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:Forbes family residences]]\n[[Category:Dietrich Mateschitz]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Laucala\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = \n| settlement_type         = Island\n| pushpin_map             = Fiji\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Fiji\n| coordinates             = {{coord|16|45|00|S|179|41|00|W|region:FJ_type:isle|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Fiji]]\n| subdivision_type1       = Island group\n| subdivision_name1       = Northern [[Lau Islands]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 10\n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Laucala''' (pronounced {{IPA-fj|lau\u02c8\u00f0ala|}}) is one of a triplet of small islands that lie to the east of Thurston Point on the island of [[Taveuni]] in [[Fiji]]. The privately owned islands are the site of the Laucala Resort.\n\nThe total land area of the main island is 12 square kilometres. It is 5 kilometres long with a maximum width of 3 kilometres, narrowing to 1.5 kilometres in some places. The other two islands in the group are [[Qamea]] several hundred metres to the west and [[Matagi Island|Matagi]].\n\n==Sale to Dietrich Mateschitz==\nIn 2003 [[Dietrich Mateschitz]], head of the [[Red Bull]] energy drink company, bought the island from [[Forbes]]'s heirs.<ref name=\"Booth, T\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.epubbud.com/read.php?g=B486GPP3&p=1|title=Travel Adventures - Fiji|author=Booth, Thomas H.|date=Oct 26, 2011|publisher=Hunter Publishing, Inc.|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe resort now includes 25 [[Bure (Fiji)|bures]], each unique from one another with differing themes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.designboom.com/architecture/red-bull-co-founder-dietrich-mateschitzs-laucala-island-resort-10-12-2013/|title=red bull co-founder dietrich mateschitz's laucala island resort|date=Oct 26, 2011}}</ref> The projected cost per night ranges from US$7,000 to $36,000.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vanua Levu}}\n{{Islands of Fiji}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of Fiji]]\n[[Category:Vanua Levu]]\n[[Category:Cakaudrove Province]]\n[[Category:Private islands]]\n[[Category:Forbes family residences]]\n[[Category:Dietrich Mateschitz]]\n\n{{Fiji-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laucala"}
{"title_page": "Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m", "text_new": "{{short description|Writing system for the Vietnamese language using Chinese characters}}\n{{Infobox Writing system\n|name=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m <br/>\ud846\ude38\u5583\n|sample=Chu nom.svg\n|imagesize=140px\n|type=[[Logographic]]\n|languages=[[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n|fam1=[[Chinese characters]]\n|sisters=[[Kanji]], [[Hanja]], [[Sawndip]], [[Khitan large script]]\n|time=13th\u2013present<br>(limited use)\n}}\n{{Contains Nom text}}\n{{Table Hanzi}}\n'''Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''' ({{linktext|lang=Vi-nom|\ud846\ude38\u5583}}, {{IPA-vi|c\u0268\u030c\u02c0 nom|IPA}}, literally 'Southern characters'),<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=5}}</ref> in earlier times also called '''Ch\u1eef Nam''' ({{linktext|lang=Vi-nom|\ud846\ude38\u5357}}) or '''Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m''' (\u570b\u97f3, \"National sound\"), is a [[logographic]] writing system formerly used to write the [[Vietnamese language]].  It used the standard set of classical [[Chinese characters]] to represent [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary]] and some native Vietnamese words, while new characters were created on the Chinese model to represent other words.<ref name=\"Ch\u1eef-n\u00f4m script\">{{cite web\n|publisher= Omniglot\n|title=Ch\u1eef-n\u00f4m script\n|url= https://www.omniglot.com/writing/chunom.htm\n}}</ref>\n\nAlthough formal writing in Vietnam was done in [[classical Chinese]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Tri T\u00e0i |date=2002 |title=Gi\u00e1o tr\u00ecnh ti\u1ebfng H\u00e1n. T\u1eadp I: C\u01a1 s\u1edf |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=5}}</ref> until the early 20th century (except for two brief interludes), ch\u1eef N\u00f4m was widely used between the 15th and 19th centuries by Vietnam's cultured elite, including women, for popular works, many in verse. One of the best-known pieces of [[Vietnamese literature]], ''[[The Tale of Ki\u1ec1u]]'', was composed in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m.\n\nIn the 1920s, the Latin-based [[Vietnamese alphabet]] created by [[Jesuit]] missionaries displaced ch\u1eef N\u00f4m as the preferred way to record Vietnamese. While Han characters are still used for decorative, historic and ceremonial value and as symbols of [[good luck]], N\u00f4m characters have fallen into disuse in any other function in modern [[Vietnam]] in favour of  the alphabet. The task of preservation and study of Vietnamese texts written in N\u00f4m (but also classical Chinese texts from Vietnam) is conducted by the [[Institute of H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m Studies]] in [[Hanoi]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Vietnamese word ''ch\u1eef'' (character) is derived from the [[Old Chinese]] word {{Zh|c={{linktext|\u5b57}}|s=|t=|labels=no}}, meaning '[Chinese] character'.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=T\u00e0i C\u1ea9n |date=1995 |title=Gi\u00e1o tr\u00ecnh l\u1ecbch s\u1eed ng\u1eef \u00e2m ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t (s\u01a1 th\u1ea3o) |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n Gi\u00e1o d\u1ee5c |page=47}}</ref> The word ''N\u00f4m'' in ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' means 'Southern', and is derived from the [[Middle Chinese]] word {{Zh|c={{linktext|\u5357}}|s=|t=|labels=no}}, meaning 'south'.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |pages=5, 215}}</ref>\n\nThere are many ways to write the name ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m characters. The word ''ch\u1eef'' may be written as {{vi-nom|\u5b57}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86f\udcd8(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b81)}}}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86a\uddda(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b88)}}}}, {{vi-nom|\ud846\ude38}}, {{vi-nom|\u8321}}, {{vi-nom|\u8293}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86f\udff0(\u2ff0\u5b57\u6587)}}}}, {{vi-nom|\ud846\udd82}}(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b57), {{vi-nom|\u4f47}} or {{vi-nom|\u5b81}}, while ''N\u00f4m'' may be written as {{vi-nom|\u5583}} or {{vi-nom|\u8af5}}.<ref>{{cite book |last=V\u0169 |first=V\u0103n K\u00ednh |date=2005 |title=\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ngh\u1ec7 Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |pages=293, 899}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Nguy\u1ec5n |first1=H\u1eefu Vinh |last2=\u0110\u1eb7ng |first2=Th\u1ebf Ki\u1ec7t |last3=Nguy\u1ec5n |first3=Do\u00e3n V\u01b0\u1ee3ng |last4=L\u00ea |first4=V\u0103n \u0110\u1eb7ng |last5=Nguy\u1ec5n |first5=V\u0103n S\u00e2m |last6=Nguy\u1ec5n |first6=Ng\u1ecdc B\u00edch |last7=Tr\u1ea7n |first7=Uy\u00ean Thi |date=2009 |title=T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m tr\u00edch d\u1eabn |publisher=Vi\u1ec7n Vi\u1ec7t-h\u1ecdc |pages=[http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0248.png 248], [http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0249.png 249], [http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0866.png 866]}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n{{main|History of writing in Vietnam}}\n''Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' is the logographic writing system of the Vietnamese language. It is based on the Chinese writing system but adds a high number of new characters to make it fit the Vietnamese language.\n\nIn Vietnamese, Chinese characters are called ''ch\u1eef H\u00e1n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57|\u6f22}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), ''H\u00e1n t\u1ef1'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u5b57}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u6587}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), or ''ch\u1eef nho'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57\u5112}}}} \u2018Confucian characters\u2019).<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=T\u00e0i C\u1ea9n |date=2001 |title=Ngu\u1ed3n g\u1ed1c v\u00e0 qu\u00e1 tr\u00ecnh h\u00ecnh th\u00e0nh c\u00e1ch \u0111\u1ecdc H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc qu\u1ed1c gia H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=H\u1ed9i Khai-tr\u00ed ti\u1ebfn-\u0111\u1ee9c |date=1954 |title=Vi\u1ec7t-nam t\u1ef1-\u0111i\u1ec3n |publisher=V\u0103n M\u1edbi |pages=141, 228}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=\u0110\u00e0o |first=Duy Anh |date=2005 |title=H\u00e1n-Vi\u1ec7t t\u1eeb-\u0111i\u1ec3n gi\u1ea3n y\u1ebfu |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ho\u00e1 Th\u00f4ng tin |page=281}}</ref> ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u6587}}}}) also means Chinese language literature (in this case, ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' literally means \u2018Han literature\u2019).<ref>{{cite book |author=H\u1ed9i Khai-tr\u00ed ti\u1ebfn-\u0111\u1ee9c |date=1954 |title=Vi\u1ec7t-nam t\u1ef1-\u0111i\u1ec3n |publisher=V\u0103n M\u1edbi |page=228}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=\u0110\u00e0o |first=Duy Anh |date=2005 |title=H\u00e1n-Vi\u1ec7t t\u1eeb-\u0111i\u1ec3n gi\u1ea3n y\u1ebfu |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ho\u00e1 Th\u00f4ng tin |pages=281, 900}}</ref>\n\nThe term ''H\u00e1n N\u00f4m'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22|\u5583}}}} \u2018Han and ch\u1eef N\u00f4m characters\u2019)<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tr\u1ea7n |first=V\u0103n Ch\u00e1nh |date=January 2012 |title=T\u1ea3n m\u1ea1n kinh nghi\u1ec7m h\u1ecdc ch\u1eef H\u00e1n c\u1ed5|journal=Su\u1ed1i Ngu\u1ed3n, t\u1eadp 3&4 |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n T\u1ed5ng h\u1ee3p Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=82}}</ref> in Vietnamese designates the whole body of Vietnamese premodern written materials, either written in Chinese (''ch\u1eef h\u00e1n'') or in Vietnamese (''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'').<ref>Asian research trends: a humanities and social science review \u2013 No 8 to 10 \u2013 Page 140 Yunesuko Higashi Ajia Bunka Kenky\u016b Sent\u0101 (Tokyo, Japan) \u2013 1998 \"Most of the source materials from premodern Vietnam are written in Chinese, obviously using Chinese characters; however, a portion of the literary genre is written in Vietnamese, using chu nom. Therefore, han nom is the term designating the whole body of premodern written materials..\"</ref> H\u00e1n and N\u00f4m could also be found in the same document side by side,<ref>Vietnam Courier 1984 Vol20/21 Page 63 \"Altogether about 15,000 books in Han, Nom and Han\u2014Nom have been collected. These books include royal certificates granted to deities, stories and records of deities, clan histories, family genealogies, records of cutsoms, land registers, ...\"</ref> for example, in the case of translations of books on [[Chinese medicine]].<ref>Kh\u1eafc M\u1ea1nh Tr\u1ecbnh, ''Nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: K\u1ef7 y\u1ebfu H\u1ed9i ngh\u1ecb Qu\u1ed1c t\u1ebf v\u1ec1 ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''\nVi\u1ec7n nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u H\u00e1n N\u00f4m (Vietnam), Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation \u2013 2006 \"The Di s\u1ea3n H\u00e1n N\u00f4m notes 366 entries which are solely on either medicine or pharmacy; of these 186 are written in Chinese, 50 in N\u00f4m, and 130 in a mixture of the two scripts. Many of these entries ... Vietnam were written in either N\u00f4m or H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m rather than in 'pure' Chinese. My initial impression was that the percentage of texts written in N\u00f4m was even higher. This is because for the particular medical subject I wished to investigate-[[smallpox]]-the percentage of texts written in Nom or H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m is even higher than is the percentage of texts in N\u00f4m and H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m for general medical and pharmaceutical ..\"</ref> The [[Buddhist]] history ''C\u1ed5 Ch\u00e2u Ph\u00e1p V\u00e2n ph\u1eadt b\u1ea3n h\u1ea1nh ng\u1eef l\u1ee5c'' (1752) gives the story of early [[Buddhism in Vietnam]] both in H\u00e1n script and in a parallel N\u00f4m translation.<ref>Wynn Wilcox ''Vietnam and the West: New Approaches'' 2010- Page 31 \"At least one Buddhist text, the C\u1ed5 Ch\u00e2u Ph\u00e1p V\u00e2n ph\u1eadt b\u1ea3n h\u1ea1nh ng\u1eef l\u1ee5c (CCPVP), preserves a story in H\u00e1n script about the early years of Buddhist influence in Vietnam and gives a parallel N\u00f4m translation.\"</ref> The Jesuit [[Girolamo Maiorica]] (1605\u20131656) had also used parallel H\u00e1n and N\u00f4m texts.\n\nThe term ''ch\u1eef qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef'' ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\ud846\ude38|\ud846\ude38]][[wikt:\u570b|\u570b]][[wikt:\u8a9e|\u8a9e]]}} \"national language script\") refers to the [[romanized]] [[writing system]] based on the [[Vietnamese alphabet]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Tu duc thanh che tu hoc giai nghia ca.jpg|thumb|250px|A page from ''T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u00e1nh Ch\u1ebf T\u1ef1 H\u1ecdc Gi\u1ea3i Ngh\u0129a Ca'' ({{vi-nom|\u55e3\u5fb7\u8056\u88fd\u5b57\u5b78\u89e3\u7fa9\u6b4c}}), a 19th-century primer for teaching Vietnamese children Chinese characters. The work is attributed to Emperor [[T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c]], the 4th Emperor of the Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty. In this primer, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m is used to gloss the Chinese characters, for example, {{vi-nom|\ud845\uddf6}} is used to gloss {{vi-nom|\u5929}}.]]\nChinese characters were introduced to Vietnam after the [[Han dynasty]] conquered the country in 111 BC. Independence was achieved in 939, but [[Literary Chinese]] was adopted for official purposes in 1010.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=78\u201379, 82}} For most of the period up to the early 20th century, formal writing was indistinguishable from contemporaneous classical Chinese works produced in China, Korea, and Japan.<ref name=\"Marr141\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|p=141}}: \"Because the Chinese characters were pronounced according to Vietnamese preferences, and because certain stylistic modifications occurred over time, later scholars came to refer to a hybrid \"Sino-Vietnamese\" (Han-Viet) language. However, there would seem to be no more justification for this term than for a fifteenth-century \"Latin-English\" versus the Latin written contemporaneously in Rome.\"</ref>\n\nVietnamese scholars were thus intimately familiar with Chinese writing.  In order to record their native language, they applied the structural principles of Chinese characters to develop ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''.  The new script was mostly used to record folk songs and for other popular literature.{{sfn|Marr|1984|p=141}}  Vietnamese written in ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' briefly replaced Chinese for official purposes under the [[H\u1ed3 dynasty]] (1400\u20131407) and under the [[T\u00e2y S\u01a1n]] (1778\u20131802), but in both cases this was swiftly reversed.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=32, 38}}\n\n===Earliest evidence===\n\nThe use of Chinese characters to write the Vietnamese language can be traced to an inscription with the two characters \"{{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u5e03|\u5e03]][[:wikt:\u84cb|\u84cb]]}}\", as part of the posthumous title of [[Ph\u00f9ng H\u01b0ng]], a national hero who succeeded in expelling the Chinese, albeit briefly in the late 8th century. These two characters literally mean \"cloth\" + \"cover\" in Chinese but when pronounced by the Vietnamese, the phonetic value is employed to represent ''vua c\u00e1i'' (\"great king\"), or archaic Vietnamese ''b\u1ed1 c\u00e1i'' (\"father and mother\", i.e. as respectable as one's parents). During the 10th century, the founder of the [[\u0110inh dynasty]] (968-979) named the country ''\u0110\u1ea1i C\u1ed3 Vi\u1ec7t ''({{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u5927|\u5927]][[:wikt:\u77bf|\u77bf]][[:wikt:\u8d8a|\u8d8a]]}}). The second character of this title is another early example of using Chinese characters to represent Vietnamese native words, although which word it represents is still debated.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=21\u201323}}<ref>Keith Weller Taylor ''The Birth of Vietnam'' 1976 \u2013 Page 220 \"The earliest example of Vietnamese character writing, as we have noted earlier, is for the words bo and cai in the posthumous title given to Phung Hung. Although Vietnamese character writing was eventually developed for literary purposes\"</ref>\n\nThe oldest surviving objects with ch\u1eef N\u00f4m inscriptions are a stele (1209) at B\u1ea3o \u00c2n temple containing 18 characters naming villages and people, and a stele at H\u1ed9 Th\u00e0nh S\u01a1n in [[Ninh B\u00ecnh Province]] (1343), listing 20 villages.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=23}}<ref>Laurence C. Thompson A Vietnamese Reference Grammar 1987 Page 53 \"This stele at Ho-th\u00e0nh-s\u01a1n is the earliest irrefutable piece of evidence of this writing system, which is called in Vietnamese ch\u1eef n\u00f4m (chu 'written word', nom 'popular language', probably ultimately related to nam 'south'-note that the ...\"</ref>\n\nThe first literary writing in Vietnamese is said to have been an [[incantation]] in verse composed in 1282 by the Minister of Justice [[Nguy\u1ec5n Thuy\u00ean]] and thrown into the [[Red River (Asia)|Red River]] to expel a menacing [[crocodile]].{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=23}} The oldest Nom text that is still extant is the collected poetry of Emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng]] written in the 13th century.<ref name=\"Tong\">{{in lang|vi}} Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng, ''[[s:vi:C\u01b0 tr\u1ea7n l\u1ea1c \u0111\u1ea1o ph\u00fa|C\u01b0 tr\u1ea7n l\u1ea1c \u0111\u1ea1o ph\u00fa]]''</ref>\n\n===H\u1ed3 dynasty (1400\u201307) and Ming conquest (1407\u201327)===\n\nDuring the seven years of the [[H\u1ed3 dynasty]] (1400\u201307) Classical Chinese was discouraged in favor of vernacular Vietnamese written in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m, which became the official script. The emperor [[H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly]] even ordered the translation of the [[Book of Documents]] into N\u00f4m and pushed for reinterpretation of Confucian thoughts in his book ''Minh \u0111\u1ea1o''.<ref>[http://www.nguoiduatin.vn/nhin-lai-cuoc-cai-cach-cua-ho-quy-ly-600-nam-truoc-a59764.html \"Reexamining the Reforms of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly 600 years ago\"]</ref> These efforts were reversed with the fall of the H\u1ed3 and [[fourth Chinese domination|Chinese conquest of 1407]], lasting twenty years, during which use of the vernacular language and demotic script were suppressed.<ref>{{harvnb|Hannas|1997|p=83}}: \"An exception was during the brief H\u1ed3 dynasty (1400\u201307), when Chinese was abolished and ch\u1eef N\u00f4m became the official script, but the subsequent Chinese invasion and twenty-year occupation put an end to that (Helmut Martin 1982:34).\"</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ming dynasty occupation of Vietnam]], ch\u1eef N\u00f4m printing blocks, texts and inscriptions were thoroughly destroyed; as a result the earliest surviving texts of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m post-date the occupation.<ref>Mark W. McLeod, Thi Dieu Nguyen ''Culture and Customs of Vietnam'' 2001 Page 68  \u2013  \"In part because of the ravages of the Ming occupation \u2014 the invaders destroyed or removed many Viet texts and the blocks for printing them \u2014 the earliest body of nom texts that we have dates from the early post-occupation era ...\"</ref>\n\n===L\u00ea (1428\u20131788), T\u00e2y S\u01a1n (1788\u20131802) and Nguy\u1ec5n dynasties (1802\u20131945) ===\n[[File:Nh\u1eadt d\u1ee5ng th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0111\u00e0m, p. 38.jpg|thumb|A page from the bilingual dictionary ''Nh\u1eadt d\u1ee5ng th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0111\u00e0m'' (1851). Characters representing words in ''H\u00e1n'' (Chinese) are explained in ''N\u00f4m'' (Vietnamese).]]\nAmong the earlier works in N\u00f4m of this era are the writings of [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u00e3i]] (1380\u20131442).<ref name=\"McLeod\">Mark W. McLeod, Thi Dieu Nguyen, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=a2TerRF1j74C&dq= Culture and Customs of Vietnam]'', Greenwood Publishing Group, 2001, p.  68.</ref> The corpus of N\u00f4m writings grew over time as did more scholarly compilations of the script itself. [[Tr\u1ecbnh Th\u1ecb Ng\u1ecdc Tr\u00fac]], consort of King [[L\u00ea Th\u1ea7n T\u00f4ng]], is generally given credit for ''{{lang|vi|[[Ch\u1ec9 nam ng\u1ecdc \u00e2m gi\u1ea3i ngh\u0129a]]}}'' (the Explication of the Guide to Jeweled Sounds), a 24,000-character bilingual Han-to-Nom [[dictionary]] compiled between the 15th and 18th centuries, most likely in 1641 or 1761.<ref name=chu>Vi\u1ebft Lu\u00e2n Chu, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=-XZuAAAAMAAJ&q= Thanh H\u00f3a, th\u1ebf v\u00e0 l\u1ef1c m\u1edbi trong th\u1ebf k\u1ef7 XXI]'', 2003, p. 52</ref><ref name=\"Phan 2013\">{{cite journal|title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and the Taming of the South: A Bilingual Defense for Vernacular Writing in the ''{{lang|vi|Ch\u1ec9 Nam Ng\u1ecdc \u00c2m Gi\u1ea3i Ngh\u0129a|nocat=true}}''|first=John|last=Phan|journal=[[Journal of Vietnamese Studies]]|location=Oakland, California|publisher=University of California Press|year=2013|volume=8|issue=1|page=1|jstor=10.1525/vs.2013.8.1.1|doi=10.1525/vs.2013.8.1.1}}</ref>\n\nWhile almost all official writings and documents continued to be written in [[classical Chinese]] until the early 20th century, N\u00f4m was the preferred script for literary compositions of the cultural elites. N\u00f4m reached its golden period with the Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty in the 19th century as it became a vehicle for diverse genres, from novels to theatrical pieces, and instructional manuals. Apogees of Vietnamese literature emerged with [[Nguy\u1ec5n Du]]'s ''[[The Tale of Ki\u1ec1u]]''<ref>B. N. Ng\u00f4 \"The Vietnamese Language Learning Framework\" \u2013 ''Journal of Southeast Asian Language and Teaching'', 2001 \"... to a word, is most frequently represented by combining two Chinese characters, one of which indicates the sound and the other the meaning. From the fifteenth to the nineteenth century many major works of Vietnamese poetry were composed in ch\u1eef n\u00f4m, including Truy\u1ec7n Ki\u1ec1u\"</ref> and [[H\u1ed3 Xu\u00e2n H\u01b0\u01a1ng]]'s poetry. Although literacy in premodern Vietnam was limited to just 3 to 5 percent of the population,{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=78}} nearly every village had someone who could read Nom aloud for the benefit of other villagers.{{sfn|Marr|1984|p=142}} Thus these N\u00f4m works circulated orally in the villages, making it accessible even to the illiterates.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=44-46}}\n\nIn 1838, [[Jean-Louis Taberd]] compiled a Nom dictionary, helping with the standardization of the script.<ref name=\"Taberd\">Taberd, J.L., ''[http://staging.nomfoundation.org/taberd/ Dictionarium Anamitico-Latinum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626064515/http://staging.nomfoundation.org/taberd/ |date=2013-06-26 }}'', 1838. This is a revision of a dictionary by Pierre-Joseph [[Pigneau de B\u00e9hain]] compiled in 1772\u20131773 and reprinted in 1884.</ref> In 1867, Catholic scholar [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u01b0\u1eddng T\u1ed9]] made the bold move to petition the Emperor [[T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c]] to adopt N\u00f4m as the official script. The court failed to make a break with chu Nho but N\u00f4m did gain some sanction as ''Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m'', i.e. the national speech.<ref name=\"Dinh\">Quyen Vuong Dinh, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uB2OAAAAMAAJ&q= V\u0103n b\u1ea3n qu\u1ea3n l\u00fd nh\u00e0 n\u01b0\u1edbc v\u00e0 c\u00f4ng t\u00e1c c\u00f4ng v\u0103n, gi\u1ea5y t\u1edd th\u1eddi phong ki\u1ebfn Vi\u1ec7t Nam]'', 2002, p. 50. The decree is entitled, ''Xin khoan dung Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m'' (\"Please respect the national voice.\")</ref>\n\n===French Indochina and the Latin alphabet===\nFrom the latter half of the 19th century onwards, the [[Cochinchina|French colonial authorities]] discouraged or simply banned the use of classical Chinese, and promoted the use of the Vietnamese alphabet, which they viewed as a stepping stone toward learning French. Language reform movements in other Asian nations stimulated Vietnamese interest in the subject. Following the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1905, Japan was increasingly cited as a model for modernization. The Confucian education system was compared unfavorably to the Japanese system of public education. According to a polemic by writer [[Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh]], \"so-called Confucian scholars\" lacked knowledge of the modern world, as well as real understanding of Han literature. Their degrees showed only that they had learned how to write characters, he claimed.<ref>Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh, \"Monarchy and Democracy\", ''Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh and His Political Writings'', SEAP Publications, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-87727-749-1}}, p. 126. This is a translation of a lecture Chau gave in Saigon in 1925. \"Even at this moment, the so-called \"Confucian scholars (i.e. those who have studied Chinese characters, and in particular, those who have passed the degrees of ''c\u1eed nh\u00e2n'' [bachelor] and ''ti\u1ebfn s\u0129'' [doctorate]) do not know anything, I am sure, of Confucianism. Yet every time they open their mouths they use Confucianism to attack modern civilization \u2013 a civilization they do not comprehend even a tiny bit.\"</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Hanoi's short-lived [[Tonkin Free School]] suggested that broad reform was possible. In 1910, the colonial school system adopted a \"Franco-Vietnamese curriculum\", which emphasized French and alphabetic Vietnamese. The teaching of Chinese characters was discontinued in 1917.<ref name=\"Chung\">{{in lang|vi}} Ph\u00f9ng Th\u00e0nh Ch\u1ee7ng, \"[http://damau.org/archives/10281 H\u01b0\u1edbng t\u1edbi 1000 n\u0103m Th\u0103ng Long-H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]\", November 12, 2009.</ref> On December 28, 1918, Emperor [[Kh\u1ea3i \u0110\u1ecbnh]] declared that the traditional writing system no longer had official status.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> The traditional Civil Service Examination, which emphasized the command of classical Chinese, was dismantled in 1915 in [[Tonkin]] and was given for the last time at the imperial capital of [[Hu\u1ebf]] on January 4, 1919.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> The examination system, and the education system based on it, had been in effect for almost 900 years.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> <!--China itself abandoned the imperial examinations soon afterward as part of the [[May Fourth Movement]].-->\n\nThe decline of the Chinese script also led to the decline of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m given that N\u00f4m and Chinese characters are so intimately connected.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=179}} During the early half of the 20th century, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m gradually died out as qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef grew more and more standardized and popular. In an article published in 1935 by Cordier he stated that qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef is rapidly dethroning Chinese characters and is replacing ch\u1eef N\u00f4m so that by 1935 out of one hundred literate persons 70 knew qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef, 20 knew ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and 10 knew Chinese characters.<ref name=\"Cordier\">Cordier, Georges (1935), [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5658111f/f127 ''Les trois \u00e9critures utilis\u00e9es en Annam: chu-nho, chu-nom et quoc-ngu (conf\u00e9rence faite \u00e0 l'Ecole Coloniale, \u00e0 Paris, le 28 mars 1925)''], Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Enseignement Mutuel du Tonkin 15: 121.</ref>\n\n==Texts==\n[[File:Tale of Kieu, vol. 24, p.22.jpg|thumb|A page from ''[[The Tale of Kieu]]'' by [[Nguy\u1ec5n Du]]. This novel was first published in 1820 and is the best-known work in Nom. The edition shown was printed in the late 19th century.]]\n*''\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd ti\u1ec7p l\u1ee5c t\u1ed5ng t\u1ef1.''<ref name=history>''[http://lib.nomfoundation.org/collection/1/volume/115/ \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd ti\u1ec7p l\u1ee5c t\u1ed5ng t\u1ef1]'', NLVNPF-0105 R.2254.</ref> This history of Vietnam was written during the [[T\u00e2y S\u01a1n dynasty]]. The original is Han, and there is also a Nom translation.\n*Nguy\u1ec5n Du, ''The Tale of Kieu'' (1820)\n*Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u00e3i, ''Qu\u1ed1c \u00e2m thi t\u1eadp'' (\"National Language Poetry Compilation\") \n*Ph\u1ea1m \u0110\u00ecnh H\u1ed3, ''Nh\u1eadt D\u1ee5ng Th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0110\u00e0m'' (1851). A Han-to-Nom dictionary for Vietnamese speakers.\n*[[Nguy\u1ec5n \u0110\u00ecnh Chi\u1ec3u]], ''L\u1ee5c V\u00e2n Ti\u00ean'' (19th century)\n*[[\u0110\u1eb7ng Tr\u1ea7n C\u00f4n]], ''Chinh Ph\u1ee5 Ng\u00e2m Kh\u00fac'' (18th century)\n*[[H\u1ed3 Xu\u00e2n H\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (18th century) female poet\n\n==Syntax==\nThe syntax of n\u00f4m naturally follows [[Vietnamese grammar]], not [[Chinese grammar]]. For example, in n\u00f4m texts the [[Tr\u1ecbnh]] lords (1545\u20131787) are Ch\u00faa Tr\u1ecbnh (ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: {{vi-nom|\u4e3b\u912d}}) not as in Sino-Vietnamese Tr\u1ecbnh v\u01b0\u01a1ng (ch\u1eef H\u00e1n: {{vi-nom|\u912d\u738b}}). Here the character used (lord in Vietnamese, king in Chinese) is also different, but the difference in syntax is that in Vietnamese the noun \"lord\" precedes the name, whereas in Chinese \"king\" follows the name.\n\nA similar example, in Vietnamese [[Truy\u1ec7n Ki\u1ec1u]] ({{vi-nom|\u50b3\u7ff9}}, lit. \"Tale of Ki\u1ec1u\") the word \"tale\" precedes the name, but in Chinese syntax \"tale\" (''truy\u1ec7n'' {{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u50b3|\u50b3]]}}) should follow the name Ki\u1ec1u. The n\u00f4m term \"ch\u1eef N\u00f4m\" itself is an example of this. In Vietnamese n\u00f4m syntax the noun \"script\" ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\ud846\ude38|\ud846\ude38]]}}) precedes \"Southern\" ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\u5583|\u5583]]}}), whereas in ch\u1eef H\u00e1n the order is reversed and a purely Chinese ch\u1eef H\u00e1n character used instead of the locally created Ch\u1eef (ch\u1eef H\u00e1n: {{vi-nom|\u5583\u5b57}}). Similarly with gods and heroes; the syntax of the popular name [[Th\u00e1nh Gi\u00f3ng]] ({{vi-nom|\u8056\u5bb9}}) differs from his ch\u1eef H\u00e1n name Ph\u00f9 \u0110\u1ed5ng Thi\u00ean V\u01b0\u01a1ng ({{vi-nom|\u6276\u8463\u5929\u738b}}); the n\u00f4m name [[M\u1eabu Tho\u1ea3i]] ({{vi-nom|\u6bcd\u6c34}}), has a Vietnamese syntax while her ch\u1eef H\u00e1n name Th\u1ee7y cung Th\u00e1nh M\u1eabu ({{vi-nom|\u6c34\u5bae\u8056\u6bcd}}) exhibits Chinese syntax. The official Chinese [[T\u00ean ch\u1eef]] and vernacular [[T\u00ean n\u00f4m]] for village names may also have different syntax as well as different characters.<ref>Xavier Guillaume La Terre du Dragon Tome 2 \u2013 Page 59 \"Elle comprenait en g\u00e9n\u00e9ral un village principal (Xa) et les hameaux environnants (L\u00e0ng). Le village vi\u00eatnamien poss\u00e9dait alors deux noms : un nom courant ou vulgaire (T\u00ean N\u00f4m) et un nom litt\u00e9raire r\u00e9serv\u00e9 \u00e0 l'administration (T\u00ean Chu).\"</ref>\n\nChinese poems translated into N\u00f4m could retain more Chinese syntax and poetic forms than those translated into Korean or Japanese.<ref>The Columbia History of Chinese Literature -Victor H. Mair \u2013 2012  Page 1097 -\"Chinese vocabulary was largely kept in place even in poetic writings in Vietnamese using chu nom (adapted from the sinographs) phonetics. Chinese poetic forms could be maintained without the radical restructuring required by translation to a foreign syntax required in Japan and Korea.</ref> Though as literature in N\u00f4m developed it increasingly freed itself from Chinese syntax.<ref>The Vietnamese novel in French: a literary response to colonialism -Jack Andrew Yeager, University of New Hampshire \u2013 1987  Page 30 \"Nom would eventually free itself of the influence of Chinese syntax and, with the gradual hardening of Confucian philosophy, become more important than Chinese for literary production in Viet Nam. By the eighteenth century, important ...\"</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nIn ch\u1eef N\u00f4m, each monosyllabic word of Vietnamese was represented by a character, either borrowed from Chinese or locally created.\nThere was no development of a [[syllabary]] like Japanese [[kana]] or Korean [[hangul]]; in part due to the [[analytic language|analytic nature]] of Vietnamese, similar to Chinese, as opposed to the [[agglutinative]] morphology of Japanese and Korean.<ref>{{harvnb|Marr|1984|pp=141\u2013142}}: \"By the same token, some women developed word skills to the point where they could outmatch any male participants \u2014 much to the delight of their peers.9 Partly as a means to capture Vietnamese folklore in writing, the literati gradually improvised a separate ideographic system to accord with the sounds and syntax of the spoken language.10 known subsequently as nom, this unique Vietnamese script unfortunately remained even more unwieldy than the Chinese from which it was spawned. Unlike Japanese kana or Korean Hangul/no process of character simplification that resulted in a basic set of phonemes or syllables. Some of the problem lay in the tonal and nonagglutinative nature of Vietnamese as contrasted with Japanese or Korean.11 More important, however, was the attitude of most Vietnamese literati, who continued to regard Chinese as the ultimate in civilized communication and thus considered nom a form of recreation.\"</ref>\n\n===Borrowed characters===\n{{see also|Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese reading|Literary and colloquial readings of Chinese characters}}\nUnmodified Chinese characters were used in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m in three different ways.\n\nA large proportion of Vietnamese vocabulary had been borrowed from Chinese from the Tang period.\nSuch [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary]] could be written with the original Chinese character for each word, for example:{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=80\u201381}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5f79}}}} ''d\u1ecbch'' (\"service\", \"corv\u00e9e\"), from Early [[Middle Chinese]] (EMC) /jwiajk/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=371}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u672c}}}} ''b\u1ea3n'' (\"root\", \"foundation\"), from EMC /p\u0259n'/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=32}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u982d}}}} ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' (\"head\"), from EMC /d\u0259w/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=311}}\nTo represent a native Vietnamese word, one method was to use a Chinese character for a Chinese word with a similar meaning. For example, {{vi-nom|\u672c}} may also represent ''v\u1ed1n'' (\"capital, funds\"). When a character would have two readings, a diacritic may be added to the character to indicate the \"indigenous\" reading. Thus when {{vi-nom|\u672c}} is meant to be read as ''v\u1ed1n'', it is written as {{vi-nom|\u672c<sup>\u3191</sup>}},<ref>{{vi-nom|\u3191}} is a visual approximation. The ''c\u00e1''' and ''nh\u00e1y'' marks will be added to the [[Ideographic Symbols and Punctuation]] in Unicode 13.0.</ref> with a diacritic at the upper right corner. The two most common alternate reading diacritical marks are ''c\u00e1'' and ''nh\u00e1y'' (a variant form of {{vi-nom|\u4e2a}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=Proposal to Encode Two Vietnamese Alternate Reading Marks|first1=Lee|last1=Collins|author2=Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n|date=6 November 2017|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2017/17373r-viet-alt-reading-marks.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> In this case, the word ''v\u1ed1n'' is actually an earlier Chinese loan that has become accepted as Vietnamese; William Hannas claims that all such readings are similar early loans.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=80\u201381}}\n\nAlternatively, a native Vietnamese word could be written using a Chinese character for a Chinese word with a similar sound, regardless of the meaning of the Chinese word. For example, {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6c92}}}} (Early Middle Chinese /m\u0259t/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=218}}) may represent the Vietnamese word ''m\u1ed9t'' (\"one\").{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=80}}\n\nTo draw an analogy to the [[Japanese writing system]], the first two categories are similar to the ''[[on'yomi|on]]'' and [[kun'yomi|''kun'' reading]]s of Japanese [[Kanji#Readings|kanji]] respectively. The third is similar to ''[[ateji]]'', in which characters are used only for their sound value, or the [[Man'y\u014dgana]] script that became the origin of [[hiragana]] and [[katakana]].\n\n===Locally invented characters===\n[[File:Nom Character V04-5055.svg|thumb|right|upright|The Nom character for ''[[pho|ph\u1edf]]'' ({{linktext|\ud871\uddbe|}}), a popular soup made from rice noodles, was added to the Unicode 8.0 as part of CJK Unified Ideographs Extended-E (\ud871\uddbe, U+2C5BE).{{efn|The character is part of the proposed set for Extension E. See \"[http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n4358-A.pdf Code Charts - CJK Ext. E]\", (N4358-A), JTC1/SC2/WG2, Oct. 10, 2012, p. 5. The V Source code is V04-5055.}} The radical {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7c73}}}} on the left suggests that the meaning of the character is linked to rice. The phonetic component {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u9817}}}} on the right suggests that the pronunciation of the character is linked to that of \u9817 ''ph\u1edf'', and in this case the character's pronunciation and that of its phonetic component is the same.]]\nIn contrast to the few hundred Japanese [[kokuji]] and handful of Korean [[gukja]], which are mostly rarely used characters for indigenous natural phenomena, Vietnamese scribes created thousands of new characters, used throughout the language.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=79}}\n\nSimilar to the Chinese writing system, the most common kind of invented character in Nom is the phono-semantic compound, made by combining two characters or components, one suggesting the word's meaning and the other its approximate sound. For example,{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=81}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\udc27}}}} (''ba'' \"three\") is composed of the phonetic part {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5df4}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''ba'') and the semantic part {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e09}}}} \"three\". \"Father\" is also ''ba'', but written as {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7238}} (\u2ff1{{linktext|\u7236|\u5df4}}}}), while \"turtle\" is ''con ba ba'' {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6606|\u8686|\u8686}}}}.\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5a84}}}} (''m\u1eb9'' \"mother\") has {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5973}}}} \"woman\" as semantic component and {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7f8e}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''m\u1ef9'') as phonetic component.{{efn|The character \u5a84 is also used in Chinese as an alternate form of \u7f8e \"beautiful\".}}\n\nA smaller group consists of semantic compound characters, which are composed of two Chinese characters representing words of similar meaning. For example, {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud845\uddf6}}}} (''gi\u1eddi'' or ''tr\u1eddi'' \"sky\", \"heaven\") is composed of {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5929}}}} (\"sky\") and {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e0a}}}} (\"upper\").{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=81}}\n\nA few characters were obtained by modifying Chinese characters related either semantically or phonetically to the word to be represented. For example,\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85d\ude07}}}} (''\u1ea5y'' \"that', \"those\") is a simplified form of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8863}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''\u00fd'').<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=63}}</ref>\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}} (l\u00e0m \"work\", \"labour\") is a simplified form of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6feb}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''l\u1ea1m'') ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6feb}}}} > {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6c35}}}}<u>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}}</u> > {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}}).<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=56}}</ref>\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud842\udf20}}}} (m\u1ed9t 'one') comes from the right part of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6ca1}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''m\u1ed9t'').<ref>{{cite book |last=V\u0169 |first=V\u0103n K\u00ednh |date=2005 |title=\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ngh\u1ec7 Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=838}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea and Japan, phonetic systems were developed so that Chinese characters could be taught to the general public.<ref name=\"Marr141-2\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|pp=141\u2013142}}: \"Known subsequently as ''nom'', this unique Vietnamese script unfortunately remained even more unwieldy than the Chinese from which it was spawned. Unlike Japanese ''kana'' or Korean ''hangul'', there was no process of character simplification that resulted in a basic set of phonemes or syllables.\"</ref> Vietnam's educated class looked down on Nom as inferior to Han, so they were not interested in doing the work required to turn Nom into a form of writing suitable for mass communication.<ref name=\"Marr142\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|p=142}}: \"More important, however, was the attitude of most Vietnamese literati, who continued to regard Chinese as the ultimate in civilized communication and thus considered ''nom'' a form of recreation...Meanwhile, the minority of the literati who took ''nom'' writing seriously had to be careful not to offend the fraternity or be accused of subversion through circulating 'vulgar' texts.\"</ref> Like Chinese, Vietnamese is a tonal language and has nearly 5,000 distinct syllables.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=78\u201379, 82}} Neither the Korean nor the Japanese writing systems indicate tones, so they cannot be accurately applied to the Vietnamese language without significant modifications to their systems.<ref name=\"Marr141\" />\n\n===Most common characters===\nThe website chunom.org gives a frequency table of the 586 most common characters in Nom literature. According to this table, the most common 50 characters are as follows, with the modern spelling given in italics:<ref>[http://www.chunom.org/charsets/ Comparison of Character Sets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616023959/http://www.chunom.org/charsets/ |date=2013-06-16 }}, chunom.org.</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7f85}}}}</big> ''l\u00e0'' to be\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5427}}}}</big> ''v\u00e0'' and\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5404}}}}</big> ''c\u00e1c'' each; every\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6ca1}}}}</big> ''m\u1ed9t'' one\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u56fa}}}}</big> ''c\u00f3'' there is\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85f\udd51}}}}</big> ''c\u1ee7a'' of\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5f97}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c'' to get, to obtain \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud856\ude9d}}}}</big> ''trong'' in\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud850\udd2f}}}}</big> ''trong'' clear\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9b}}}}</big> (<small>or</small> <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9a}}}}</big>) ''ng\u01b0\u1eddi'' people\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5fcd}}}}</big> ''nh\u1eefng'' (plural marker)\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b78}}}}</big> ''h\u1ecdc'' to learn\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5982}}}}</big> ''nh\u01b0'' as\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8a5e}}}}</big> ''t\u1eeb'' word\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6703}}}}</big> ''h\u1ed9i'', ''g\u1ecdi'' to meet, to call \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u548d}}}}</big> ''hay'' or, good\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7a7a}}}}</big> ''kh\u00f4ng'' not\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4f53}}}}</big> ''th\u1ec3'' body, able \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u56db}}}}</big> ''t\u01b0'' four\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u62f1}}}}</big> ''c\u0169ng'' also\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\uddcd}}}}</big> ''v\u1edbi'', ''m\u1ea5y'' with, some \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6731}}}}</big> ''cho'' to give\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u793e}}}}</big> ''x\u00e3'' society, company\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5c3c}}}}</big> ''n\u00e0y'', ''n\u01a1i'' this, place\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5e95}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ec3'' to place\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u95dc}}}}</big> ''quan'' frontier, barrier, gate\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u89c0}}}}</big> ''quan'' to see\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5834}}}}</big> ''tr\u01b0\u1eddng'' school\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u672c}}}}</big> ''b\u1ea3n'', ''v\u1ed1n'', composition, financial capital\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85d\uddf1}}}}</big> ''v\u1ec1'' to return; about\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7d93}}}}</big> ''kinh'' classic works, sutra \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u884c}}}}</big> ''h\u00e0ng, h\u00e3ng, h\u00e0nh, h\u1ea1nh'' company, firm\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u822a}}}}</big> ''h\u00e0ng'' sail; navigate\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7523}}}}</big> ''s\u1ea3n'', ''s\u1eb5n'' to give birth, to be prepared \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud841\udea2}}}}</big> ''ra'' to get out\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e16}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' world; era\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u66ff}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' to replace\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u52e2}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' position, power; like that, so\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5e38}}}}</big> ''th\u01b0\u1eddng'' frequent; common, normal, usual\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e8b}}}}</big> ''s\u1ef1'' matter; event\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u59ac}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u00f3'' there; that\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6fdf}}}}</big> ''t\u00e9'' to splash\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u982d}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' head; top (of a multitude)\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6295}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' to throw, to send\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud859\udce1}}}}</big> ''m\u00e0'' but\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u606a}}}}</big> ''kh\u00e1c'' another, different; further\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e00}}}}</big> ''nh\u1ea5t'' first\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u65e6}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ebfn'' arrive, reach\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5bb6}}}}</big> ''nh\u00e0'' home, house; family.\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Standardization===\nIn 1867, the reformist [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u01b0\u1eddng T\u1ed9]] proposed a standardization of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m (along with the abolition of classical Chinese), but the new system, what he called ''qu\u1ed1c \u00e2m H\u00e1n t\u1ef1'' ({{vi-nom|\u570b\u97f3\u6f22\u5b57}} lit. \"Han characters with national pronunciations\"), was rejected by Emperor T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=101-105}} To this date, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m has never been officially standardized. As a result, a Vietnamese word can be represented by variant N\u00f4m characters. For example, the very word ''ch\u1eef'' (\"character\", \"script\"), a Chinese loan word, can be written as either {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57}}}} (Chinese character), {{vi-nom|\ud846\udd82}} (invented character, \"compound-semantic\") or {{vi-nom|\ud846\ude38}} (invented character, \"semantic-phonetic\"). For another example, the word ''b\u00e9o'' (\"fat\", \"greasy\") can be written either as {{vi-nom|\u813f}} or {{vi-nom|[[File:Chu nom fat.svg|18px|\u2ff0\u6708\u5831]]}}. Both characters are invented characters with a semantic-phonetic structure, the difference being the phonetic indicator ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8868}}}} vs. {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5831}}}}).\n\nFrom 2013, Han-Nom Revival Committee of Vietnam, an internet-based organization has started its standardization work for Ch\u1eef [[H\u00e1n N\u00f4m]]. Aiming at both ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and [[Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]] standardization, the Committee's \"Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Standardization Project<ref>[http://www.hannom-rcv.org/wi/index.php?title=%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96%E5%8C%96:%E4%BB%8B%E7%B4%B9 {{vi-nom|\u6a19\u6e96\u5316:\u4ecb\u7d39 \u2013 \u97cb\u90a3\u5a01\u7b95\uff08VI NA UY KI\uff09\u30fb\u59d4\u73ed\u5fa9\u751f\u6f22\u5583\u8d8a\u5357}}]</ref>\" is designed to determine the Standard ch\u1eef N\u00f4m among many variant N\u00f4m characters, to confirm the usage of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n in [[:vi:T\u1eeb thu\u1ea7n Vi\u1ec7t|Pure Vietnamese words]], [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese words]] (especially Vietnamese-made Sino-Vietnamese words), and [[:vi:Ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t#T\u1eeb h\u1ed7n ch\u1ee7ng|Hybrid words]], as well as to determine the ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n characters in [[Loan words]] for phonetic transliteration. Till 2015, based on discussions among many specialists of Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m, around 500 frequently-used Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m are determined and published on its website.<ref>[http://www.hannom-rcv.org/wi/index.php?title=%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96%E5%8C%96:%E9%9F%B3%E7%AF%80%E9%80%9A%E5%B8%B8 {{vi-nom|\u6a19\u6e96\u5316:\u97f3\u7bc0\u901a\u5e38 \u2013 \u97cb\u90a3\u5a01\u7b95\uff08VI NA UY KI\uff09\u30fb\u59d4\u73ed\u5fa9\u751f\u6f22\u5583\u8d8a\u5357}}]</ref>\n\n==Computer encoding==\nIn 1993, the Vietnamese government released an 8-bit coding standard for alphabetic Vietnamese ([[TCVN 5712]]:1993, or VSCII), as well as a 16-bit standard for Nom (TCVN 5773:1993).<ref>Luong Van Phan, \"[http://www.cicc.or.jp/japanese/hyoujyunka/j-af15/15-21.pdf Country Report on Current Status and Issues of e-government Vietnam \u2013 Requirements for Documentation Standards]\". The character list for the 1993 standard is given in [http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~nhan/npct-2.1.pdf N\u00f4m Proper Code Table: Version 2.1] by Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n.</ref> This group of glyphs is referred to as \"V0.\" In 1994, the [[Ideographic Rapporteur Group]] agreed to include Nom characters as part of [[Unicode]].<ref name=unicode>\"[https://www.unicode.org/uni2book/appA.pdf Han Unification History]\", ''The Unicode Standard, Version 5.0'' (2006).</ref> A revised standard, TCVN 6909:2001, defines 9,299 glyphs.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> About half of these glyphs are specific to Vietnam.<ref name=Hong>{{in lang|vi}} Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng, \"[http://nomfoundation.org/vn/du-an-nom/Kho-chu-Han-Nom-ma-hoa/Gioi-thieu-Kho-chu-Han-Nom-ma-hoa Gi\u1edbi thi\u1ec7u Kho ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m m\u00e3 ho\u00e1]\" [H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire Introduction], ''Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation''.</ref> Nom characters not already encoded were added to [[CJK Unified Ideographs Extension B|<abbr title=\"Chinese/Japanese/Korean\">CJK</abbr> Unified Ideographs Extension B]].<ref name=\"Hong\" /> (These characters have five-digit [[hexadecimal]] code points. The characters that were encoded earlier have four-digit hex.)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Code!!Characters!!Unicode block!!Standard!!Date!!V Source!!Sources\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V0||2,246||Basic Block (593), A (138), B (1,515)||TCVN 5773:1993||2001||V0-3021 to V0-4927||5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V1||3,311||Basic Block (3,110), C (1)||TCVN 6056:1995||1999||V1-4A21 to V1-6D35||2, 5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V2||3,205||Basic Block (763), A (151), B (2,291)||VHN 01:1998||2001||V2-6E21 to V2-9171||2, 5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V3||535||Basic Block (91), A (19), B (425)||VHN 02:1998||2001||V3-3021 to V3-3644||Manuscripts\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V4||785 (encoded)||Extension C||Defined as sources 1, 3, and 6||2009||V4-4021 to V4-4B2F||1, 3, 6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V04||1,028||Extension E||Unencoded V4 and V6 characters||Projected||V04-4022 to V04-583E||V4: 1, 3, 6;<br>V6: 4, manuscripts\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V5||~900||colspan=\"2\"|Proposed in 2001, but already coded||2001||None||2, 5\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\"|<small>'''Sources''': Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng,<ref name=Hong/> \"[https://www.unicode.org/unibook/ Unibook Character Browser]\", Unicode,Inc., \"Code Charts \u2013 CJK Ext. E\" (N4358-A).<ref name=CJK-E>\"[http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n4358-A.pdf Code Charts - CJK Ext. E]\", (N4358-A), JTC1/SC2/WG2, Oct. 10, 2012.</ref></small>\n|}\n\nCharacters were extracted from the following sources:\n# Ho\u00e0ng Tri\u1ec1u \u00c2n, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m T\u00e0y'' [Nom of the Tay People], 2003.\n# Institute of Linguistics, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Index], Hanoi, 1976.\n# Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng, editor, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Dictionary], 2006.\n# Father Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m, ''Gi\u00fap \u0111\u1ecdc N\u00f4m v\u00e0 H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t'' [Help with Nom and Sino-Vietnamese], 2004.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh & Nguy\u1ec5n Quang X\u1ef7, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Dictionary], Saigon, 1971.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m mi\u1ec1n Nam'' [Table of Nom in the South], 1994.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m sau th\u1ebf k\u1ef7 XVII'' [Table of Nom After the 17th Century], 1994.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Great Nom Dictionary], 1999.\n# Nguy\u1ec5n V\u0103n Huy\u00ean, ''G\u00f3p ph\u1ea7n nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u v\u0103n ho\u00e1 Vi\u1ec7t Nam'' [Contributions to the Study of Vietnamese Culture], 1995.<ref name=Hong/>\n\nThe V2, V3, and V4 proposals were developed by a group at the Han-Nom Research Institute led by Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> V4, developed in 2001, includes over 400 ideograms formerly used by the [[Tay people]] of northern Vietnam.<ref name=Hong/> This allows the Tay language to get its own registration code.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> V5 is a set of about 900 characters proposed in 2001.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> As these characters were already part of Unicode, the IRG concluded that they could not be edited and no Vietnamese code was added.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> (This is despite the fact that national codes were added retroactively for version 3.0 in 1999.) The Nom Na Group, led by Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n, published a set of nearly 20,000 Nom characters in 2005.<ref name=Ng\u00f4>Thanh Nh\u00e0n Ng\u00f4, ''[https://books.google.com/books/about/Manual_the_N%C3%B4m_Na_Coded_Character_Set.html?id=YyIOHAAACAAJ Manual, the N\u00f4m Na Coded Character Set]'', N\u00f4m Na Group, Hanoi, 2005. The set contains 19,981 characters.</ref> This set includes both the characters proposed earlier and a large group of additional characters referred to as \"V6\".<ref name=\"Hong\" /> These are mainly Han characters from Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m's dictionary which were already assigned code points. Character readings were determined manually by H\u1ed3ng's group, while Nh\u00e0n's group developed software for this purpose.<ref name=VNPF>Institute of H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m Studies and Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation, ''[http://nomfoundation.org/nom-tools/Nom-Books/54-Han_Nom_Coded_Character_Repertoire Kho Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m M\u00e3 Ho\u00e1]'' [H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire] (2008).</ref> The work of the two groups was integrated and published in 2008 as the ''H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire''.<ref name=\"VNPF\" />\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Character!!Composition!!Nom reading!!Han Viet!!English!!Code point!!V Source!!Other sources\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5427}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u53e3|\u5df4}}}}||ba||ba||[emphatic final particle]||U+5427||V0-3122||G0,J,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u50b7}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4ebb}}}}\u2ff1{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\udc89|\u661c}}}}||th\u01b0\u01a1ng||th\u01b0\u01a1ng||to love||U+50B7||V1-4C22||G1,J,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9b}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u3775|\u4eba}}}}||ng\u01b0\u1eddi||ng\u1ea1i ({{vi-nom|\u788d}})||people||U+2029B||V2-6E4F||None\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u391d}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5fc4|\u5145}}}}||su\u00f4ng||song||to become interested in||U+391D||V3-313D||G3,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud86c\uded9}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u866b|\u5f37}}}}||c\u00e0ng||c\u01b0\u1eddng ({{vi-nom|\u5f37}})||claw, pincer||U+2B2D9||V4-536F||None\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud86e\udc6f}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u671d|\u4e59}}}}||gi\u00e0u||tr\u00e0o ({{vi-nom|\u671d}})||wealth||U+2B86F||V4-405E||None\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\"|<small>'''Key:''' G0 = China ([[GB 2312]]);  G1 = China (GB 12345); G3 = China (GB 7589); GHZ = ''[[Hanyu Da Zidian]]''; J = Japan; KP= North Korea; K = South Korea; T = Taiwan.<br/>'''Sources''': [https://www.unicode.org/cgi-bin/GetUnihanData.pl? Unihan Database], [http://nomfoundation.org/ Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation], \"Code Charts \u2013 CJK Ext. E\" (N4358-A).<ref name=CJK-E/> The Han-Viet readings are from ''[http://www.hanviet.org/ H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t T\u1eeb \u0110i\u1ec3n]''.</small>\n|}</center>\n\nThe characters that do not exist in Chinese have Han-Viet readings that are based on the characters given in parenthesis. The common character for ''c\u00e0ng'' ({{vi-nom|\u5f37}}) contains the radical {{vi-nom|\u866b}} (insects).<ref name=kiem>{{in lang|vi}} Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m, ''[http://nomfoundation.org/nom-tools/Nom-Dictionary Gi\u00fap \u0111\u1ecdc N\u00f4m v\u00e0 H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t]'' [Help with Nom and Sino-Vietnamese], 2004, \"Entry c\u00e0ng\", p. 290.</ref> This radical is added redundantly to create {{vi-nom|\ud86c\uded9}}, a rare variation shown in the chart above. The character {{vi-nom|\ud86e\udc6f}} (''gi\u00e0u'') is specific to the Tay people.<ref name=\"An\">Ho\u00e0ng Tri\u1ec1u \u00c2n, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m T\u00e0y'' [Nom of the Tay People], 2003, p. 178.</ref> It has been part of the Unicode standard only since version 8.0 of June 2015, so there is still very little font and [[input method]] support for it. It is a variation of {{vi-nom|\u671d}}, the corresponding character in Vietnamese.<ref name=NomFoundation>[http://nomfoundation.org/common/nom_details.php?codepoint=63830&img=1 Detailed information: V+63830\"], Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation.<br/>\"[http://nomfoundation.org/common/show_radical.php?radical=0005&img=1 List of Unicode Radicals]\", VNPF.<br/>Ki\u1ec7m, 2004, p. 424, \"Entry gi\u00e0u.\"<br/>[http://vdict.com/gi%C3%A0u,2,0,0.html Entry gi\u00e0u]\", VDict.com.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Vietnam|Languages}}\n* [[Chinese family of scripts]]\n**[[Hanja]] in Korean\n**[[Kanji]] in Japanese\n* [[Sinoxenic]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n* {{citation\n  | first = John | last = DeFrancis | authorlink = John DeFrancis\n  | title = Colonialism and language policy in Viet Nam\n  | publisher = Mouton | year = 1977 | isbn = 978-90-279-7643-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Asia's Orthographic Dilemma | first = Wm. C. | last = Hannas\n  | publisher = University of Hawaii Press | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-0-8248-1892-0\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Vietnamese Tradition on Trial, 1920-1945 | first = David G. | last = Marr\n  | publisher = University of California Press | year = 1984 | isbn = 978-0-520-90744-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Lexicon of reconstructed pronunciation in early Middle Chinese, late Middle Chinese, and early Mandarin\n  | first = Edwin George | last = Pulleyblank | authorlink = Edwin G. Pulleyblank\n  | location = Vancouver | publisher = University of British Columbia Press | year = 1991\n  | isbn = 978-0-7748-0366-3\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Ch\u02bben, Ching-ho (n. d.). ''A Collection of Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m Scripts with Pronunciation in Qu\u1ed1c-Ng\u1eef''. Tokyo: Kei\u00f4 University.\n* Nguy\u1ec5n, \u0110\u00ecnh Ho\u00e0 (2001). ''Chuy\u00ean Kh\u1ea3o V\u1ec1 Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m = Monograph on N\u00f4m Characters''. Westminster, California: Institute of Vietnamese Studies, Viet-Hoc Pub. Dept.. {{ISBN|0-9716296-0-9}}\n* Nguy\u1ec5n, N. B. (1984). ''The State of Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m Studies: The Demotic Script of Vietnam''. Vietnamese Studies Papers. [Fairfax, Virginia]: Indochina Institute, George Mason University.\n* O'Harrow, S. (1977). ''A Short Bibliography of Sources on \"Ch\u1eef-N\u00f4m\"''. Honolulu: Asia Collection, University of Hawaii.\n*Schneider, Paul 1992. ''Dictionnaire Historique Des Id\u00e9ogrammes Vietnamiens'' / (licenci\u00e9 en droit Nice, France : Universit\u00e9 de Nice-Sophia Antipolis, R.I.A.S.E.M.)\n*Zhou Youguang {{lang|zh-cn|\u5468\u6709\u5149}} (1998). ''Bijiao wenzi xue chutan'' ({{lang|zh-cn|\u6bd4\u8f03\u6587\u5b57\u5b66\u521d\u63a2}} \"A Comparative Study of Writing Systems\"). Beijing: Yuwen chubanshe.\n*http://www.academia.edu/6797639/Rebooting_the_Vernacular_in_17th-century_Vietnam\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m}}\n*[https://www.endangeredalphabets.net/alphabets/chu-nom/ Chu-Nom - Atlas of Endangered Alphabets]\n*[http://www.chunom.org/ Chunom.org] \"This site is about Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m, the classical writing system of Vietnam.\"\n*[http://www.nomfoundation.org/ Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation]. Features a character dictionary.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130403084625/http://nlv.gov.vn/ef/en/han-nom-collection.html Han-Nom Collection], digitized manuscripts held by the National Library of Vietnam.\n*[http://www.omniglot.com/writing/chunom.htm Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m], Omniglot\n*[http://www.cjvlang.com/Writing/writsys/writviet.html The Vietnamese Writing System], Bathrobe's Chinese, Japanese & Vietnamese Writing Systems\n* [http://www.hannom-rcv.org/ Han-Nom Revival Committee of Vietnam]\n** {{in lang|vi}} [https://archive.today/20141219055417/http://www.hannom-rcv.org/wi/ VinaWiki]&nbsp;\u2013 wiki encyclopedia in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m with many articles transliterated from the [[Vietnamese Wikipedia]]\n*{{in lang|vi}} [http://www.hannom.org.vn/ Han-Nom Research Institute]\n*{{in lang|vi}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20060505105548/http://www.viethoc.com/hannom/tdnom_chidan.php T\u1ef1 \u0110i\u1ec3n Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m Tr\u00edch D\u1eabn], Vi\u1ec7n Vi\u1ec7t-H\u1ecdc\n*{{in lang|vi}} [http://ngonngu.net/index.php?fld=nnh&sub=nguam&pst=cv_lstv_01 V\u1ea5n \u0111\u1ec1 ch\u1eef vi\u1ebft nh\u00ecn t\u1eeb g\u00f3c \u0111\u1ed9 l\u1ecbch s\u1eed ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t], Tr\u1ea7n Tr\u00ed D\u00f5i\n*[https://www.kci.go.kr/kciportal/ci/sereArticleSearch/ciSereArtiView.kci?sereArticleSearchBean.artiId=ART001875760 {{Lang|zh|\u8d8a\u5357\u5317\u5c6c\u6642\u671f\u6f22\u5b57\u6587\u737b\u7570\u9ad4\u5b57\u6574\u7406\u8207\u7814\u7a76}}]\n*[http://transliterationisfun.blogspot.com/2016/02/chinese-character-and-chunom-characters.html Ch\u1eef n\u00f4m to Vietnamese Latin Converter]\n\n===Software===\nThere are a number of software tools that can produce ch\u1eef N\u00f4m characters simply by typing Vietnamese words in qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef:\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060505105536/http://www.viethoc.com/hannom/bango_intro.php HanNomIME], a Windows-based Vietnamese keyboard driver that supports H\u00e1n characters and ch\u1eef N\u00f4m.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120618040841/http://herr.atspace.eu/ Vietnamese Keyboard Set] which enables ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and H\u00e1n typing on Mac OS X.\n*[http://winvnkey.sourceforge.net/ WinVNKey], a Windows-based Vietnamese multilingual keyboard driver that supports typing ch\u1eef N\u00f4m in addition to Traditional and Simplified Chinese.\n*[http://www.chunom.org/ime/ Chunom.org Online Editor], a browser-based editor for typing ch\u1eef N\u00f4m.\nOther entry methods:\n*{{in lang|zh}} [http://www.chinesecj.com/forum/viewthread.php?tid=2596&extra=page%3D1 {{Lang|zh|\u5009\u9821\u4e4b\u53cb\u300a\u5009\u9821\u5e73\u53f02012\u300b}}] [[Cangjie input method]] for Windows that allows keyboard entry of all [[Han unification|Unicode CJK characters]] by character shape. Supports over 70,000 characters. Users may add their own characters and character combinations.\n\n===Fonts===\nCh\u1eef N\u00f4m fonts include:\n*[http://sourceforge.jp/projects/hanazono-font/releases/ Hanamin B] \u2013 Japanese font supporting nearly 90,000 characters, including those in Unicode CJK Extension C.\n*[http://vietunicode.sourceforge.net/fonts/fonts_hannom.html VietUnicode Han Nom Font Set] \u2013 Two open source TrueType fonts including Unicode CJK Extensions A and B.\n*[http://nomfoundation.org/nom-tools/Nom-Font NomNaTongLight] \u2013 TrueType font, created by the Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation, based on characters found in traditional Vietnamese wood-block prints.\n*[[Mojikyo]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150920200127/http://www.hannom-rcv.org/font.html#e Han Nom Gothic] \u2013 A [[sans-serif]] font for Chu Han Nom.\n\n{{list of writing systems}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chu Nom}}\n[[Category:Chinese scripts]]\n[[Category:Writing systems]]\n[[Category:Logographic writing systems]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese writing systems]]\n[[Category:Chinese characters]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Writing system for the Vietnamese language using Chinese characters}}\n{{Infobox Writing system\n|name=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m <br/>\ud846\ude38\u5583\n|sample=Chu nom.svg\n|imagesize=140px\n|type=[[Logographic]]\n|languages=[[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n|fam1=[[Chinese characters]]\n|sisters=[[Kanji]], [[Hanja]], [[Sawndip]], [[Khitan large script]]\n|time=13th\u2013present<br>(limited use)\n}}\n{{Contains Nom text}}\n{{Table Hanzi}}\n'''Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''' ({{linktext|lang=Vi-nom|\ud846\ude38\u5583}}, {{IPA-vi|c\u0268\u030c\u02c0 nom|IPA}}, literally 'Southern characters'),<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=5}}</ref> in earlier times also called '''Ch\u1eef Nam''' ({{linktext|lang=Vi-nom|\ud846\ude38\u5357}}) or '''Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m''' (\u570b\u97f3, \"National sound\"), is a [[logographic]] writing system formerly used to write the [[Vietnamese language]].  It used the standard set of classical [[Chinese characters]] to represent [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary]] and some native Vietnamese words, while new characters were created on the Chinese model to represent other words.<ref name=\"Ch\u1eef-n\u00f4m script\">{{cite web\n|publisher= Omniglot\n|title=Ch\u1eef-n\u00f4m script\n|url= https://www.omniglot.com/writing/chunom.htm\n}}</ref>\n\nAlthough formal writing in Vietnam was done in [[classical Chinese]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Tri T\u00e0i |date=2002 |title=Gi\u00e1o tr\u00ecnh ti\u1ebfng H\u00e1n. T\u1eadp I: C\u01a1 s\u1edf |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=5}}</ref> until the early 20th century (except for two brief interludes), ch\u1eef N\u00f4m was widely used between the 15th and 19th centuries by Vietnam's cultured elite, including women, for popular works, many in verse. One of the best-known pieces of [[Vietnamese literature]], ''[[The Tale of Ki\u1ec1u]]'', was composed in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m.\n\nIn the 1920s, the Latin-based [[Vietnamese alphabet]] created by [[Jesuit]] missionaries displaced ch\u1eef N\u00f4m as the preferred way to record Vietnamese. While Han characters are still used for decorative, historic and ceremonial value and as symbols of [[good luck]], N\u00f4m characters have fallen into disuse in any other function in modern [[Vietnam]] in favour of  the alphabet. The task of preservation and study of Vietnamese texts written in N\u00f4m (but also classical Chinese texts from Vietnam) is conducted by the [[Institute of H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m Studies]] in [[Hanoi]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe Vietnamese word ''ch\u1eef'' (character) is derived from the [[Old Chinese]] word {{Zh|c={{linktext|\u5b57}}|s=|t=|labels=no}}, meaning '[Chinese] character'.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=T\u00e0i C\u1ea9n |date=1995 |title=Gi\u00e1o tr\u00ecnh l\u1ecbch s\u1eed ng\u1eef \u00e2m ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t (s\u01a1 th\u1ea3o) |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n Gi\u00e1o d\u1ee5c |page=47}}</ref> The word ''N\u00f4m'' in ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' means 'Southern', and is derived from the [[Middle Chinese]] word {{Zh|c={{linktext|\u5357}}|s=|t=|labels=no}}, meaning 'south'.<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |pages=5, 215}}</ref>\n\nThere are many ways to write the name ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m characters. The word ''ch\u1eef'' may be written as {{vi-nom|\u5b57}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86f\udcd8(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b81)}}}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86a\uddda(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b88)}}}}, {{vi-nom|\ud846\ude38}}, {{vi-nom|\u8321}}, {{vi-nom|\u8293}}, {{nowrap|{{vi-nom|\ud86f\udff0(\u2ff0\u5b57\u6587)}}}}, {{vi-nom|\ud846\udd82}}(\u2ff0\u5b57\u5b57), {{vi-nom|\u4f47}} or {{vi-nom|\u5b81}}, while ''N\u00f4m'' may be written as {{vi-nom|\u5583}} or {{vi-nom|\u8af5}}.<ref>{{cite book |last=V\u0169 |first=V\u0103n K\u00ednh |date=2005 |title=\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ngh\u1ec7 Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |pages=293, 899}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Nguy\u1ec5n |first1=H\u1eefu Vinh |last2=\u0110\u1eb7ng |first2=Th\u1ebf Ki\u1ec7t |last3=Nguy\u1ec5n |first3=Do\u00e3n V\u01b0\u1ee3ng |last4=L\u00ea |first4=V\u0103n \u0110\u1eb7ng |last5=Nguy\u1ec5n |first5=V\u0103n S\u00e2m |last6=Nguy\u1ec5n |first6=Ng\u1ecdc B\u00edch |last7=Tr\u1ea7n |first7=Uy\u00ean Thi |date=2009 |title=T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m tr\u00edch d\u1eabn |publisher=Vi\u1ec7n Vi\u1ec7t-h\u1ecdc |pages=[http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0248.png 248], [http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0249.png 249], [http://www.vietnamtudien.org/chunom-trichdan/tr0866.png 866]}}</ref>\n\n==Terminology==\n{{main|History of writing in Vietnam}}\n''Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' is the logographic writing system of the Vietnamese language. It is based on the Chinese writing system but adds a high number of new characters to make it fit the Vietnamese language.\n\nIn Vietnamese, Chinese characters are called ''ch\u1eef H\u00e1n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57|\u6f22}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), ''H\u00e1n t\u1ef1'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u5b57}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u6587}}}} \u2018Han characters\u2019), or ''ch\u1eef nho'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57\u5112}}}} \u2018Confucian characters\u2019).<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=T\u00e0i C\u1ea9n |date=2001 |title=Ngu\u1ed3n g\u1ed1c v\u00e0 qu\u00e1 tr\u00ecnh h\u00ecnh th\u00e0nh c\u00e1ch \u0111\u1ecdc H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc qu\u1ed1c gia H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i |page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=H\u1ed9i Khai-tr\u00ed ti\u1ebfn-\u0111\u1ee9c |date=1954 |title=Vi\u1ec7t-nam t\u1ef1-\u0111i\u1ec3n |publisher=V\u0103n M\u1edbi |pages=141, 228}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=\u0110\u00e0o |first=Duy Anh |date=2005 |title=H\u00e1n-Vi\u1ec7t t\u1eeb-\u0111i\u1ec3n gi\u1ea3n y\u1ebfu |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ho\u00e1 Th\u00f4ng tin |page=281}}</ref> ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22\u6587}}}}) also means Chinese language literature (in this case, ''H\u00e1n v\u0103n'' literally means \u2018Han literature\u2019).<ref>{{cite book |author=H\u1ed9i Khai-tr\u00ed ti\u1ebfn-\u0111\u1ee9c |date=1954 |title=Vi\u1ec7t-nam t\u1ef1-\u0111i\u1ec3n |publisher=V\u0103n M\u1edbi |page=228}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=\u0110\u00e0o |first=Duy Anh |date=2005 |title=H\u00e1n-Vi\u1ec7t t\u1eeb-\u0111i\u1ec3n gi\u1ea3n y\u1ebfu |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ho\u00e1 Th\u00f4ng tin |pages=281, 900}}</ref>\n\nThe term ''H\u00e1n N\u00f4m'' ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6f22|\u5583}}}} \u2018Han and ch\u1eef N\u00f4m characters\u2019)<ref>{{cite journal |last=Tr\u1ea7n |first=V\u0103n Ch\u00e1nh |date=January 2012 |title=T\u1ea3n m\u1ea1n kinh nghi\u1ec7m h\u1ecdc ch\u1eef H\u00e1n c\u1ed5|journal=Su\u1ed1i Ngu\u1ed3n, t\u1eadp 3&4 |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n T\u1ed5ng h\u1ee3p Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=82}}</ref> in Vietnamese designates the whole body of Vietnamese premodern written materials, either written in Chinese (''ch\u1eef h\u00e1n'') or in Vietnamese (''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'').<ref>Asian research trends: a humanities and social science review \u2013 No 8 to 10 \u2013 Page 140 Yunesuko Higashi Ajia Bunka Kenky\u016b Sent\u0101 (Tokyo, Japan) \u2013 1998 \"Most of the source materials from premodern Vietnam are written in Chinese, obviously using Chinese characters; however, a portion of the literary genre is written in Vietnamese, using chu nom. Therefore, han nom is the term designating the whole body of premodern written materials..\"</ref> H\u00e1n and N\u00f4m could also be found in the same document side by side,<ref>Vietnam Courier 1984 Vol20/21 Page 63 \"Altogether about 15,000 books in Han, Nom and Han\u2014Nom have been collected. These books include royal certificates granted to deities, stories and records of deities, clan histories, family genealogies, records of cutsoms, land registers, ...\"</ref> for example, in the case of translations of books on [[Chinese medicine]].<ref>Kh\u1eafc M\u1ea1nh Tr\u1ecbnh, ''Nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: K\u1ef7 y\u1ebfu H\u1ed9i ngh\u1ecb Qu\u1ed1c t\u1ebf v\u1ec1 ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''\nVi\u1ec7n nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u H\u00e1n N\u00f4m (Vietnam), Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation \u2013 2006 \"The Di s\u1ea3n H\u00e1n N\u00f4m notes 366 entries which are solely on either medicine or pharmacy; of these 186 are written in Chinese, 50 in N\u00f4m, and 130 in a mixture of the two scripts. Many of these entries ... Vietnam were written in either N\u00f4m or H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m rather than in 'pure' Chinese. My initial impression was that the percentage of texts written in N\u00f4m was even higher. This is because for the particular medical subject I wished to investigate-[[smallpox]]-the percentage of texts written in Nom or H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m is even higher than is the percentage of texts in N\u00f4m and H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m for general medical and pharmaceutical ..\"</ref> The [[Buddhist]] history ''C\u1ed5 Ch\u00e2u Ph\u00e1p V\u00e2n ph\u1eadt b\u1ea3n h\u1ea1nh ng\u1eef l\u1ee5c'' (1752) gives the story of early [[Buddhism in Vietnam]] both in H\u00e1n script and in a parallel N\u00f4m translation.<ref>Wynn Wilcox ''Vietnam and the West: New Approaches'' 2010- Page 31 \"At least one Buddhist text, the C\u1ed5 Ch\u00e2u Ph\u00e1p V\u00e2n ph\u1eadt b\u1ea3n h\u1ea1nh ng\u1eef l\u1ee5c (CCPVP), preserves a story in H\u00e1n script about the early years of Buddhist influence in Vietnam and gives a parallel N\u00f4m translation.\"</ref> The Jesuit [[Girolamo Maiorica]] (1605\u20131656) had also used parallel H\u00e1n and N\u00f4m texts.\n\nThe term ''ch\u1eef qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef'' ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\ud846\ude38|\ud846\ude38]][[wikt:\u570b|\u570b]][[wikt:\u8a9e|\u8a9e]]}} \"national language script\") refers to the [[romanized]] [[writing system]] based on the [[Vietnamese alphabet]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Tu duc thanh che tu hoc giai nghia ca.jpg|thumb|250px|A page from ''T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c Th\u00e1nh Ch\u1ebf T\u1ef1 H\u1ecdc Gi\u1ea3i Ngh\u0129a Ca'' ({{vi-nom|\u55e3\u5fb7\u8056\u88fd\u5b57\u5b78\u89e3\u7fa9\u6b4c}}), a 19th-century primer for teaching Vietnamese children Chinese characters. The work is attributed to Emperor [[T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c]], the 4th Emperor of the Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty. In this primer, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m is used to gloss the Chinese characters, for example, {{vi-nom|\ud845\uddf6}} is used to gloss {{vi-nom|\u5929}}.]]\nChinese characters were introduced to Vietnam after the [[Han dynasty]] conquered the country in 111 BC. Independence was achieved in 939, but [[Literary Chinese]] was adopted for official purposes in 1010.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=78\u201379, 82}} For most of the period up to the early 20th century, formal writing was indistinguishable from contemporaneous classical Chinese works produced in China, Korea, and Japan.<ref name=\"Marr141\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|p=141}}: \"Because the Chinese characters were pronounced according to Vietnamese preferences, and because certain stylistic modifications occurred over time, later scholars came to refer to a hybrid \"Sino-Vietnamese\" (Han-Viet) language. However, there would seem to be no more justification for this term than for a fifteenth-century \"Latin-English\" versus the Latin written contemporaneously in Rome.\"</ref>\n\nVietnamese scholars were thus intimately familiar with Chinese writing.  In order to record their native language, they applied the structural principles of Chinese characters to develop ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m''.  The new script was mostly used to record folk songs and for other popular literature.{{sfn|Marr|1984|p=141}}  Vietnamese written in ''ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' briefly replaced Chinese for official purposes under the [[H\u1ed3 dynasty]] (1400\u20131407) and under the [[T\u00e2y S\u01a1n]] (1778\u20131802), but in both cases this was swiftly reversed.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=32, 38}}\n\n===Earliest evidence===\n\nThe use of Chinese characters to write the Vietnamese language can be traced to an inscription with the two characters \"{{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u5e03|\u5e03]][[:wikt:\u84cb|\u84cb]]}}\", as part of the posthumous title of [[Ph\u00f9ng H\u01b0ng]], a national hero who succeeded in expelling the Chinese, albeit briefly in the late 8th century. These two characters literally mean \"cloth\" + \"cover\" in Chinese but when pronounced by the Vietnamese, the phonetic value is employed to represent ''vua c\u00e1i'' (\"great king\"), or archaic Vietnamese ''b\u1ed1 c\u00e1i'' (\"father and mother\", i.e. as respectable as one's parents). During the 10th century, the founder of the [[\u0110inh dynasty]] (968-979) named the country ''\u0110\u1ea1i C\u1ed3 Vi\u1ec7t ''({{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u5927|\u5927]][[:wikt:\u77bf|\u77bf]][[:wikt:\u8d8a|\u8d8a]]}}). The second character of this title is another early example of using Chinese characters to represent Vietnamese native words, although which word it represents is still debated.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=21\u201323}}<ref>Keith Weller Taylor ''The Birth of Vietnam'' 1976 \u2013 Page 220 \"The earliest example of Vietnamese character writing, as we have noted earlier, is for the words bo and cai in the posthumous title given to Phung Hung. Although Vietnamese character writing was eventually developed for literary purposes\"</ref>\n\nThe oldest surviving objects with ch\u1eef N\u00f4m inscriptions are a stele (1209) at B\u1ea3o \u00c2n temple containing 18 characters naming villages and people, and a stele at H\u1ed9 Th\u00e0nh S\u01a1n in [[Ninh B\u00ecnh Province]] (1343), listing 20 villages.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=23}}<ref>Laurence C. Thompson A Vietnamese Reference Grammar 1987 Page 53 \"This stele at Ho-th\u00e0nh-s\u01a1n is the earliest irrefutable piece of evidence of this writing system, which is called in Vietnamese ch\u1eef n\u00f4m (chu 'written word', nom 'popular language', probably ultimately related to nam 'south'-note that the ...\"</ref>\n\nThe first literary writing in Vietnamese is said to have been an [[incantation]] in verse composed in 1282 by the Minister of Justice [[Nguy\u1ec5n Thuy\u00ean]] and thrown into the [[Red River (Asia)|Red River]] to expel a menacing [[crocodile]].{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=23}} The oldest Nom text that is still extant is the collected poetry of Emperor [[Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng]] written in the 13th century.<ref name=\"Tong\">{{in lang|vi}} Tr\u1ea7n Nh\u00e2n T\u00f4ng, ''[[s:vi:C\u01b0 tr\u1ea7n l\u1ea1c \u0111\u1ea1o ph\u00fa|C\u01b0 tr\u1ea7n l\u1ea1c \u0111\u1ea1o ph\u00fa]]''</ref>\n\n===H\u1ed3 dynasty (1400\u201307) and Ming conquest (1407\u201327)===\n\nDuring the seven years of the [[H\u1ed3 dynasty]] (1400\u201307) Classical Chinese was discouraged in favor of vernacular Vietnamese written in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m, which became the official script. The emperor [[H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly]] even ordered the translation of the [[Book of Documents]] into N\u00f4m and pushed for reinterpretation of Confucian thoughts in his book ''Minh \u0111\u1ea1o''.<ref>[http://www.nguoiduatin.vn/nhin-lai-cuoc-cai-cach-cua-ho-quy-ly-600-nam-truoc-a59764.html \"Reexamining the Reforms of H\u1ed3 Qu\u00fd Ly 600 years ago\"]</ref> These efforts were reversed with the fall of the H\u1ed3 and [[fourth Chinese domination|Chinese conquest of 1407]], lasting twenty years, during which use of the vernacular language and demotic script were suppressed.<ref>{{harvnb|Hannas|1997|p=83}}: \"An exception was during the brief H\u1ed3 dynasty (1400\u201307), when Chinese was abolished and ch\u1eef N\u00f4m became the official script, but the subsequent Chinese invasion and twenty-year occupation put an end to that (Helmut Martin 1982:34).\"</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Ming dynasty occupation of Vietnam]], ch\u1eef N\u00f4m printing blocks, texts and inscriptions were thoroughly destroyed; as a result the earliest surviving texts of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m post-date the occupation.<ref>Mark W. McLeod, Thi Dieu Nguyen ''Culture and Customs of Vietnam'' 2001 Page 68  \u2013  \"In part because of the ravages of the Ming occupation \u2014 the invaders destroyed or removed many Viet texts and the blocks for printing them \u2014 the earliest body of nom texts that we have dates from the early post-occupation era ...\"</ref>\n\n===L\u00ea (1428\u20131788), T\u00e2y S\u01a1n (1788\u20131802) and Nguy\u1ec5n dynasties (1802\u20131945) ===\n[[File:Nh\u1eadt d\u1ee5ng th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0111\u00e0m, p. 38.jpg|thumb|A page from the bilingual dictionary ''Nh\u1eadt d\u1ee5ng th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0111\u00e0m'' (1851). Characters representing words in ''H\u00e1n'' (Chinese) are explained in ''N\u00f4m'' (Vietnamese).]]\nAmong the earlier works in N\u00f4m of this era are the writings of [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u00e3i]] (1380\u20131442).<ref name=\"McLeod\">Mark W. McLeod, Thi Dieu Nguyen, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=a2TerRF1j74C&dq= Culture and Customs of Vietnam]'', Greenwood Publishing Group, 2001, p.  68.</ref> The corpus of N\u00f4m writings grew over time as did more scholarly compilations of the script itself. [[Tr\u1ecbnh Th\u1ecb Ng\u1ecdc Tr\u00fac]], consort of King [[L\u00ea Th\u1ea7n T\u00f4ng]], is generally given credit for ''{{lang|vi|[[Ch\u1ec9 nam ng\u1ecdc \u00e2m gi\u1ea3i ngh\u0129a]]}}'' (the Explication of the Guide to Jeweled Sounds), a 24,000-character bilingual Han-to-Nom [[dictionary]] compiled between the 15th and 18th centuries, most likely in 1641 or 1761.<ref name=chu>Vi\u1ebft Lu\u00e2n Chu, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=-XZuAAAAMAAJ&q= Thanh H\u00f3a, th\u1ebf v\u00e0 l\u1ef1c m\u1edbi trong th\u1ebf k\u1ef7 XXI]'', 2003, p. 52</ref><ref name=\"Phan 2013\">{{cite journal|title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and the Taming of the South: A Bilingual Defense for Vernacular Writing in the ''{{lang|vi|Ch\u1ec9 Nam Ng\u1ecdc \u00c2m Gi\u1ea3i Ngh\u0129a|nocat=true}}''|first=John|last=Phan|journal=[[Journal of Vietnamese Studies]]|location=Oakland, California|publisher=University of California Press|year=2013|volume=8|issue=1|page=1|jstor=10.1525/vs.2013.8.1.1|doi=10.1525/vs.2013.8.1.1}}</ref>\n\nWhile almost all official writings and documents continued to be written in [[classical Chinese]] until the early 20th century, N\u00f4m was the preferred script for literary compositions of the cultural elites. N\u00f4m reached its golden period with the Nguy\u1ec5n dynasty in the 19th century as it became a vehicle for diverse genres, from novels to theatrical pieces, and instructional manuals. Apogees of Vietnamese literature emerged with [[Nguy\u1ec5n Du]]'s ''[[The Tale of Ki\u1ec1u]]''<ref>B. N. Ng\u00f4 \"The Vietnamese Language Learning Framework\" \u2013 ''Journal of Southeast Asian Language and Teaching'', 2001 \"... to a word, is most frequently represented by combining two Chinese characters, one of which indicates the sound and the other the meaning. From the fifteenth to the nineteenth century many major works of Vietnamese poetry were composed in ch\u1eef n\u00f4m, including Truy\u1ec7n Ki\u1ec1u\"</ref> and [[H\u1ed3 Xu\u00e2n H\u01b0\u01a1ng]]'s poetry. Although literacy in premodern Vietnam was limited to just 3 to 5 percent of the population,{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=78}} nearly every village had someone who could read Nom aloud for the benefit of other villagers.{{sfn|Marr|1984|p=142}} Thus these N\u00f4m works circulated orally in the villages, making it accessible even to the illiterates.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=44-46}}\n\nIn 1838, [[Jean-Louis Taberd]] compiled a Nom dictionary, helping with the standardization of the script.<ref name=\"Taberd\">Taberd, J.L., ''[http://staging.nomfoundation.org/taberd/ Dictionarium Anamitico-Latinum] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626064515/http://staging.nomfoundation.org/taberd/ |date=2013-06-26 }}'', 1838. This is a revision of a dictionary by Pierre-Joseph [[Pigneau de B\u00e9hain]] compiled in 1772\u20131773 and reprinted in 1884.</ref> In 1867, Catholic scholar [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u01b0\u1eddng T\u1ed9]] made the bold move to petition the Emperor [[T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c]] to adopt N\u00f4m as the official script. The court failed to make a break with chu Nho but N\u00f4m did gain some sanction as ''Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m'', i.e. the national speech.<ref name=\"Dinh\">Quyen Vuong Dinh, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uB2OAAAAMAAJ&q= V\u0103n b\u1ea3n qu\u1ea3n l\u00fd nh\u00e0 n\u01b0\u1edbc v\u00e0 c\u00f4ng t\u00e1c c\u00f4ng v\u0103n, gi\u1ea5y t\u1edd th\u1eddi phong ki\u1ebfn Vi\u1ec7t Nam]'', 2002, p. 50. The decree is entitled, ''Xin khoan dung Qu\u1ed1c \u00c2m'' (\"Please respect the national voice.\")</ref>\n\n===French Indochina and the Latin alphabet===\nFrom the latter half of the 19th century onwards, the [[Cochinchina|French colonial authorities]] discouraged or simply banned the use of classical Chinese, and promoted the use of the Vietnamese alphabet, which they viewed as a stepping stone toward learning French. Language reform movements in other Asian nations stimulated Vietnamese interest in the subject. Following the [[Russo-Japanese War]] of 1905, Japan was increasingly cited as a model for modernization. The Confucian education system was compared unfavorably to the Japanese system of public education. According to a polemic by writer [[Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh]], \"so-called Confucian scholars\" lacked knowledge of the modern world, as well as real understanding of Han literature. Their degrees showed only that they had learned how to write characters, he claimed.<ref>Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh, \"Monarchy and Democracy\", ''Phan Ch\u00e2u Trinh and His Political Writings'', SEAP Publications, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-87727-749-1}}, p. 126. This is a translation of a lecture Chau gave in Saigon in 1925. \"Even at this moment, the so-called \"Confucian scholars (i.e. those who have studied Chinese characters, and in particular, those who have passed the degrees of ''c\u1eed nh\u00e2n'' [bachelor] and ''ti\u1ebfn s\u0129'' [doctorate]) do not know anything, I am sure, of Confucianism. Yet every time they open their mouths they use Confucianism to attack modern civilization \u2013 a civilization they do not comprehend even a tiny bit.\"</ref>\n\nThe popularity of Hanoi's short-lived [[Tonkin Free School]] suggested that broad reform was possible. In 1910, the colonial school system adopted a \"Franco-Vietnamese curriculum\", which emphasized French and alphabetic Vietnamese. The teaching of Chinese characters was discontinued in 1917.<ref name=\"Chung\">{{in lang|vi}} Ph\u00f9ng Th\u00e0nh Ch\u1ee7ng, \"[http://damau.org/archives/10281 H\u01b0\u1edbng t\u1edbi 1000 n\u0103m Th\u0103ng Long-H\u00e0 N\u1ed9i]\", November 12, 2009.</ref> On December 28, 1918, Emperor [[Kh\u1ea3i \u0110\u1ecbnh]] declared that the traditional writing system no longer had official status.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> The traditional Civil Service Examination, which emphasized the command of classical Chinese, was dismantled in 1915 in [[Tonkin]] and was given for the last time at the imperial capital of [[Hu\u1ebf]] on January 4, 1919.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> The examination system, and the education system based on it, had been in effect for almost 900 years.<ref name=\"Chung\" /> <!--China itself abandoned the imperial examinations soon afterward as part of the [[May Fourth Movement]].-->\n\nThe decline of the Chinese script also led to the decline of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m given that N\u00f4m and Chinese characters are so intimately connected.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|p=179}} During the early half of the 20th century, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m gradually died out as qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef grew more and more standardized and popular. In an article published in 1935 by Cordier he stated that qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef is rapidly dethroning Chinese characters and is replacing ch\u1eef N\u00f4m so that by 1935 out of one hundred literate persons 70 knew qu\u1ed1c ng\u1eef, 20 knew ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and 10 knew Chinese characters.<ref name=\"Cordier\">Cordier, Georges (1935), [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k5658111f/f127 ''Les trois \u00e9critures utilis\u00e9es en Annam: chu-nho, chu-nom et quoc-ngu (conf\u00e9rence faite \u00e0 l'Ecole Coloniale, \u00e0 Paris, le 28 mars 1925)''], Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 d'Enseignement Mutuel du Tonkin 15: 121.</ref>\n\n==Texts==\n[[File:Tale of Kieu, vol. 24, p.22.jpg|thumb|A page from ''[[The Tale of Kieu]]'' by [[Nguy\u1ec5n Du]]. This novel was first published in 1820 and is the best-known work in Nom. The edition shown was printed in the late 19th century.]]\n*''\u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd ti\u1ec7p l\u1ee5c t\u1ed5ng t\u1ef1.''<ref name=history>''[http://lib.nomfoundation.org/collection/1/volume/115/ \u0110\u1ea1i Vi\u1ec7t s\u1eed k\u00fd ti\u1ec7p l\u1ee5c t\u1ed5ng t\u1ef1]'', NLVNPF-0105 R.2254.</ref> This history of Vietnam was written during the [[T\u00e2y S\u01a1n dynasty]]. The original is Han, and there is also a Nom translation.\n*Nguy\u1ec5n Du, ''The Tale of Kieu'' (1820)\n*Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u00e3i, ''Qu\u1ed1c \u00e2m thi t\u1eadp'' (\"National Language Poetry Compilation\") \n*Ph\u1ea1m \u0110\u00ecnh H\u1ed3, ''Nh\u1eadt D\u1ee5ng Th\u01b0\u1eddng \u0110\u00e0m'' (1851). A Han-to-Nom dictionary for Vietnamese speakers.\n*[[Nguy\u1ec5n \u0110\u00ecnh Chi\u1ec3u]], ''L\u1ee5c V\u00e2n Ti\u00ean'' (19th century)\n*[[\u0110\u1eb7ng Tr\u1ea7n C\u00f4n]], ''Chinh Ph\u1ee5 Ng\u00e2m Kh\u00fac'' (18th century)\n*[[H\u1ed3 Xu\u00e2n H\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (18th century) female poet\n\n==Syntax==\nThe syntax of n\u00f4m naturally follows [[Vietnamese grammar]], not [[Chinese grammar]]. For example, in n\u00f4m texts the [[Tr\u1ecbnh]] lords (1545\u20131787) are Ch\u00faa Tr\u1ecbnh (ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: {{vi-nom|\u4e3b\u912d}}) not as in Sino-Vietnamese Tr\u1ecbnh v\u01b0\u01a1ng (ch\u1eef H\u00e1n: {{vi-nom|\u912d\u738b}}). Here the character used (lord in Vietnamese, king in Chinese) is also different, but the difference in syntax is that in Vietnamese the noun \"lord\" precedes the name, whereas in Chinese \"king\" follows the name.\n\nA similar example, in Vietnamese [[Truy\u1ec7n Ki\u1ec1u]] ({{vi-nom|\u50b3\u7ff9}}, lit. \"Tale of Ki\u1ec1u\") the word \"tale\" precedes the name, but in Chinese syntax \"tale\" (''truy\u1ec7n'' {{vi-nom|[[:wikt:\u50b3|\u50b3]]}}) should follow the name Ki\u1ec1u. The n\u00f4m term \"ch\u1eef N\u00f4m\" itself is an example of this. In Vietnamese n\u00f4m syntax the noun \"script\" ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\ud846\ude38|\ud846\ude38]]}}) precedes \"Southern\" ({{vi-nom|[[wikt:\u5583|\u5583]]}}), whereas in ch\u1eef H\u00e1n the order is reversed and a purely Chinese ch\u1eef H\u00e1n character used instead of the locally created Ch\u1eef (ch\u1eef H\u00e1n: {{vi-nom|\u5583\u5b57}}). Similarly with gods and heroes; the syntax of the popular name [[Th\u00e1nh Gi\u00f3ng]] ({{vi-nom|\u8056\u5bb9}}) differs from his ch\u1eef H\u00e1n name Ph\u00f9 \u0110\u1ed5ng Thi\u00ean V\u01b0\u01a1ng ({{vi-nom|\u6276\u8463\u5929\u738b}}); the n\u00f4m name [[M\u1eabu Tho\u1ea3i]] ({{vi-nom|\u6bcd\u6c34}}), has a Vietnamese syntax while her ch\u1eef H\u00e1n name Th\u1ee7y cung Th\u00e1nh M\u1eabu ({{vi-nom|\u6c34\u5bae\u8056\u6bcd}}) exhibits Chinese syntax. The official Chinese [[T\u00ean ch\u1eef]] and vernacular [[T\u00ean n\u00f4m]] for village names may also have different syntax as well as different characters.<ref>Xavier Guillaume La Terre du Dragon Tome 2 \u2013 Page 59 \"Elle comprenait en g\u00e9n\u00e9ral un village principal (Xa) et les hameaux environnants (L\u00e0ng). Le village vi\u00eatnamien poss\u00e9dait alors deux noms : un nom courant ou vulgaire (T\u00ean N\u00f4m) et un nom litt\u00e9raire r\u00e9serv\u00e9 \u00e0 l'administration (T\u00ean Chu).\"</ref>\n\nChinese poems translated into N\u00f4m could retain more Chinese syntax and poetic forms than those translated into Korean or Japanese.<ref>The Columbia History of Chinese Literature -Victor H. Mair \u2013 2012  Page 1097 -\"Chinese vocabulary was largely kept in place even in poetic writings in Vietnamese using chu nom (adapted from the sinographs) phonetics. Chinese poetic forms could be maintained without the radical restructuring required by translation to a foreign syntax required in Japan and Korea.</ref> Though as literature in N\u00f4m developed it increasingly freed itself from Chinese syntax.<ref>The Vietnamese novel in French: a literary response to colonialism -Jack Andrew Yeager, University of New Hampshire \u2013 1987  Page 30 \"Nom would eventually free itself of the influence of Chinese syntax and, with the gradual hardening of Confucian philosophy, become more important than Chinese for literary production in Viet Nam. By the eighteenth century, important ...\"</ref>\n\n==Characters==\nIn ch\u1eef N\u00f4m, each monosyllabic word of Vietnamese was represented by a character, either borrowed from Chinese or locally created.\nThere was no development of a [[syllabary]] like Japanese [[kana]] or Korean [[hangul]]; in part due to the [[analytic language|analytic nature]] of Vietnamese, similar to Chinese, as opposed to the [[agglutinative]] morphology of Japanese and Korean.<ref>{{harvnb|Marr|1984|pp=141\u2013142}}: \"By the same token, some women developed word skills to the point where they could outmatch any male participants \u2014 much to the delight of their peers.9 Partly as a means to capture Vietnamese folklore in writing, the literati gradually improvised a separate ideographic system to accord with the sounds and syntax of the spoken language.10 known subsequently as nom, this unique Vietnamese script unfortunately remained even more unwieldy than the Chinese from which it was spawned. Unlike Japanese kana or Korean Hangul/no process of character simplification that resulted in a basic set of phonemes or syllables. Some of the problem lay in the tonal and nonagglutinative nature of Vietnamese as contrasted with Japanese or Korean.11 More important, however, was the attitude of most Vietnamese literati, who continued to regard Chinese as the ultimate in civilized communication and thus considered nom a form of recreation.\"</ref>\n\n===Borrowed characters===\n{{see also|Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese reading|Literary and colloquial readings of Chinese characters}}\nUnmodified Chinese characters were used in ch\u1eef N\u00f4m in three different ways.\n\nA large proportion of Vietnamese vocabulary had been borrowed from Chinese from the Tang period.\nSuch [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary]] could be written with the original Chinese character for each word, for example:{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=80\u201381}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5f79}}}} ''d\u1ecbch'' (\"service\", \"corv\u00e9e\"), from Early [[Middle Chinese]] (EMC) /jwiajk/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=371}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u672c}}}} ''b\u1ea3n'' (\"root\", \"foundation\"), from EMC /p\u0259n'/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=32}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u982d}}}} ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' (\"head\"), from EMC /d\u0259w/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=311}}\nTo represent a native Vietnamese word, one method was to use a Chinese character for a Chinese word with a similar meaning. For example, {{vi-nom|\u672c}} may also represent ''v\u1ed1n'' (\"capital, funds\"). When a character would have two readings, a diacritic may be added to the character to indicate the \"indigenous\" reading. Thus when {{vi-nom|\u672c}} is meant to be read as ''v\u1ed1n'', it is written as {{vi-nom|\u672c<sup>\u3191</sup>}},<ref>{{vi-nom|\u3191}} is a visual approximation. The ''c\u00e1''' and ''nh\u00e1y'' marks will be added to the [[Ideographic Symbols and Punctuation]] in Unicode 13.0.</ref> with a diacritic at the upper right corner. The two most common alternate reading diacritical marks are ''c\u00e1'' and ''nh\u00e1y'' (a variant form of {{vi-nom|\u4e2a}}).<ref>{{cite web|title=Proposal to Encode Two Vietnamese Alternate Reading Marks|first1=Lee|last1=Collins|author2=Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n|date=6 November 2017|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2017/17373r-viet-alt-reading-marks.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> In this case, the word ''v\u1ed1n'' is actually an earlier Chinese loan that has become accepted as Vietnamese; William Hannas claims that all such readings are similar early loans.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=80\u201381}}\n\nAlternatively, a native Vietnamese word could be written using a Chinese character for a Chinese word with a similar sound, regardless of the meaning of the Chinese word. For example, {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6c92}}}} (Early Middle Chinese /m\u0259t/{{sfn|Pulleyblank|1991|p=218}}) may represent the Vietnamese word ''m\u1ed9t'' (\"one\").{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=80}}\n\nTo draw an analogy to the [[Japanese writing system]], the first two categories are similar to the ''[[on'yomi|on]]'' and [[kun'yomi|''kun'' reading]]s of Japanese [[Kanji#Readings|kanji]] respectively. The third is similar to ''[[ateji]]'', in which characters are used only for their sound value, or the [[Man'y\u014dgana]] script that became the origin of [[hiragana]] and [[katakana]].\n\n===Locally invented characters===\n[[File:Nom Character V04-5055.svg|thumb|right|upright|The Nom character for ''[[pho|ph\u1edf]]'' ({{linktext|\ud871\uddbe|}}), a popular soup made from rice noodles, was added to the Unicode 8.0 as part of CJK Unified Ideographs Extended-E (\ud871\uddbe, U+2C5BE).{{efn|The character is part of the proposed set for Extension E. See \"[http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n4358-A.pdf Code Charts - CJK Ext. E]\", (N4358-A), JTC1/SC2/WG2, Oct. 10, 2012, p. 5. The V Source code is V04-5055.}} The radical {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7c73}}}} on the left suggests that the meaning of the character is linked to rice. The phonetic component {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u9817}}}} on the right suggests that the pronunciation of the character is linked to that of \u9817 ''ph\u1edf'', and in this case the character's pronunciation and that of its phonetic component is the same.]]\nIn contrast to the few hundred Japanese [[kokuji]] and handful of Korean [[gukja]], which are mostly rarely used characters for indigenous natural phenomena, Vietnamese scribes created thousands of new characters, used throughout the language.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=79}}\n\nSimilar to the Chinese writing system, the most common kind of invented character in Nom is the phono-semantic compound, made by combining two characters or components, one suggesting the word's meaning and the other its approximate sound. For example,{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=81}}\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\udc27}}}} (''ba'' \"three\") is composed of the phonetic part {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5df4}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''ba'') and the semantic part {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e09}}}} \"three\". \"Father\" is also ''ba'', but written as {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7238}} (\u2ff1{{linktext|\u7236|\u5df4}}}}), while \"turtle\" is ''con ba ba'' {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6606|\u8686|\u8686}}}}.\n* {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5a84}}}} (''m\u1eb9'' \"mother\") has {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5973}}}} \"woman\" as semantic component and {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7f8e}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''m\u1ef9'') as phonetic component.{{efn|The character \u5a84 is also used in Chinese as an alternate form of \u7f8e \"beautiful\".}}\n\nA smaller group consists of semantic compound characters, which are composed of two Chinese characters representing words of similar meaning. For example, {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud845\uddf6}}}} (''gi\u1eddi'' or ''tr\u1eddi'' \"sky\", \"heaven\") is composed of {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5929}}}} (\"sky\") and {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e0a}}}} (\"upper\").{{sfn|Hannas|1997|p=81}}\n\nA few characters were obtained by modifying Chinese characters related either semantically or phonetically to the word to be represented. For example,\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85d\ude07}}}} (''\u1ea5y'' \"that', \"those\") is a simplified form of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8863}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''\u00fd'').<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=63}}</ref>\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}} (l\u00e0m \"work\", \"labour\") is a simplified form of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6feb}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''l\u1ea1m'') ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6feb}}}} > {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6c35}}}}<u>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}}</u> > {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u722b}}}}).<ref>{{cite book |last=Nguy\u1ec5n |first=Khu\u00ea |date=2009 |title=Ch\u1eef N\u00f4m: c\u01a1 s\u1edf v\u00e0 n\u00e2ng cao |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Qu\u1ed1c gia Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=56}}</ref>\n* the N\u00f4m character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud842\udf20}}}} (m\u1ed9t 'one') comes from the right part of the Chinese character {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6ca1}}}} (Sino-Vietnamese reading: ''m\u1ed9t'').<ref>{{cite book |last=V\u0169 |first=V\u0103n K\u00ednh |date=2005 |title=\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m |publisher=Nh\u00e0 xu\u1ea5t b\u1ea3n V\u0103n ngh\u1ec7 Th\u00e0nh ph\u1ed1 H\u1ed3 Ch\u00ed Minh |page=838}}</ref>\n\nIn Korea and Japan, phonetic systems were developed so that Chinese characters could be taught to the general public.<ref name=\"Marr141-2\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|pp=141\u2013142}}: \"Known subsequently as ''nom'', this unique Vietnamese script unfortunately remained even more unwieldy than the Chinese from which it was spawned. Unlike Japanese ''kana'' or Korean ''hangul'', there was no process of character simplification that resulted in a basic set of phonemes or syllables.\"</ref> Vietnam's educated class looked down on Nom as inferior to Han, so they were not interested in doing the work required to turn Nom into a form of writing suitable for mass communication.<ref name=\"Marr142\">{{harvnb|Marr|1984|p=142}}: \"More important, however, was the attitude of most Vietnamese literati, who continued to regard Chinese as the ultimate in civilized communication and thus considered ''nom'' a form of recreation...Meanwhile, the minority of the literati who took ''nom'' writing seriously had to be careful not to offend the fraternity or be accused of subversion through circulating 'vulgar' texts.\"</ref> Like Chinese, Vietnamese is a tonal language and has nearly 5,000 distinct syllables.{{sfn|Hannas|1997|pp=78\u201379, 82}} Neither the Korean nor the Japanese writing systems indicate tones, so they cannot be accurately applied to the Vietnamese language without significant modifications to their systems.<ref name=\"Marr141\" />\n\n===Most common characters===\nThe website chunom.org gives a frequency table of the 586 most common characters in Nom literature. According to this table, the most common 50 characters are as follows, with the modern spelling given in italics:<ref>[http://www.chunom.org/charsets/ Comparison of Character Sets] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616023959/http://www.chunom.org/charsets/ |date=2013-06-16 }}, chunom.org.</ref>\n\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7f85}}}}</big> ''l\u00e0'' to be\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5427}}}}</big> ''v\u00e0'' and\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5404}}}}</big> ''c\u00e1c'' each; every\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6ca1}}}}</big> ''m\u1ed9t'' one\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u56fa}}}}</big> ''c\u00f3'' there is\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85f\udd51}}}}</big> ''c\u1ee7a'' of\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5f97}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c'' to get, to obtain \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud856\ude9d}}}}</big> ''trong'' in\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud850\udd2f}}}}</big> ''trong'' clear\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9b}}}}</big> (<small>or</small> <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9a}}}}</big>) ''ng\u01b0\u1eddi'' people\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5fcd}}}}</big> ''nh\u1eefng'' (plural marker)\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b78}}}}</big> ''h\u1ecdc'' to learn\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5982}}}}</big> ''nh\u01b0'' as\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8a5e}}}}</big> ''t\u1eeb'' word\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6703}}}}</big> ''h\u1ed9i'', ''g\u1ecdi'' to meet, to call \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u548d}}}}</big> ''hay'' or, good\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7a7a}}}}</big> ''kh\u00f4ng'' not\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4f53}}}}</big> ''th\u1ec3'' body, able \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u56db}}}}</big> ''t\u01b0'' four\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u62f1}}}}</big> ''c\u0169ng'' also\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\uddcd}}}}</big> ''v\u1edbi'', ''m\u1ea5y'' with, some \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6731}}}}</big> ''cho'' to give\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u793e}}}}</big> ''x\u00e3'' society, company\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5c3c}}}}</big> ''n\u00e0y'', ''n\u01a1i'' this, place\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5e95}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ec3'' to place\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u95dc}}}}</big> ''quan'' frontier, barrier, gate\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u89c0}}}}</big> ''quan'' to see\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5834}}}}</big> ''tr\u01b0\u1eddng'' school\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u672c}}}}</big> ''b\u1ea3n'', ''v\u1ed1n'', composition, financial capital\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud85d\uddf1}}}}</big> ''v\u1ec1'' to return; about\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7d93}}}}</big> ''kinh'' classic works, sutra \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u884c}}}}</big> ''h\u00e0ng, h\u00e3ng, h\u00e0nh, h\u1ea1nh'' company, firm\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u822a}}}}</big> ''h\u00e0ng'' sail; navigate\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u7523}}}}</big> ''s\u1ea3n'', ''s\u1eb5n'' to give birth, to be prepared \n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud841\udea2}}}}</big> ''ra'' to get out\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e16}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' world; era\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u66ff}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' to replace\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u52e2}}}}</big> ''th\u1ebf'' position, power; like that, so\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5e38}}}}</big> ''th\u01b0\u1eddng'' frequent; common, normal, usual\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e8b}}}}</big> ''s\u1ef1'' matter; event\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u59ac}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u00f3'' there; that\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6fdf}}}}</big> ''t\u00e9'' to splash\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u982d}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' head; top (of a multitude)\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u6295}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ea7u'' to throw, to send\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud859\udce1}}}}</big> ''m\u00e0'' but\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u606a}}}}</big> ''kh\u00e1c'' another, different; further\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4e00}}}}</big> ''nh\u1ea5t'' first\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u65e6}}}}</big> ''\u0111\u1ebfn'' arrive, reach\n# <big>{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5bb6}}}}</big> ''nh\u00e0'' home, house; family.\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Standardization===\nIn 1867, the reformist [[Nguy\u1ec5n Tr\u01b0\u1eddng T\u1ed9]] proposed a standardization of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m (along with the abolition of classical Chinese), but the new system, what he called ''qu\u1ed1c \u00e2m H\u00e1n t\u1ef1'' ({{vi-nom|\u570b\u97f3\u6f22\u5b57}} lit. \"Han characters with national pronunciations\"), was rejected by Emperor T\u1ef1 \u0110\u1ee9c.{{sfn|DeFrancis|1977|pp=101-105}} To this date, ch\u1eef N\u00f4m has never been officially standardized. As a result, a Vietnamese word can be represented by variant N\u00f4m characters. For example, the very word ''ch\u1eef'' (\"character\", \"script\"), a Chinese loan word, can be written as either {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5b57}}}} (Chinese character), {{vi-nom|\ud846\udd82}} (invented character, \"compound-semantic\") or {{vi-nom|\ud846\ude38}} (invented character, \"semantic-phonetic\"). For another example, the word ''b\u00e9o'' (\"fat\", \"greasy\") can be written either as {{vi-nom|\u813f}} or {{vi-nom|[[File:Chu nom fat.svg|18px|\u2ff0\u6708\u5831]]}}. Both characters are invented characters with a semantic-phonetic structure, the difference being the phonetic indicator ({{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u8868}}}} vs. {{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5831}}}}).\n\nFrom 2013, Han-Nom Revival Committee of Vietnam, an internet-based organization has started its standardization work for Ch\u1eef [[H\u00e1n N\u00f4m]]. Aiming at both ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and [[Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]] standardization, the Committee's \"Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Standardization Project<ref>[http://www.hannom-rcv.org/wi/index.php?title=%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96%E5%8C%96:%E4%BB%8B%E7%B4%B9 {{vi-nom|\u6a19\u6e96\u5316:\u4ecb\u7d39 \u2013 \u97cb\u90a3\u5a01\u7b95\uff08VI NA UY KI\uff09\u30fb\u59d4\u73ed\u5fa9\u751f\u6f22\u5583\u8d8a\u5357}}]</ref>\" is designed to determine the Standard ch\u1eef N\u00f4m among many variant N\u00f4m characters, to confirm the usage of ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n in [[:vi:T\u1eeb thu\u1ea7n Vi\u1ec7t|Pure Vietnamese words]], [[Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary|Sino-Vietnamese words]] (especially Vietnamese-made Sino-Vietnamese words), and [[:vi:Ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t#T\u1eeb h\u1ed7n ch\u1ee7ng|Hybrid words]], as well as to determine the ch\u1eef N\u00f4m and Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n characters in [[Loan words]] for phonetic transliteration. Till 2015, based on discussions among many specialists of Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m, around 500 frequently-used Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m are determined and published on its website.<ref>[http://www.hannom-rcv.org/wi/index.php?title=%E6%A8%99%E6%BA%96%E5%8C%96:%E9%9F%B3%E7%AF%80%E9%80%9A%E5%B8%B8 {{vi-nom|\u6a19\u6e96\u5316:\u97f3\u7bc0\u901a\u5e38 \u2013 \u97cb\u90a3\u5a01\u7b95\uff08VI NA UY KI\uff09\u30fb\u59d4\u73ed\u5fa9\u751f\u6f22\u5583\u8d8a\u5357}}]</ref>\n\n==Computer encoding==\nIn 1993, the Vietnamese government released an 8-bit coding standard for alphabetic Vietnamese ([[TCVN 5712]]:1993, or VSCII), as well as a 16-bit standard for Nom (TCVN 5773:1993).<ref>Luong Van Phan, \"[http://www.cicc.or.jp/japanese/hyoujyunka/j-af15/15-21.pdf Country Report on Current Status and Issues of e-government Vietnam \u2013 Requirements for Documentation Standards]\". The character list for the 1993 standard is given in [http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~nhan/npct-2.1.pdf N\u00f4m Proper Code Table: Version 2.1] by Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n.</ref> This group of glyphs is referred to as \"V0.\" In 1994, the [[Ideographic Rapporteur Group]] agreed to include Nom characters as part of [[Unicode]].<ref name=unicode>\"[https://www.unicode.org/uni2book/appA.pdf Han Unification History]\", ''The Unicode Standard, Version 5.0'' (2006).</ref> A revised standard, TCVN 6909:2001, defines 9,299 glyphs.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> About half of these glyphs are specific to Vietnam.<ref name=Hong>{{in lang|vi}} Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng, \"[http://nomfoundation.org/vn/du-an-nom/Kho-chu-Han-Nom-ma-hoa/Gioi-thieu-Kho-chu-Han-Nom-ma-hoa Gi\u1edbi thi\u1ec7u Kho ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m m\u00e3 ho\u00e1]\" [H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire Introduction], ''Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation''.</ref> Nom characters not already encoded were added to [[CJK Unified Ideographs Extension B|<abbr title=\"Chinese/Japanese/Korean\">CJK</abbr> Unified Ideographs Extension B]].<ref name=\"Hong\" /> (These characters have five-digit [[hexadecimal]] code points. The characters that were encoded earlier have four-digit hex.)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Code!!Characters!!Unicode block!!Standard!!Date!!V Source!!Sources\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V0||2,246||Basic Block (593), A (138), B (1,515)||TCVN 5773:1993||2001||V0-3021 to V0-4927||5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V1||3,311||Basic Block (3,110), C (1)||TCVN 6056:1995||1999||V1-4A21 to V1-6D35||2, 5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V2||3,205||Basic Block (763), A (151), B (2,291)||VHN 01:1998||2001||V2-6E21 to V2-9171||2, 5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V3||535||Basic Block (91), A (19), B (425)||VHN 02:1998||2001||V3-3021 to V3-3644||Manuscripts\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V4||785 (encoded)||Extension C||Defined as sources 1, 3, and 6||2009||V4-4021 to V4-4B2F||1, 3, 6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V04||1,028||Extension E||Unencoded V4 and V6 characters||Projected||V04-4022 to V04-583E||V4: 1, 3, 6;<br>V6: 4, manuscripts\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|V5||~900||colspan=\"2\"|Proposed in 2001, but already coded||2001||None||2, 5\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\"|<small>'''Sources''': Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng,<ref name=Hong/> \"[https://www.unicode.org/unibook/ Unibook Character Browser]\", Unicode,Inc., \"Code Charts \u2013 CJK Ext. E\" (N4358-A).<ref name=CJK-E>\"[http://std.dkuug.dk/jtc1/sc2/wg2/docs/n4358-A.pdf Code Charts - CJK Ext. E]\", (N4358-A), JTC1/SC2/WG2, Oct. 10, 2012.</ref></small>\n|}\n\nCharacters were extracted from the following sources:\n# Ho\u00e0ng Tri\u1ec1u \u00c2n, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m T\u00e0y'' [Nom of the Tay People], 2003.\n# Institute of Linguistics, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Index], Hanoi, 1976.\n# Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng, editor, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Dictionary], 2006.\n# Father Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m, ''Gi\u00fap \u0111\u1ecdc N\u00f4m v\u00e0 H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t'' [Help with Nom and Sino-Vietnamese], 2004.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh & Nguy\u1ec5n Quang X\u1ef7, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Nom Dictionary], Saigon, 1971.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m mi\u1ec1n Nam'' [Table of Nom in the South], 1994.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''B\u1ea3ng tra ch\u1eef N\u00f4m sau th\u1ebf k\u1ef7 XVII'' [Table of Nom After the 17th Century], 1994.\n# V\u0169 V\u0103n K\u00ednh, ''\u0110\u1ea1i t\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m'' [Great Nom Dictionary], 1999.\n# Nguy\u1ec5n V\u0103n Huy\u00ean, ''G\u00f3p ph\u1ea7n nghi\u00ean c\u1ee9u v\u0103n ho\u00e1 Vi\u1ec7t Nam'' [Contributions to the Study of Vietnamese Culture], 1995.<ref name=Hong/>\n\nThe V2, V3, and V4 proposals were developed by a group at the Han-Nom Research Institute led by Nguy\u1ec5n Quang H\u1ed3ng.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> V4, developed in 2001, includes over 400 ideograms formerly used by the [[Tay people]] of northern Vietnam.<ref name=Hong/> This allows the Tay language to get its own registration code.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> V5 is a set of about 900 characters proposed in 2001.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> As these characters were already part of Unicode, the IRG concluded that they could not be edited and no Vietnamese code was added.<ref name=\"Hong\" /> (This is despite the fact that national codes were added retroactively for version 3.0 in 1999.) The Nom Na Group, led by Ng\u00f4 Thanh Nh\u00e0n, published a set of nearly 20,000 Nom characters in 2005.<ref name=Ng\u00f4>Thanh Nh\u00e0n Ng\u00f4, ''[https://books.google.com/books/about/Manual_the_N%C3%B4m_Na_Coded_Character_Set.html?id=YyIOHAAACAAJ Manual, the N\u00f4m Na Coded Character Set]'', N\u00f4m Na Group, Hanoi, 2005. The set contains 19,981 characters.</ref> This set includes both the characters proposed earlier and a large group of additional characters referred to as \"V6\".<ref name=\"Hong\" /> These are mainly Han characters from Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m's dictionary which were already assigned code points. Character readings were determined manually by H\u1ed3ng's group, while Nh\u00e0n's group developed software for this purpose.<ref name=VNPF>Institute of H\u00e1n-N\u00f4m Studies and Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation, ''[http://nomfoundation.org/nom-tools/Nom-Books/54-Han_Nom_Coded_Character_Repertoire Kho Ch\u1eef H\u00e1n N\u00f4m M\u00e3 Ho\u00e1]'' [H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire] (2008).</ref> The work of the two groups was integrated and published in 2008 as the ''H\u00e1n N\u00f4m Coded Character Repertoire''.<ref name=\"VNPF\" />\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Character!!Composition!!Nom reading!!Han Viet!!English!!Code point!!V Source!!Other sources\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5427}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u53e3|\u5df4}}}}||ba||ba||[emphatic final particle]||U+5427||V0-3122||G0,J,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u50b7}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u4ebb}}}}\u2ff1{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\udc89|\u661c}}}}||th\u01b0\u01a1ng||th\u01b0\u01a1ng||to love||U+50B7||V1-4C22||G1,J,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud840\ude9b}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u3775|\u4eba}}}}||ng\u01b0\u1eddi||ng\u1ea1i ({{vi-nom|\u788d}})||people||U+2029B||V2-6E4F||None\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u391d}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u5fc4|\u5145}}}}||su\u00f4ng||song||to become interested in||U+391D||V3-313D||G3,KP,K,T\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud86c\uded9}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u866b|\u5f37}}}}||c\u00e0ng||c\u01b0\u1eddng ({{vi-nom|\u5f37}})||claw, pincer||U+2B2D9||V4-536F||None\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"font-size:140%;\">{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\ud86e\udc6f}}}}</span>||\u2ff0{{vi-nom|{{linktext|\u671d|\u4e59}}}}||gi\u00e0u||tr\u00e0o ({{vi-nom|\u671d}})||wealth||U+2B86F||V4-405E||None\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\"|<small>'''Key:''' G0 = China ([[GB 2312]]);  G1 = China (GB 12345); G3 = China (GB 7589); GHZ = ''[[Hanyu Da Zidian]]''; J = Japan; KP= North Korea; K = South Korea; T = Taiwan.<br/>'''Sources''': [https://www.unicode.org/cgi-bin/GetUnihanData.pl? Unihan Database], [http://nomfoundation.org/ Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation], \"Code Charts \u2013 CJK Ext. E\" (N4358-A).<ref name=CJK-E/> The Han-Viet readings are from ''[http://www.hanviet.org/ H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t T\u1eeb \u0110i\u1ec3n]''.</small>\n|}</center>\n\nThe characters that do not exist in Chinese have Han-Viet readings that are based on the characters given in parenthesis. The common character for ''c\u00e0ng'' ({{vi-nom|\u5f37}}) contains the radical {{vi-nom|\u866b}} (insects).<ref name=kiem>{{in lang|vi}} Tr\u1ea7n V\u0103n Ki\u1ec7m, ''[http://nomfoundation.org/nom-tools/Nom-Dictionary Gi\u00fap \u0111\u1ecdc N\u00f4m v\u00e0 H\u00e1n Vi\u1ec7t]'' [Help with Nom and Sino-Vietnamese], 2004, \"Entry c\u00e0ng\", p. 290.</ref> This radical is added redundantly to create {{vi-nom|\ud86c\uded9}}, a rare variation shown in the chart above. The character {{vi-nom|\ud86e\udc6f}} (''gi\u00e0u'') is specific to the Tay people.<ref name=\"An\">Ho\u00e0ng Tri\u1ec1u \u00c2n, ''T\u1ef1 \u0111i\u1ec3n ch\u1eef N\u00f4m T\u00e0y'' [Nom of the Tay People], 2003, p. 178.</ref> It has been part of the Unicode standard only since version 8.0 of June 2015, so there is still very little font and [[input method]] support for it. It is a variation of {{vi-nom|\u671d}}, the corresponding character in Vietnamese.<ref name=NomFoundation>[http://nomfoundation.org/common/nom_details.php?codepoint=63830&img=1 Detailed information: V+63830\"], Vietnamese N\u00f4m Preservation Foundation.<br/>\"[http://nomfoundation.org/common/show_radical.php?radical=0005&img=1 List of Unicode Radicals]\", VNPF.<br/>Ki\u1ec7m, 2004, p. 424, \"Entry gi\u00e0u.\"<br/>[http://vdict.com/gi%C3%A0u,2,0,0.html Entry gi\u00e0u]\", VDict.com.</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Vietnam|Languages}}\n* [[Chinese family of scripts]]\n**[[Hanja]] in Korean\n**[[Kanji]] in Japanese\n* [[Sinoxenic]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n* {{citation\n  | first = John | last = DeFrancis | authorlink = John DeFrancis\n  | title = Colonialism and language policy in Viet Nam\n  | publisher = Mouton | year = 1977 | isbn = 978-90-279-7643-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Asia's Orthographic Dilemma | first = Wm. C. | last = Hannas\n  | publisher = University of Hawaii Press | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-0-8248-1892-0\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Vietnamese Tradition on Trial, 1920-1945 | first = David G. | last = Marr\n  | publisher = University of California Press | year = 1984 | isbn = 978-0-520-90744-7\n  | postscript = .\n  }}\n* {{citation\n  | title = Lexicon of reconstructed pronunciation in early Middle Chinese, late Middle Chinese, and early Mandarin\n  | first